const groups = [
  { id: "pwn", kicker: "Build the primitive", title: "Exploit Development & Pwn", items: [
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Abusing the User-Mode Debugger", "https://projectzero.google/2019/04/windows-exploitation-tricks-abusing.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2019", 5, "Windows user mode debugger handle access upgrade kernel exploitation primitive", "Shows that attaching through the native debugger path with only process suspend/resume rights can yield full-access process and thread handles in debug events, then develops a second primitive for reclaiming dangling kernel handles. It is a model exploitation-tricks article because it turns subtle access-mode mismatches into reusable building blocks without mislabeling them as standalone vulnerabilities."],
    ["Trapping Virtual Memory Access on Windows 11 24H2", "https://projectzero.google/2025/01/windows-exploitation-tricks-trapping.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2025", 5, "Windows 11 24H2 TOCTOU virtual memory trap SMB custom port", "Updates the virtual-memory trapping technique for Windows 11 24H2 by using the SMB client's configurable destination port to host a delaying server locally. The change removes the earlier remote-host dependency and creates a practical primitive for widening TOCTOU races and testing false-file-immutability assumptions on current systems."],
    ["NetMan DLL Hijacking: Administrator to SYSTEM", "https://itm4n.github.io/windows-server-netman-dll-hijacking/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "Network Connections NetMan service DLL hijacking SYSTEM Windows Server", "Investigates the Network Connections service on Windows Server and turns its privileged DLL-loading behavior into an Administrator-to-SYSTEM escalation. The writeup is particularly useful for its careful treatment of service activation, module resolution, writable locations, and the operational conditions required to make a DLL-hijacking observation exploitable."],
    ["Windows DLL Hijacking Clarified", "https://itm4n.github.io/windows-dll-hijacking-clarified/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "Windows DLL hijacking search order phantom DLL proxying methodology", "Separates several techniques that are often collapsed under the DLL-hijacking label, including search-order abuse, phantom DLLs, replacement, and proxying. It supplies a precise vocabulary and a repeatable validation workflow, helping researchers distinguish a Process Monitor lead from a privilege boundary that can actually be crossed."],
    ["Chimichurri Reloaded", "https://itm4n.github.io/chimichurri-reloaded/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "Chimichurri Task Scheduler token impersonation Windows privilege escalation", "Revisits the classic Chimichurri technique on modern Windows and reconstructs the underlying Task Scheduler and token behavior instead of merely updating an old exploit. The analysis shows which assumptions survived, which platform changes broke the original chain, and how a historical service-abuse primitive can be methodically re-evaluated."],
    ["Windows Privilege Escalation with DLL Proxying", "https://itm4n.github.io/dll-proxying/", "itm4n", "2019", 5, "DLL proxying hijacking exports Windows privilege escalation", "Explains how to preserve a legitimate DLL's exported behavior while interposing malicious initialization code, including export forwarding, dependency analysis, proxy construction, and deployment constraints. The technique is developed as a reliable Windows privilege-escalation building block rather than confused with ordinary missing-DLL search-order hijacking."],
    ["Weaponizing Privileged File Writes with USO, Part 1", "https://itm4n.github.io/usodllloader-part1/", "itm4n", "2019", 5, "Update Session Orchestrator USO privileged file write DLL LPE", "Investigates the Update Session Orchestrator as a way to convert a privileged arbitrary file write into code execution, mapping the service, filesystem targets, and DLL-loading opportunity. The post carefully develops prerequisites and constraints before the follow-up turns the primitive into a working loader."],
    ["Weaponizing Privileged File Writes with USO, Part 2", "https://itm4n.github.io/usodllloader-part2/", "itm4n", "2019", 5, "UsoDllLoader Windows Update service DLL hijack SYSTEM exploit", "Completes the USO research with the practical exploit chain and UsoDllLoader implementation, showing how to place the payload, trigger the privileged service, and obtain SYSTEM while respecting update-service behavior. Reading both parts provides a reusable method for evaluating other privileged file-write bugs."],
    ["Recovering LOCAL SERVICE Privileges", "https://itm4n.github.io/localservice-privileges/", "itm4n", "2019", 5, "LOCAL SERVICE token privileges SeImpersonate Windows service LPE", "Examines why expected token privileges may be absent from a LOCAL SERVICE process and how Windows service configuration and token construction affect them. The investigation matters for exploit chains that depend on impersonation privileges and demonstrates how to verify the effective token instead of trusting the account name."],
    ["CDPSvc DLL Hijacking: LOCAL SERVICE to SYSTEM", "https://itm4n.github.io/cdpsvc-dll-hijacking/", "itm4n", "2019", 5, "CDPSvc DLL hijacking LOCAL SERVICE SYSTEM privilege escalation", "Builds a service-to-SYSTEM escalation through Connected Devices Platform Service DLL loading, combining service context, writable locations, module resolution, and trigger behavior. The article records the complete chain and the boundary crossed, making it more instructive than a generic DLL-hijacking checklist."],
    ["PrintSpoofer", "https://itm4n.github.io/printspoofer-abusing-impersonate-privileges/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "PrintSpoofer SeImpersonate named pipe spooler token SYSTEM", "Develops the PrintSpoofer technique from named-pipe impersonation and Print Spooler coercion through token duplication and SYSTEM process creation on modern Windows 10 and Server. It explains why older Potato approaches fail in some environments and provides implementation-level detail for the replacement primitive."],
    ["Windows .NET Core SDK Elevation of Privilege", "https://itm4n.github.io/dotnet-sdk-eop/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, ".NET Core SDK Windows service writable path DLL hijack EoP", "Analyzes a local elevation path introduced by the Windows .NET Core SDK installation and develops it from filesystem and service behavior to privileged code execution. The writeup is useful for learning how developer tooling changes system attack surface and how to validate an apparent writable-path finding operationally."],
    ["An Unconventional RpcEptMapper Exploit", "https://itm4n.github.io/windows-registry-rpceptmapper-exploit/", "itm4n", "2021", 5, "RpcEptMapper registry service DLL load Windows SYSTEM exploit", "Turns insecure RpcEptMapper registry permissions into execution using an unconventional service and registry path after obvious approaches prove unreliable. The article documents failed ideas, service hosting constraints, and the final trigger, offering a strong example of refining a configuration primitive into a dependable exploit."],
    ["MareBackup Scheduled Task Privilege Escalation", "https://itm4n.github.io/hijacking-the-windows-marebackup-scheduled-task-for-privilege-escalation/", "itm4n", "2025", 5, "MareBackup scheduled task DLL hijack SYSTEM Windows LPE", "Reverse engineers the built-in MareBackup scheduled task and its execution environment to identify a hijack path that elevates a local user. The analysis covers task definition, trigger conditions, privileged process behavior, load resolution, and practical exploitation, making it a current service-and-task escalation case study."],
    ["Arbitrary Object Directory Creation to LPE", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/08/windows-exploitation-tricks-exploiting.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "object manager directory creation CSRSS AppContainer LPE Windows", "Turns an arbitrary object-manager directory creation bug into local privilege escalation by combining CSRSS behavior, namespace shadowing, symbolic links, and AppContainer-specific directories. The article is exemplary non-memory-corruption exploitation: each object and access check is developed explicitly until a constrained namespace primitive crosses a privilege boundary."],
    ["Symbolic Hooks Part 2: Getting the Target Name", "https://windows-internals.com/symhooks-part-two/", "Alex Ionescu", "2020", 5, "object manager symbolic link hook target name Windows exploitation", "Continues the Symbolic Hooks research by recovering the target of object-manager symbolic links and working through the internal name-resolution machinery required for a reliable hook. The series is valuable exploit-development material because it builds a primitive from namespace semantics and kernel objects rather than relying on code patching."],
    ["Symbolic Hooks Part 3: The Remainder Theorem", "https://windows-internals.com/symhooks-part-three/", "Alex Ionescu", "2020", 5, "symbolic hooks object manager parse procedure kernel redirection", "Develops the symbolic-link interception mechanism further by addressing unresolved parsing and redirection cases inside the object manager. It documents the constraints that emerge when a proof of concept meets real namespace behavior, making this installment essential for understanding the technique as a robust primitive rather than a novelty."],
    ["Symbolic Hooks Part 4: The App Container Traverse-ty", "https://windows-internals.com/symhooks-part-four/", "Alex Ionescu", "2020", 5, "symbolic hooks AppContainer object manager path traversal sandbox", "Applies the symbolic-hook model to AppContainer namespace traversal and shows how sandbox-specific path handling changes the reachable objects and redirection behavior. The article connects a low-level object-manager technique to an actual security boundary, while carefully examining the access checks and namespace layout that determine exploitability."],
    ["Exploiting a Simple Vulnerability in 35 Steps", "https://windows-internals.com/exploiting-a-simple-vulnerability-in-35-easy-steps-or-less/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "Windows kernel exploitation arbitrary increment token privileges PreviousMode", "Begins with an intentionally modest kernel corruption primitive and develops it through the many constraints that real exploitation imposes, including address discovery, object selection, and privilege manipulation. The article is valuable precisely because it refuses to collapse the chain into token stealing and instead records the engineering decisions between trigger and reliable elevation."],
    ["Exploiting a Simple Vulnerability, Part 1.5: The Info Leak", "https://windows-internals.com/exploiting-a-simple-vulnerability-part-1-5-the-info-leak/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "Windows kernel exploitation information leak KASLR object addresses", "Extends the simple-vulnerability series by constructing the information disclosure needed to make the later exploit deterministic. It separates the leak from the corruption primitive and demonstrates why modern kernel exploitation should account explicitly for object addresses and KASLR instead of assuming a convenient legacy disclosure API."],
    ["Exploiting a Simple Vulnerability, Part 2", "https://windows-internals.com/exploiting-a-simple-vulnerability-part-2-what-if-we-made-exploitation-harder/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "Windows kernel exploitation mitigation bypass constrained primitive", "Revisits the same laboratory after deliberately removing convenient assumptions and adding exploitation constraints. Comparing the revised chain with the earlier solution shows how a primitive must be redesigned around mitigations, build behavior, and side effects, making the series useful practice for adapting rather than memorizing a single exploit."],
    ["One I/O Ring to Rule Them All", "https://windows-internals.com/one-i-o-ring-to-rule-them-all-a-full-read-write-exploit-primitive-on-windows-11/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "Windows 11 I/O rings kernel arbitrary read write primitive", "Shows how corruption of I/O ring bookkeeping can transform a limited kernel write into a full kernel read/write primitive using legitimate asynchronous I/O machinery. The post documents the relevant user and kernel objects, registered-buffer path, and operational sequence in enough detail to understand both the exploit technique and its patch surface."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Arbitrary File Writes", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/04/windows-exploitation-tricks-exploiting.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "Windows LPE arbitrary file write oplock mount point hard link", "A foundational treatment of turning a constrained file-write vulnerability into local privilege escalation on modern Windows after earlier mount-point techniques were hardened. It carefully develops the object-manager and filesystem primitives, the race window, and the security boundary being crossed, so it remains a model for reasoning about non-memory-corruption exploits."],
    ["Windows Drivers Reverse Engineering Methodology", "https://voidsec.com/windows-drivers-reverse-engineering-methodology/", "VoidSec", "2022", 5, "WDM driver reversing IOCTL MSR MmMapIoSpace methodology", "A repeatable end-to-end methodology for lab setup, driver entry-point recovery, dispatch and IOCTL mapping, dangerous primitive discovery, and exploitability analysis. It includes a deliberately constrained target and exercises that force the reader to validate data flow rather than pattern-match vulnerable APIs."],
    ["Exploiting the System Mechanic driver", "https://voidsec.com/exploiting-system-mechanic-driver/", "VoidSec", "2021", 5, "driver reversing fuzzing token privileges LPE CTF", "Turns an initially unknown commercial driver into a complete exploitation exercise: interface recovery, fuzzing, root-cause analysis, primitive constraints, and SYSTEM escalation. It is especially valuable as a CTF-style Windows pwn writeup against a realistic third-party target."],
    ["CVE-2026-40369: Twelve Bytes to Escape the Browser Sandbox", "https://voidsec.com/cve-2026-40369-browser-sandbox-escape/", "VoidSec", "2026", 5, "Windows kernel arbitrary write sandbox escape NtCreateToken KASLR", "Develops a twelve-byte kernel write reachable from a browser renderer into SYSTEM without relying on classical token stealing. The chain disables the kernel-address-leak gate, locates the token, acquires token-creation privileges, and forges a SYSTEM primary token with unusually clear primitive accounting."],
    ["Crucial MOD Utility LPE (CVE-2021-41285)", "https://voidsec.com/crucial-mod-utility-lpe-cve-2021-41285/", "VoidSec", "2021", 5, "WinRing0 physical memory mapping driver LPE CVE-2021-41285", "Shows how a vendor utility inherited WinRing0's dangerous MSR and physical-memory functionality verbatim. The article combines binary comparison, IOCTL recovery, physical mapping, page-table reasoning, and a published exploit, making it a model driver-reuse case study."],
    ["Swimming in the (Kernel) Pool, Part 1", "https://connormcgarr.github.io/swimming-in-the-kernel-pool-part-1/", "Connor McGarr", "2021", 5, "HEVD pool exploitation, kLFH behavior, and low-integrity pool attacks", "Builds a Windows kernel pool exploit from allocator behavior upward, including an out-of-bounds read used for KASLR defeat. The careful treatment of kLFH makes it a strong foundation for understanding why heap shaping works rather than merely copying a spray."],
    ["ROP Gadget Hunting on Windows", "https://core-jmp.org/2026/06/rop-scanner-windows-rop-gadget-hunting-exploit-chain/", "core-jmp", "2026", 5, "ROP JOP gadgets CFG DEP VirtualProtect stack pivot", "Walks from instruction-pointer control to a bad-byte-clean VirtualProtect chain using ROP, JOP, syscall, and stack-pivot gadgets. It also considers CFG-aware gadget selection, making the article useful for designing a repeatable modern gadget-hunting workflow."],
    ["Exploiting the NT Kernel in 24H2", "https://exploits.forsale/24h2-nt-exploit/", "exploits.forsale", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 24H2 double fetch KASLR prefetch", "Covers bug discovery and exploit development against Windows 11 24H2, including double-fetch flaws introduced by user-memory handling changes. Its KASLR section connects prefetch timing with the reliability differences seen across Intel, AMD, native, and virtualized targets."],
    ["Physical-memory KASLR bypass on Windows 11 24H2", "https://xacone.github.io/kaslr_leak_24h2.html", "xacone", "2024", 5, "physical memory CR3 page tables HVCI KASLR", "Turns driver-assisted physical-memory access into a kernel-base disclosure after legacy pointer leaks were restricted. The post is an excellent practical reference for CR3 discovery, page-table traversal, and physical-to-virtual translation under HVCI."],
    ["From arbitrary pointer dereference to kernel R/W", "https://hnsecurity.it/blog/from-arbitrary-pointer-dereference-to-arbitrary-read-write-in-latest-windows-11/", "Hacking Notes", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 arbitrary pointer dereference SMEP kernel read write", "Develops a constrained arbitrary-pointer dereference into an arbitrary kernel read/write capability on a current Windows 11 target. The value lies in the intermediate reasoning: primitive refinement, SMEP constraints, and the choices needed to reach reliable privilege escalation."],
    ["Non-Paged Pool Overflow Exploitation", "https://github.com/vp777/Windows-Non-Paged-Pool-Overflow-Exploitation", "vp777", "2021", 4, "CVE-2020-17087 pool overflow off by one named pipe", "A hands-on collection for exploiting named-pipe non-paged-pool corruption, including CVE-2020-17087 and an off-by-one variant. It is useful for comparing allocator manipulation and exploitation techniques across older and newer Windows releases."],
    ["Shadow SSDT hijacking via R/W primitives", "https://www.exploitpack.com/blogs/news/shadow-ssdt-hijacking-to-achieve-kernel-code-execution-via-rw-primitives", "Exploit Pack", "2026", 4, "Shadow SSDT VBS HVCI kCET kernel execution", "Explores converting kernel read/write into code execution by targeting the Shadow SSDT while VBS, HVCI, and kernel CET are active. Treat it as a specialized chain-design study and validate assumptions against the exact Windows build you target."],
    ["HEVD SMEP bypass", "https://fluidattacks.com/blog/hevd-smep-bypass", "Fluid Attacks", "2020", 4, "HEVD SMEP bypass ROP kernel exploitation", "Introduces SMEP's effect on classic kernel shellcode execution and adapts an HEVD exploit to bypass it. The tutorial is especially useful as a bridge from older token-stealing exercises to ROP-based kernel exploitation."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Trapping Virtual Memory Access", "https://projectzero.google/2021/01/windows-exploitation-tricks-trapping.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "Windows kernel TOCTOU double fetch memory trap SMB Cloud Filter", "Develops a reusable way to stall a kernel read or write of attacker-controlled virtual memory, giving exploit code both a timing signal and an arbitrarily widened race window. The research compares remote SMB-backed mappings with Cloud Filter placeholders, works through ProbeForWrite behavior, and states which double-fetch and false-immutability patterns can consume the primitive."],
    ["Exploiting Arbitrary File Writes for Local Elevation", "https://projectzero.google/2018/04/windows-exploitation-tricks-exploiting.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "Windows arbitrary file write LPE oplock mount point LPAC exploit primitive", "Turns a constrained privileged file-write vulnerability into local elevation on Windows 10 by combining filesystem redirection, opportunistic locks, object-manager links, and a privileged execution sink. The article is especially valuable because it explains the post-RS4 constraints and demonstrates that the chain can begin inside an Edge Low Privilege AppContainer."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Techniques: Winning Path-Lookup Races", "https://projectzero.google/2025/12/windows-exploitation-techniques.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2025", 5, "Windows path lookup race condition oplock object manager TOCTOU", "Revisits a practical technique for winning extremely narrow named-resource lookup races and retests the original PoC||GTFO method on modern Windows 11. It breaks the check-use sequence into observable filesystem and namespace operations, explains how to hold intermediate lookups, and distinguishes deterministic synchronization from blind retry loops."],
    ["Trying to Exploit a Windows Kernel Arbitrary Read", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2022/06-trying-to-exploit-a-windows-kernel-arbitrary-read-vulnerability/", "Phan Thanh Duy / STAR Labs", "2022", 5, "Windows kernel arbitrary read registry process SAM bounce buffer race", "Explores the real limitations of a kernel arbitrary-read bug instead of assuming it immediately yields SYSTEM. After prototype-PTE and Registry-process address-space dead ends, the article derives a race against CmpBounceBufferLookaside while LSASS reads SAM data, providing a rare study of converting a narrow read into sensitive cross-context disclosure."],
  ]},
  { id: "ctf", kicker: "Practice the full chain", title: "Windows CTF Pwn", items: [
    ["Cache Cache — Insomni'hack 2024", "https://itm4n.github.io/insomnihack-2024-cache-cache/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "Windows CTF cache service RPC authentication privilege escalation", "A full solution to a Windows-native Insomni'hack challenge that begins with an unfamiliar privileged service and works through its exposed interface, state model, and security assumptions to a reliable exploit. The post preserves the investigative branches and verification steps, making it useful practice in service-oriented Windows pwn rather than only a flag-recovery recipe."],
    ["Easier — DEF CON CTF Quals 2016", "https://github.com/legitbs/quals-2016/tree/master/easier", "LegitBS", "2016", 5, "Windows CTF pwn DEF CON source binary exploitation", "An official DEF CON Quals challenge repository preserving the target source and deployment material for a Windows pwnable. The artifact supports a full audit of the intended vulnerability and lets researchers compare independent solutions against the organizer's exact build rather than a reconstructed binary."],
    ["Divided — DEF CON CTF Quals 2017", "https://github.com/securifera/Defcon-Quals-2017-Divided", "Securifera", "2017", 5, "Windows CTF DEP CFG ROP process exploitation writeup", "A dedicated solution repository for DEF CON's Windows challenge with exploit code and an accompanying technical narrative. It is strong practice for analyzing an unfamiliar PE service, recovering its corruption primitive, and working through platform mitigations to a stable payload."],
    ["VBS — 0CTF 2015", "https://github.com/ctfs/write-ups-2015/tree/master/0ctf-2015/exploit/vbs", "0CTF community archive", "2015", 4, "Windows VBScript engine CTF exploitation challenge writeup", "A preserved challenge package and solution material targeting Windows scripting behavior rather than a conventional ELF service. It offers historical but still useful practice in recovering a language runtime's object and memory model before converting a script-level bug into native control."],
    ["Drunk — BCTF 2015", "https://github.com/pwning/public-writeup/tree/master/bctf2015/pwn300-drunk", "PPP", "2015", 5, "Windows CTF usermode exploit public writeup code", "A public solution from a top CTF team for a Windows pwnable, retaining both the reasoning and exploit artifacts. The repository is useful for studying how experienced solvers identify Windows-specific attack surface, obtain the necessary disclosures, and assemble a reliable chain under competition constraints."],
    ["Thing2 — DEF CON CTF Quals 2015", "https://github.com/ctfs/write-ups-2015/tree/master/defcon-qualifier-ctf-2015/pwnable/thing2", "DEF CON CTF community archive", "2015", 4, "Windows CTF pwn Thing2 source exploit writeup", "A mirrored set of original materials and writeups for an uncommon Windows challenge from DEF CON Quals. Its age makes it best treated as historical exploitation practice, but the retained binary and solution still support reproducible work with PE layout, Windows APIs, and native memory corruption."],
    ["Memory — CONFidence CTF 2014", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/CONFidence%20CTF%202014/Main%20event/Memory", "j00ru", "2014", 5, "Windows CTF memory corruption challenge source j00ru", "An official Windows challenge authored and archived by j00ru with sufficient material to reconstruct both design and intended vulnerability. It is a useful historical benchmark for the Windows exploitation techniques emphasized in high-level CTFs before modern pool and control-flow mitigations changed common chains."],
    ["Entree — CONFidence CTF 2016", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/CONFidence%20CTF%202016/Main%20event/Entree", "j00ru", "2016", 5, "Windows CTF exploitation challenge PE source binary", "A Windows-native exploitation task preserved by its author with challenge files and documentation. The clean provenance and complete artifacts make it suitable for methodical reverse engineering, debugging, and exploit reproduction instead of relying on a potentially modified mirror."],
    ["Bubblegum — CONFidence CTF 2016 Teaser", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/CONFidence%20CTF%202016/Teaser/Bubblegum", "j00ru", "2016", 5, "Windows CTF Bubblegum binary exploitation source", "A compact Windows pwnable from the CONFidence teaser series, released by the challenge author. It provides a controlled environment for practicing PE triage, input-path recovery, and native exploit development with authoritative artifacts and known challenge intent."],
    ["Fastcalc — CONFidence CTF 2017 Teaser", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/CONFidence%20CTF%202017/Teaser/Fastcalc", "j00ru", "2017", 5, "Windows CTF calculator floating point exploitation challenge", "An organizer-authored Windows challenge centered on a calculator-style target and distributed with the original files. Its unusual data processing rewards careful semantic analysis before memory-corruption work, and the hardened companion makes it possible to compare the primitive as mitigations change."],
    ["Fastcalc Hardened — CONFidence CTF 2017", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/CONFidence%20CTF%202017/Main%20event/Fastcalc-hardened", "j00ru", "2017", 5, "Windows CTF hardened Fastcalc mitigation bypass exploit", "The main-event evolution of Fastcalc deliberately strengthens the original target, creating a useful before-and-after exploitation exercise. Researchers can compare what the teaser solution depended on, identify which assumptions were removed, and redesign the chain against the hardened Windows binary."],
    ["Globetrotter — CSAW CTF 2018 Finals", "https://github.com/osirislab/CSAW-CTF-2018-Finals/tree/master/pwn/globetrotter", "OSIRIS Lab", "2018", 5, "Windows CTF Globetrotter pwn source notes exploit", "An official CSAW Finals repository containing the Windows challenge and author notes. The retained design material makes this more than a binary archive: it allows readers to trace the intended attack surface, constraints, and exploitation decisions directly from the organizer's implementation."],
    ["Greenhornd — CSAW CTF 2014", "https://github.com/trailofbits/ctf-challenges/tree/master/csaw-2014/greenhornd", "Trail of Bits", "2014", 4, "Windows CTF beginner PE buffer overflow exploit source", "A deliberately approachable Windows exploitation challenge preserved by its authors with source and supporting files. It is a good bridge from basic stack corruption to PE tooling and Windows calling conventions, with enough provenance to reproduce the original exercise reliably."],
    ["PE Analysis — Pwn2Win CTF 2021", "https://github.com/epicleet/write-ups/tree/master/2021/Pwn2Win/pwn-pe_analysis/solution", "Epic Leet Team", "2021", 5, "Windows PE analysis CTF exploitation solution source", "A complete solution directory for a Windows PE-focused pwnable with the code needed to reproduce the solve. It combines file-format reasoning and native exploitation, making it useful to analysts who want practice translating static PE observations into an operational attack rather than stopping at reverse engineering."],
    ["PwnME — INTENT CTF 2022", "https://github.com/nobodyisnobody/write-ups/tree/main/INTENT.CTF.2022/pwn/PwnME", "nobodyisnobody", "2022", 4, "Windows CTF PwnME PE exploitation writeup exploit", "A code-backed writeup for a Windows pwn challenge that records the target analysis and final exploit in a reproducible repository. Its value lies in the complete solver path and explicit Windows environment assumptions, which allow readers to validate each stage locally."],
    ["StrikeBack — Insomni'hack 2018", "https://github.com/Insomnihack/Insomnihack-2018/tree/master/StrikeBack", "Insomni'hack", "2018", 5, "Windows VBA CTF exploitation Office macro challenge source", "An official challenge archive for a Windows and VBA-oriented exploitation task, retaining the files necessary to examine its Office execution and memory model. It broadens the CTF table beyond conventional native services while still demanding low-level reasoning and a concrete exploit path."],
    ["Fullchain LPE — CODEGATE 2025 Finals", "https://github.com/enki-kr/codegate2025-final-fullchain/tree/main/Fullchain-LPE/prob", "ENKI", "2025", 5, "Windows fullchain CTF browser sandbox kernel LPE source", "A purpose-built Windows full-chain challenge distributed with its target components and environment rather than only a remote endpoint. The preserved source makes it possible to study how the stages and security boundaries were designed, reproduce the intended escalation path, and compare a solution against the exact vulnerable implementation."],
    ["BabyKernel — Dragon CTF 2019", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/Dragon%20CTF%202019/Main%20event/BabyKernel", "j00ru", "2019", 5, "Windows kernel CTF driver pool memory corruption source exploit", "A Windows kernel pwnable authored by a specialist in Windows vulnerability research and preserved with challenge materials and documentation. It offers a compact but realistic driver interface for practicing reverse engineering, kernel debugging, memory-corruption triage, and exploit construction against a known build."],
    ["Winsanity — CODEGATE 2020 Finals", "https://github.com/leesh3288/CTF/tree/master/2020/CODEGATE_2020_Finals/winsanity", "leesh3288", "2020", 5, "Windows usermode CTF heap exploitation source exploit writeup", "A difficult Windows user-mode pwn challenge preserved with exploit and writeup material from CODEGATE Finals. The artifact is particularly useful for reconstructing the allocator state and mitigation assumptions from code, then comparing that reasoning with a complete solver instead of relying on a short event recap."],
    ["Winterpreter — CODEGATE 2020 Quals", "https://github.com/leesh3288/CTF/tree/master/2020/CODEGATE_2020_Preliminary/winterpreter", "leesh3288", "2020", 5, "Windows CTF interpreter VM exploitation arbitrary code execution", "A Windows pwnable built around a custom interpreter, with the target and exploit writeup retained together. It exercises the transition from recovering bytecode and object semantics to identifying a memory-safety primitive and escaping the virtualized execution model under Windows-specific calling and memory constraints."],
    ["LowFunHeap — Hack.lu CTF 2020", "https://github.com/leesh3288/CTF/tree/master/2020/Hacklu_2020/LowFunHeap", "leesh3288", "2020", 5, "Windows Low Fragmentation Heap CTF LFH exploitation", "A rare Windows heap challenge centered on Low Fragmentation Heap behavior, accompanied by exploit material from an experienced Windows CTF solver. It is valuable for practicing subsegment and bucket reasoning, heap shaping, and corruption under an allocator whose behavior differs substantially from the glibc heap assumed by most pwn curricula."],
    ["Breath of Shadow — HITCON CTF 2019", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/CTF/blob/master/2019-writeup/hitcon/breathofshadow.c", "AngelBoy", "2019", 5, "Windows kernel CTF driver stack pivot kernel shellcode exploit", "A complete exploit artifact for a Windows kernel challenge whose constrained execution environment forces careful use of kernel APIs and control-flow state. Reading the source alongside the challenge writeups exposes the practical decisions around stack integrity, payload execution, and returning a stable system after ring-0 code runs."],
    ["dadadb — HITCON CTF 2019", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/CTF/blob/master/2019-writeup/hitcon/dadadb.py", "AngelBoy", "2019", 5, "Windows CTF usermode heap database exploit Python", "A solver artifact for HITCON's Windows database pwnable from a researcher known for advanced Windows heap challenges. The exploit provides a concrete route through protocol interaction, memory disclosure, heap manipulation, and final control flow, making it suitable for line-by-line reconstruction in a debugger."],
    ["LazyFragmentationHeap", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/LazyFragmentationHeap", "AngelBoy", "2020", 5, "Windows LFH heap exploitation training challenge slides", "A dedicated Windows heap exploitation challenge and research package with slides explaining the relevant allocator behavior. It bridges theory and practice by pairing the target with material on LFH internals and the grooming strategy needed to make a corruption primitive reliable."],
    ["BFS Windows Exploitation Challenge 2022", "https://voidsec.com/windows-exploitation-challenge-blue-frost-security-2022/", "VoidSec", "2022", 5, "Windows CTF integer overflow stack overflow IRETD GDT shellcode", "An end-to-end solution to Blue Frost Security's Windows challenge, moving from protocol recovery through a signedness bug and stack corruption to mitigation-aware code execution. The unusual IRETD and GDT work, bad-byte constraints, commented exploit, database, and target binary make it a particularly reproducible user-mode case study."],
    ["BFS Ekoparty Exploitation Challenge 2019", "https://connormcgarr.github.io/eko2019-exe/", "Connor McGarr", "2019", 5, "Windows 10 x64 CTF ASLR DEP ROP information leak", "A detailed Windows 10 x64 solution to a network service challenge requiring full ASLR and DEP bypass. It develops the vulnerability, leak, module recovery, stack pivot, and ROP chain in a debugger, providing the intermediate reasoning normally omitted from final exploit scripts."],
    ["GTF — WCTF 2019", "https://github.com/icchy/wctf2019-gtf", "icchy", "2019", 5, "Windows CTF kernel GDI exploitation challenge slides", "A preserved Windows exploitation challenge repository with accompanying slides from WCTF 2019. The combination of target artifacts, presentation, and implementation details supports independent reconstruction of the Windows-specific primitive and provides stronger evidence than an isolated solve script."],
    ["PigDriver — WCTF Kernel Driver Challenge", "https://github.com/FlappyPig/WCTF-pigdriver/blob/master/Windows%2BKernel%2BDriver%2BChallenge-r3kapig.pdf", "r3kapig", "2018", 4, "Windows kernel driver CTF PDF reverse engineering exploit", "A substantial writeup for a Windows kernel driver challenge that walks through interface recovery, bug analysis, and exploit construction. Although delivered as a PDF, it preserves the technical narrative and code needed to understand the intended ring-0 path rather than merely recording the flag or final payload."],
    ["DoroboH — SECCON CTF 2022", "https://github.com/0xcpu/ctf/blob/main/writeups/seccon_2022/DoroboH.md", "0xcpu", "2022", 5, "Windows CTF reversing heap exploitation DoroboH writeup", "A source-backed writeup for a difficult Windows challenge from SECCON, documenting the recovered program model and the exploitation path with supporting code. It is useful for studying how Windows runtime and allocator details surface in a competition target when conventional Linux tooling and assumptions do not apply."],
    ["SSTIC 2021 Stage 2", "https://github.com/nneonneo/sstic-2021/tree/main/files/stage2", "nneonneo", "2021", 5, "Windows SSTIC challenge reverse engineering emulator exploit artifacts", "The second-stage artifact set from Robert Xiao's complete SSTIC 2021 solution, preserving files and tooling for a highly layered systems challenge. It rewards careful reconstruction of undocumented formats and Windows behavior, and the repository allows the analysis to be repeated instead of consumed only as prose."],
    ["EasyWin — Insomni'hack 2017", "https://github.com/Insomnihack/Insomnihack-2017/tree/master/pwn/easywin", "Insomni'hack", "2017", 4, "Windows PE CTF beginner exploitation source binary", "An approachable Windows pwn challenge released by the organizers with source and deployment artifacts. It is a useful entry point for adapting stack-corruption and PE analysis fundamentals to Windows calling conventions, APIs, and debugger workflow before moving to the event's more advanced targets."],
    ["Winworld — Insomni'hack Teaser 2017", "https://github.com/Insomnihack/Teaser-2017/tree/master/winworld", "Insomni'hack", "2017", 4, "Windows CTF pwn PE challenge source exploit practice", "An organizer-preserved Windows challenge with the original binary and supporting material, suitable for reproducing the intended vulnerability and mitigation analysis. Its compact scope makes it valuable practice for identifying Windows-specific execution details without the environmental uncertainty of an unavailable remote service."],
    ["winhttpd — Insomni'hack Teaser 2019", "https://github.com/Insomnihack/Teaser-2019/tree/master/winhttpd", "Insomni'hack", "2019", 5, "Windows HTTP server CTF network pwn heap exploitation", "A Windows network-service pwnable released with its original challenge artifacts by the organizers. It combines protocol-facing input processing with native memory corruption, making it good practice for moving from packet structure and request lifecycle to a reliable exploit under Windows mitigations."],
    ["Firewall — CSAW CTF 2017", "https://github.com/osirislab/CSAW-CTF-2017-Quals/tree/master/pwn/firewall", "OSIRIS Lab", "2017", 5, "Windows CTF firewall driver pwn source solution", "An organizer repository containing the Windows-oriented Firewall pwnable and its solution artifacts. Keeping construction and solution side by side makes it possible to audit the intended vulnerability, reproduce the service, and understand the exploit's assumptions without depending on third-party mirrors."],
    ["STAR Labs Windows Exploitation Challenge 2025", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2025/03-star-labs-windows-exploitation-challenge-2025-writeup/", "STAR Labs / Võ Văn Tiến Dũng", "2025", 5, "Windows kernel CTF race condition UAF pool DQE arbitrary read write", "A complete solution to a purpose-built Windows kernel challenge centered on racing message buckets into a non-paged-pool use-after-free. It develops the corrupted object through buffered DQE reclamation and fake-object spraying into arbitrary kernel read/write, with enough structure recovery and timing detail to reproduce the reasoning."],
    ["HFSAntiCheat — Midnight Sun CTF Finals", "https://clubby789.me/hfsanticheat/", "clubby789", "2023", 5, "Windows kernel CTF KMDF anti-cheat IOCTL physical memory shellcode", "Reverses a KMDF anti-cheat driver, reconstructs its IOCTL surface, and works through a deliberately unusual kernel exploitation environment. The writeup is strong because it documents failed assumptions, WDF structure recovery, physical-memory constraints, and the final kernel payload rather than presenting only a solve script."],
    ["OpenDoor — HTB Business CTF 2022", "https://www.hackthebox.com/blog/open-door-business-ctf", "Hack The Box", "2022", 4, "Windows kernel CTF arbitrary read write EPROCESS token WinDbg", "An accessible Windows kernel challenge built around an intentionally backdoored driver exposing arbitrary read/write. It provides a clean laboratory for locating kernel modules and EPROCESS objects, walking ActiveProcessLinks, and replacing a token while learning the relevant WinDbg workflow."],
    ["Secure Storage Driver — CCCamp 2023", "https://ctftime.org/writeup/37751", "h4x0r-dz / CTFtime", "2023", 4, "Windows kernel CTF pool overflow IOCTL kernel read write", "A ring-0 Windows challenge writeup that begins with the supplied user-mode client and reverses the driver's IOCTL contract before exploiting a kernel pool corruption primitive. Its value is the concrete transition from interface reconnaissance to controlled kernel memory operations and a working exploit."],
    ["WkNote — SECCON CTF 2023 Finals", "https://ctftime.org/writeup/38357", "mephi42 / CTFtime", "2023", 4, "Windows kernel CTF note driver heap pool exploit", "A compact but code-backed solution to a Windows kernel note-driver pwnable from SECCON Finals. The linked exploit is the important artifact: it demonstrates kernel heap manipulation and the exact user-mode interactions needed to turn the challenge bug into privilege escalation."],
    ["FileUtility — Pflanzen CTF 2026", "https://unvariant.pages.dev/writeups/plfanzenctf-2026/die-braucht-viel-licht/", "unvariant", "2026", 5, "Windows kernel CTF file object handle driver exploitation", "A modern Windows kernel challenge whose driver consumes a user-supplied file handle and returns file metadata under subtle lifetime and object-manager constraints. The solution is valuable for its detailed exploration of Windows file objects, kernel handles, exploitation dead ends, and the stronger primitive ultimately constructed."],
    ["Reverse Engineering a Kernel Driver Challenge", "https://pwner.gg/blog/2024-09-22-kernel-driver-pwn", "pwner.gg", "2024", 4, "Windows driver challenge reversing bug PoC exploitation series", "A staged driver-pwn laboratory presented as a reversing and exploitation series: recover the interface, locate the vulnerability, build a trigger, then strengthen the primitive toward LPE. The article serves as the durable index while the accompanying videos preserve the live analysis process and mistakes."],
    ["Pwn2Own 2013 Windows kernel exploit", "https://labs.reversec.com/posts/2013/09/mwr-labs-pwn2own-2013-write-up-kernel-exploit", "MWR Labs", "2013", 5, "Pwn2Own Windows win32k pool overflow kernel fuzzer sandbox escape", "A classic but still instructive account of the win32k kernel stage used to escape Chrome's sandbox at Pwn2Own. It covers fuzzer discovery, root-cause analysis, pool layout control, exploit construction, and the mitigations of its era, making it useful historical context for how Windows kernel pwn matured."],
    ["ProcessFlipper — SekaiCTF 2024", "https://github.com/project-sekai-ctf/sekaictf-2024/tree/main/pwn/process-flipper", "Project Sekai CTF", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 kernel CTF anti-cheat driver LPE solution", "An expert Windows 11 kernel challenge inspired by commercial anti-cheat behavior and distributed with the driver, environment, and official solution. The repository preserves both challenge construction and exploit source, making it substantially more useful than a narrative writeup without artifacts."],
    ["InsoBug — Insomni'hack 2023", "https://itm4n.github.io/insomnihack-2023-insobug/", "itm4n", "2023", 5, "Windows RPC CTF impersonation WebClient NTLM relay service", "A meticulously documented Windows RPC challenge built around a realistic authentication and impersonation logic bug. The writeup reconstructs the service interface, RPC transport, WebClient behavior, token state, and exploit path while explaining why several obvious approaches fail."],
    ["Hexacon 2022 Hyper-V Challenge", "https://github.com/nneonneo/hexacon-2022", "nneonneo", "2022", 5, "Hyper-V CTF VM escape VMBus reverse engineering exploit", "A complete solution artifact for Hexacon's Windows Hyper-V escape challenge, including tooling and exploit code. It is high-value practice for reverse engineering host/guest communication, reconstructing undocumented protocols, and chaining a virtual-device bug across the VM trust boundary."],
    ["Archangel Michael's Storage — HITCON CTF 2020", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/CTF/tree/master/2020-writeup/hitcon/MichaelStorage", "AngelBoy", "2020", 5, "Windows usermode CTF segment heap exploitation", "An advanced Windows user-mode heap challenge and solution focused on the segment heap rather than the classic NT heap. The source-backed writeup is useful for allocator state reconstruction, heap grooming, and studying exploitation techniques that are underrepresented in general pwn material."],
    ["Lucifer — HITCON CTF 2020", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/CTF/tree/master/2020-writeup/hitcon/lucifer", "AngelBoy", "2020", 5, "Windows kernel CTF segment heap driver exploitation", "A Windows kernel challenge designed around the kernel segment heap, with challenge and exploit artifacts preserved together. It provides rare hands-on material for understanding allocator metadata and grooming on builds where older pool exploitation recipes no longer describe reality."],
    ["BitmapManager — Dragon CTF 2020", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/Dragon%20CTF%202020/BitmapManager", "j00ru / Dragon Sector", "2020", 5, "Windows kernel CTF bitmap manager driver challenge solution", "A professionally authored Windows kernel pwnable distributed with source, binaries, deployment material, and solution artifacts. It is a strong target for practicing driver attack-surface recovery and exploit construction against a challenge designed by an experienced Windows vulnerability researcher."],
    ["LOKALTAL — Hack.lu CTF 2025", "https://ctf.gg/blog/lokaltal", "unvariant and cope", "2026", 5, "Windows 11 kernel CTF CVE-2023-21688 ALPC UAF LPAC IO ring", "Ports the AlpcpCreateView use-after-free to Windows 11 25H2 and begins exploitation inside a Low-Privilege AppContainer. The writeup develops a difficult race, pool reclamation with several object families, an arbitrary decrement, failed modern PreviousMode paths, and two final read/write strategies including I/O rings, with challenge files and debugging notes attached."],
    ["Address Book — ECW CTF 2024", "https://blog.randorisec.fr/fr/ctf-ecw-2024/", "RandoriSec", "2024", 5, "Windows pwn CTF address book heap LFH ROP ECW", "A one-solve Windows user-mode pwn challenge documented from protocol and PE triage through heap corruption and final exploitation. The article includes the solver scripts and enough allocator and mitigation reasoning to reproduce the chain, making it a useful modern complement to older Windows 7 heap exercises."],
    ["Baby Heap but Windows — justCTF 2024 Finals", "https://eternal.red/2024/baby-heap-but-windows/", "sajjadium / justCTF", "2024", 5, "Windows usermode CTF segment heap UAF LFH note service", "An author writeup for a one-solve Windows heap challenge distributed with source, solver, VM instructions, and a remotely hosted note service. It follows a dangling note object through Windows heap behavior, disclosures, grooming, and control-flow recovery, providing a rare competition-grade user-mode allocator case with authoritative artifacts."],
    ["BadType — Dragon CTF 2019 Teaser", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/Dragon%20CTF%202019/Teaser/BadType", "j00ru / Dragon Sector", "2019", 5, "Windows CTF OpenType CharStrings font engine reverse engineering maze", "An official Windows x64 challenge that hides its verifier inside OpenType CharStrings interpreted by the platform font engine. The repository includes the PE, embedded-font workflow, maze reconstruction, solution summary, and solver, making it high-quality practice in tracing an unusual Windows parser and virtual machine rather than recognizing a conventional flag check."],
  ]},
  { id: "mitigations", kicker: "Understand the boundary", title: "Mitigations & Windows Internals", items: [
    ["The Internals of AppLocker, Part 1", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/11/the-internals-of-applocker-part-1.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "AppLocker Windows application control policy internals setup enforcement", "Establishes an instrumented AppLocker laboratory and maps policy storage, rule collections, services, event channels, and the high-level enforcement architecture. The post is the correct foundation for the series because it distinguishes user-facing policy behavior from the kernel and user-mode mechanisms examined in the later installments."],
    ["The Internals of AppLocker, Part 2", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/11/the-internals-of-applocker-part-2.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "AppLocker process creation enforcement CI policy SaferIdentifyLevel", "Traces executable enforcement through process creation, application identity, code-integrity decisions, policy queries, and the access checks that ultimately allow or block an image. Debugger and API experiments show where AppLocker obtains identity and why enforcement cannot be reduced to a simple path or hash comparison."],
    ["The Internals of AppLocker, Part 3", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/11/the-internals-of-applocker-part-3.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "AppLocker access tokens security attributes conditional ACE access check", "Explains how AppLocker materializes policy decisions as token security attributes and how conditional ACEs consume those attributes during access checks. The analysis connects application identity to the general Windows authorization model, which is essential for understanding packaged-app ACLs, policy inheritance, and why copied tokens can produce surprising results."],
    ["The Internals of AppLocker, Part 4", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/11/the-internals-of-applocker-part-4.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "AppLocker DLL enforcement loader code integrity policy Windows", "Completes the series by following DLL enforcement through the Windows loader and code-integrity interfaces, including differences from primary executable checks and the performance and compatibility tradeoffs involved. It clarifies exactly when a module load is evaluated and which process state carries the effective AppLocker policy."],
    ["Empirically Assessing Windows Service Hardening", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2020/01/empirically-assessing-windows-service.html", "James Forshaw", "2020", 5, "Windows service hardening restricted SID privileges network firewall empirical", "Builds an automated, measurement-driven view of service hardening by collecting service SIDs, privileges, restricted tokens, network permissions, process mitigations, and accessible resources across Windows services. The resulting comparisons expose where similarly privileged services have materially different attack surfaces and demonstrate how to validate hardening rather than trust configuration labels."],
    ["Don't Use SYSTEM Tokens for Sandboxing", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2020/01/dont-use-system-tokens-for-sandboxing.html", "James Forshaw", "2020", 5, "Windows sandbox restricted SYSTEM token access checks privileges security boundary", "Demonstrates why deriving a restricted sandbox token from SYSTEM can preserve dangerous access through identity, ownership, default DACLs, service objects, and authorization assumptions even after privileges and groups are removed. Concrete token comparisons and resource tests turn a subtle design warning into a reusable sandbox-review methodology."],
    ["LowBox Token Permissive Learning Mode", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2021/09/lowbox-token-permissive-learning-mode.html", "James Forshaw", "2021", 5, "AppContainer LowBox token permissive learning mode access logging sandbox", "Reverse engineers an obscure LowBox token mode that records resources an AppContainer would have been denied while allowing execution to continue. The post identifies token flags, access-check integration, event collection, and practical creation through NtObjectManager, making the feature useful for designing and testing sandbox capability policies."],
    ["Enabling Adminless Mode on Windows 10 S Mode", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/01/enabling-adminless-mode-on-windows-10.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "Windows 10 S Mode adminless WDAC UAC policy security model", "Investigates the supported but poorly documented adminless configuration of Windows 10 S Mode, tracing account creation, policy state, application restrictions, recovery paths, and the resulting privilege model. The experiment provides concrete evidence for how application control and removal of persistent local administrators change the assumptions behind UAC-era hardening."],
    ["Inside Microsoft's Plan to Kill PPLFault", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/inside-microsofts-plan-to-kill-pplfault", "Gabriel Landau / Elastic", "2023", 5, "PPLFault Code Integrity page hashes SEC_IMAGE Cloud Filter mitigation", "Patch-diffs Windows Insider builds to identify the memory-manager and Code Integrity change that blocks PPLFault by enforcing page hashes for network-backed images. Kernel debugging compares vulnerable and fixed behavior, connects the change to SEC_IMAGE immutability assumptions, and evaluates both Microsoft's fix and Elastic's NoFault mitigation."],
    ["Dismantling Smart App Control", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/dismantling-smart-app-control", "Joe Desimone / Elastic", "2024", 5, "Smart App Control SmartScreen reputation Mark of the Web LNK bypass", "Maps Smart App Control and SmartScreen trust decisions, then tests signed malware, reputation hijacking and seeding, interpreter abuse, and a Mark-of-the-Web-removing LNK canonicalization bug. Public utilities, samples, call stacks, in-the-wild evidence, and compensating detections make this both a mitigation study and a rigorous bypass assessment."],
    ["A Windows Authorization Guide", "https://csandker.io/2018/06/14/A-Windows-Authorization-Guide.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2018", 5, "Windows authorization access tokens SIDs privileges ACL security descriptors", "Builds Windows authorization from access tokens, SIDs, groups, privileges, integrity levels, security descriptors, DACLs, and the access-check algorithm. The article is valuable mitigation context for every IPC and service exploit in the catalog because it supplies the vocabulary needed to explain exactly why an operation is permitted instead of reducing findings to 'bad permissions.'"],
    ["DUT Processes in Windows 10", "https://windows-internals.com/dut-processes-in-windows-10/", "Alex Ionescu and Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "DUT process Windows protection level secure process trust model", "Investigates the undocumented DUT process category and places it within Windows' evolving protected-process and trust model. By recovering creation policy, flags, and kernel checks, the post illustrates how security-sensitive process classes differ from ordinary PPL labels and why precise terminology matters when evaluating process protection boundaries."],
    ["Random Windows Things: PreviousMode Mitigation", "https://windows-internals.com/random-windows-things-part-1-previousmode-mitigation/", "Yarden Shafir", "2026", 5, "PreviousMode Windows kernel mitigation KTHREAD exploit primitive hardening", "Examines Microsoft's newer hardening around the KTHREAD PreviousMode field, a long-standing target for turning kernel writes into trusted kernel-mode system-call behavior. It traces the implementation changes and their consequences for exploit chains, providing current context for why older PreviousMode recipes no longer transfer unchanged to recent builds."],
    ["Goodbye Secure Pool, Hello KDP Pool", "https://windows-internals.com/goodbye-secure-pool-hello-kdp-pool/", "Yarden Shafir", "2026", 5, "KDP pool secure kernel VTL1 memory integrity mitigation", "Documents the evolution from the original Secure Pool design to a KDP-backed pool mechanism for protecting sensitive kernel allocations. The analysis connects allocator behavior, VTL boundaries, access policy, and compatibility tradeoffs, making it a useful current reference for researchers evaluating which kernel data can still be modified from VTL0."],
    ["Module Tampering Protection", "https://windows-internals.com/understanding-a-new-mitigation-module-tampering-protection/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "module tampering protection MTP Windows kernel image integrity", "Reverse engineers Module Tampering Protection as introduced in Windows, explaining the policy, loader integration, protected regions, and enforcement path rather than relying on the feature name. The post is particularly useful for distinguishing this mechanism from PatchGuard, HVCI, and ordinary image-signature checks when modeling kernel code-integrity boundaries."],
    ["HyperGuard Part 1: SKPG Initialization", "https://windows-internals.com/hyperguard-secure-kernel-patch-guard-part-1-skpg-initialization/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "HyperGuard SKPG secure kernel PatchGuard VTL1 initialization", "The first part of a detailed HyperGuard reconstruction, following Secure Kernel Patch Guard initialization and the handoff of protected state into VTL1. It provides the vocabulary and lifecycle needed to reason about later extents and checks, while clearly separating hypervisor-enforced protection from traditional PatchGuard behavior in the normal kernel."],
    ["HyperGuard Part 2: SKPG Extents", "https://windows-internals.com/hyperguard-secure-kernel-patch-guard-part-2-skpg-extents/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "HyperGuard SKPG extents secure kernel protected memory", "Continues the HyperGuard analysis by decoding SKPG extents, the descriptors that identify memory and state subject to secure-kernel validation. The article ties recovered structures to initialization and checking code, enabling researchers to verify precisely what is covered rather than treating HyperGuard as an undocumented monolithic integrity feature."],
    ["HyperGuard Part 3: More SKPG Extents", "https://windows-internals.com/hyperguard-part-3-more-skpg-extents/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "HyperGuard SKPG extents callbacks MSR control registers", "Expands the extent taxonomy with additional protected targets and validation forms, including state that cannot be described as a simple immutable memory range. Read with the first two parts, it becomes an unusually complete public model of how Windows delegates sensitive kernel integrity checks across the VTL boundary."],
    ["Secure Pool Internals: Dynamic KDP", "https://windows-internals.com/secure-pool/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "Secure Pool dynamic KDP VBS VTL1 kernel data protection", "Reverse engineers Secure Pool and Dynamic Kernel Data Protection from allocation request through secure-kernel enforcement. It explains how selected kernel data becomes read-only to ordinary VTL0 code while remaining manageable through controlled interfaces, giving exploit developers and defenders a concrete model of data protection under VBS."],
    ["R.I.P ROP: CET Internals in Windows", "https://windows-internals.com/cet-on-windows/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "CET shadow stack Windows kernel user mode ROP mitigation", "A foundational implementation-level analysis of Intel CET support in Windows, covering shadow stacks, process policy, context switching, exception handling, and kernel participation. It goes well beyond a mitigation overview and explains the structures and transitions that determine whether return-address corruption is actually prevented."],
    ["CET Updates: CET on Xanax", "https://windows-internals.com/cet-updates-cet-on-xanax/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "CET relaxed mode compatibility shadow stack Windows", "Examines Windows' compatibility mechanisms for applications that cannot immediately obey strict shadow-stack semantics, including relaxed handling and policy transitions. The details are important for security analysis because they reveal where deployment compatibility changes the effective protection promised by CET on paper."],
    ["CET Updates: Dynamic Address Ranges", "https://windows-internals.com/cet-updates-dynamic-address-ranges/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "CET dynamic code JIT shadow stack address ranges mitigation", "Explains how Windows accommodates JIT engines and other dynamic-code producers under CET using managed address ranges and explicit policy. The article maps the supporting APIs and kernel bookkeeping, helping researchers distinguish legitimate dynamically generated call targets from gaps or abuse opportunities in shadow-stack enforcement."],
    ["The KASLR graveyard: leaking ntoskrnl on Windows 11 25H2", "https://afflicted.sh/blog/posts/kaslr-graveyard.html", "afflicted.sh", "2026", 5, "Windows 11 25H2 KASLR leaks GDT IDT desktop heap prefetch", "Tests a wide catalog of kernel-base disclosure paths against a concrete Windows 11 25H2 target and explains why each succeeds or fails. The result works like a modern KASLR decision tree spanning restricted queries, descriptor tables, desktop heaps, physical memory, CPU differences, and prefetch behavior."],
    ["Bypassing Windows Kernel Mitigations: Part 0", "https://hackyboiz.github.io/2025/04/13/l0ch/bypassing-kernel-mitigation-part0/en/", "Hackyboiz / L0ch", "2025", 5, "Windows 11 24H2 KASLR prefetch EntryBleed KVA shadow", "Explains the Windows 11 24H2 KASLR restriction from an exploit developer's perspective, then adapts an EntryBleed-style prefetch timing side channel. It connects page tables, KVA shadowing, TLB state, and CPU-specific timing behavior to practical ntoskrnl-base recovery."],
    ["Windows Exploit Mitigations", "https://github.com/nccgroup/exploit_mitigations/blob/main/windows_mitigations.md", "NCC Group", "Living", 5, "Windows mitigations DEP ASLR CFG CET reference", "A maintained knowledge base that maps Windows exploit mitigations to their purpose, scope, and implementation context. Use it as a high-level map before diving into a single bypass or comparing protections across platform generations."],
    ["KASLR Leaks Restriction", "https://windows-internals.com/kaslr-leaks-restriction/", "Windows Internals", "2024", 5, "ExIsRestrictedCaller NtQuerySystemInformation KASLR", "Explains the Windows changes that remove many kernel-address disclosures from unprivileged callers. It is the best starting point for understanding ExIsRestrictedCaller, affected system-information classes, and why older disclosure assumptions no longer hold."],
    ["An End to KASLR Bypasses?", "https://windows-internals.com/an-end-to-kaslr-bypasses/", "Windows Internals", "2024", 4, "kernel pointers restricted caller integrity level", "Provides the broader design context behind Microsoft's restriction of kernel pointer disclosures. It helps connect integrity levels and sandbox boundaries to the mitigation and identifies assumptions embedded in older Windows kernel exploits."],
    ["Windows Kernel Shadow Stack Mitigation", "https://www.synacktiv.com/sites/default/files/2025-06/sstic_windows_kernel_shadow_stack_mitigation.pdf", "Synacktiv / SSTIC", "2025", 5, "kernel shadow stack CET mitigation PDF", "A deep technical treatment of Windows kernel shadow stacks and their consequences for control-flow hijacking. The slides are dense but valuable when evaluating which exploitation paths kernel CET removes and what remains available."],
    ["The new Windows Component Filter mitigation", "https://big5-sec.github.io/posts/component-filter-mitigation/", "BIG5", "2024", 5, "Windows Component Filter kernel mitigation KASLR", "Reverse engineers the Component Filter mitigation and explains how Windows restricts sensitive system information by caller context. Read it alongside the KASLR restriction posts to understand both policy and implementation details."],
    ["Intel VT-rp, Part 1", "https://tandasat.github.io/blog/2023/07/05/intel-vt-rp-part-1.html", "Tandasat", "2023", 5, "Intel VT remapping HLAT KDP g_CiOptions", "Introduces a virtualization-based remapping attack and the role of Hypervisor-managed Linear Address Translation. It demonstrates how page-remapping ideas interact with KDP and g_CiOptions, connecting hardware virtualization to Windows kernel protection research."],
    ["Windows Internals archive", "https://windows-internals.com/category/windows-internals/", "Winsider", "Living", 5, "Windows internals kernel secure kernel VBS", "A concentrated archive of original Windows internals research spanning the kernel, secure kernel, mitigations, and low-level APIs. Use it as a topic index and favor the individual articles when recording a technique or claim."],
    ["ZeroHVCI", "https://github.com/zer0condition/ZeroHVCI", "zer0condition", "2024", 5, "HVCI bypass CVE-2024-26229 CVE-2024-35250 KernelForge kernel ROP", "Chains kernel read/write primitives from csc.sys and ks.sys vulnerabilities with KernelForge's HVCI-compatible function-calling technique. The source demonstrates data access and constructed kernel calls without loading an unsigned driver, making it a concrete study of what memory integrity blocks, what it still permits, and how separate primitives compose."],
    ["Introducing Kernel Data Protection", "https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2020/07/08/introducing-kernel-data-protection-a-new-platform-security-technology-for-preventing-data-corruption/", "Microsoft Security Team", "2020", 5, "Kernel Data Protection KDP VBS SLAT secure pool driver data", "The primary implementation overview of static and dynamic KDP, explaining how VTL1 and hypervisor-controlled second-level page tables make selected driver data read-only even after VTL0 kernel compromise. It documents MmProtectDriverSection, ExAllocatePool3 secure-pool parameters, tags and cookies, unload semantics, GVA-to-GPA-to-SPA translation, and the trust boundary enforced by EPT or NPT."],
    ["KVA Shadow: Mitigating Meltdown on Windows", "https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/msrc/blog/2018/03/kva-shadow-mitigating-meltdown-on-windows", "Microsoft Security Response Center", "2018", 5, "KVA Shadow Meltdown page tables PCID TLB Windows kernel mitigation", "Describes the extensive Windows kernel redesign used to isolate kernel mappings from user-mode page tables against Meltdown. The article covers separate address spaces, user/kernel transition costs, PCID_KERNEL and PCID_USER tagging, translation-buffer preservation and invalidation, driver compatibility assumptions, and why performance varies by processor capability and workload."],
    ["Understanding Hardware-enforced Stack Protection", "https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/blog/windowsosplatform/understanding-hardware-enforced-stack-protection/1247815", "Microsoft Windows Kernel Protection", "2020", 5, "Intel CET shadow stack ROP control protection exception Windows", "Introduces Windows' hardware-backed backward-edge control-flow integrity from the processor contract upward: shadow-stack pages, SSP state, CALL and RET comparison, #CP delivery, new CET management instructions, context switching, PE opt-in metadata, and the relationship with CFG, DEP, ASLR, CIG, and ACG. It provides the architectural baseline needed before studying compatibility exceptions or bypasses."],
    ["Developer Guidance for Hardware-enforced Stack Protection", "https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/blog/windowsosplatform/developer-guidance-for-hardware-enforced-stack-protection/2163340/", "Microsoft Windows Kernel Protection", "2021", 5, "CET compatibility strict mode EH continuation dynamic code Windows", "Details the deployed user-mode CET policies that the introductory article leaves open: compatibility versus strict enforcement, /CETCOMPAT modules, dynamic-code ranges, instruction-pointer validation for exception handling, process mitigation controls, audit surfaces, and unsupported WoW64 or guest scenarios. The compatibility rules are especially important when assessing the mitigation's effective rather than advertised coverage."],
    ["Kernel-mode Hardware-enforced Stack Protection", "https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/security/kernel-mode-hardware-stack-protection", "Microsoft", "Living", 4, "kernel CET shadow stacks VBS HVCI driver blocklist Windows 11", "Documents the production kernel-mode form of hardware shadow-stack enforcement, including its VBS and HVCI prerequisites, supported Intel and AMD generations, CFG interaction, return-address mismatch behavior, enablement policy, and incompatible-driver blocklist. It complements reverse-engineering research with the current platform support and deployment contract administrators and driver authors must satisfy."],
    ["Driver Compatibility with Hypervisor-Protected Code Integrity", "https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/test/hlk/testref/driver-compatibility-with-device-guard", "Microsoft", "Living", 4, "HVCI memory integrity W XOR X driver compatibility HLK Windows", "Provides the authoritative driver-development constraints imposed by HVCI: executable memory cannot be writable, executable pool and dynamic code patterns must be removed, section alignment and relocations must be valid, and HLK checks can identify incompatible images. This is a practical complement to offensive HVCI research because it defines which driver behaviors the isolated code-integrity boundary is designed to reject."],
  ]},
  { id: "evasion", kicker: "Observe and evade", title: "Evasion & EDR", items: [
    ["Working Your Way Around an ACL", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2024/06/working-your-way-around-acl.html", "James Forshaw", "2024", 5, "WindowsApps conditional ACL token security attributes impersonation Explorer", "Dissects the conditional ACL protecting the WindowsApps directory and shows how an unelevated process can borrow an existing packaged-app token carrying WIN://SYSAPPID, then preserve it through Explorer process creation. The post is a precise example of satisfying an access policy through legitimate token state instead of modifying or bypassing the ACL itself."],
    ["Bypassing SACL Auditing on LSASS", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2017/10/bypassing-sacl-auditing-on-lsass.html", "James Forshaw", "2017", 5, "LSASS SACL auditing process handle access token duplicate evasion", "Examines Windows object auditing around LSASS and develops access paths whose effective operations are not represented by the expected SACL events. Native handle, token, and access-check behavior explain the telemetry gap, making the article valuable for defenders who might otherwise treat one process-access audit as complete credential-access coverage."],
    ["Sandboxing Antimalware Products", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/sandboxing-antimalware-products", "Gabriel Landau / Elastic", "2023", 5, "PPL antimalware token sandbox trust label SYSTEM integrity EDR bypass", "Shows that an administrator can open and modify a protected antimalware service's token, remove privileges, lower integrity, and quietly incapacitate the product without terminating its PPL process. The research traces token security descriptors and trust labels, releases PPLGuard mitigation code, and records Microsoft disclosure, giving both attack and defensive implementation evidence."],
    ["Effective Parenting: Detecting LRPC PPID Spoofing", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/effective-parenting-detecting-lrpc-based-parent-pid-spoofing/", "John Uhlmann / Elastic", "2023", 5, "LRPC COM WMI PPID spoofing process creation ETW correlation", "Studies process creation proxied through COM, WMI, and other LRPC servers as a parentage-evasion problem, then develops a generic detector by correlating RPC client and server activity with kernel process events. The article tests common heuristics, documents their blind spots, and proposes telemetry that recovers the initiating process rather than trusting the visible parent."],
    ["Detecting In-Memory Threats with Kernel ETW Call Stacks", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/doubling-down-etw-callstacks", "Elastic Security Labs", "2024", 5, "kernel ETW Threat Intelligence call stacks direct syscalls injection evasion", "Explains how kernel ETW call stacks expose direct and indirect syscalls, proxied calls, ROP-like transitions, unbacked executable memory, hollowing, and AMSI or ETW patching that bypass user-mode hooks. Concrete behavior fields and production detection rules make it an unusually transparent reference for both designing and evaluating modern in-memory evasion."],
    ["A Taxonomy of Endpoint Detection Bypasses", "https://www.elastic.co/blog/edr-bypass-taxonomy", "Gabriel Landau / Elastic", "2023", 5, "EDR bypass taxonomy kernel callbacks ETW minifilters user mode hooks", "Builds an architectural taxonomy of Windows endpoint sensors—kernel callbacks, minifilters, WFP, ETW, AMSI, event logs, and user-mode hooks—and maps bypass classes to the trust layer they defeat. The explicit distinction between asynchronous detection, synchronous prevention, tampering, and semantic evasion provides a durable framework for judging individual bypass claims."],
    ["Forget Vulnerable Drivers: Admin Is All You Need", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/forget-vulnerable-drivers-admin-is-all-you-need", "Gabriel Landau / Elastic", "2023", 5, "PPLFault GodFault PPL kernel exploit EDRSandblast driverless admin kernel", "Demonstrates an admin-to-PPL chain followed by a PPL-to-kernel trust violation, then uses the resulting access to reproduce vulnerable-driver-style EDR tampering without loading a driver. The report includes PPLFault, GodFault, NoFault, kernel consequences, mitigation guidance, and a careful discussion of the contested admin-to-kernel security boundary."],
    ["Do You Really Know LSA Protection?", "https://itm4n.github.io/lsass-runasppl/", "itm4n", "2021", 5, "LSASS RunAsPPL LSA protection protected process light Windows internals", "Builds the threat model for LSA protection from the actual RunAsPPL configuration, process-protection levels, signer requirements, and boot behavior. It is the necessary foundation for judging credential-dumping claims because it distinguishes what PPL prevents, what remains observable, and which trust boundaries later bypass research must cross."],
    ["Bypassing LSA Protection in Userland", "https://itm4n.github.io/bypassing-lsa-protection-userland/", "itm4n", "2021", 5, "LSA protection PPL bypass user mode DLL loading credential dumping", "Develops a user-mode route around LSA protection by studying how LSASS loads code and how protected-process signing policy is enforced. The article accounts for prerequisites, target state, payload constraints, and detection surface, making it a strong example of converting a platform-internals observation into a bounded credential-access technique."],
    ["Revisiting a Credential Guard Bypass", "https://itm4n.github.io/credential-guard-bypass/", "itm4n", "2022", 5, "Credential Guard VBS LSASS authentication package bypass secrets", "Re-examines a published Credential Guard bypass against current Windows behavior and traces credentials across LSASS, authentication packages, and the isolated security boundary. It is valuable because it tests the scope of the protection empirically and states which material remains obtainable rather than treating Credential Guard as an all-or-nothing control."],
    ["The End of PPLdump", "https://itm4n.github.io/the-end-of-ppldump/", "itm4n", "2022", 5, "PPLdump protected process LSASS patch bypass remediation", "Analyzes the Windows changes that broke PPLdump and uses the failure to explain the exact implementation weakness the tool depended on. By comparing the original primitive with the patched object and access behavior, the post teaches both PPL bypass mechanics and the importance of revalidating offensive tools after platform servicing."],
    ["Bypassing PPL in Userland Again", "https://itm4n.github.io/bypassing-ppl-in-userland-again/", "itm4n", "2023", 5, "protected process light PPL userland bypass LSASS code execution", "Returns to user-mode PPL bypass after earlier paths were hardened and develops a new chain from Windows loading and trust behavior. The research clearly separates discovery, required privileges, protected-process constraints, and practical execution, which makes it useful for both offensive study and evaluating whether a defensive PPL deployment closes the intended path."],
    ["The Ghost in the PPL, Part 1", "https://itm4n.github.io/ghost-in-the-ppl-part-1/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "PPL protected process code injection section mapping Windows internals", "Opens a three-part investigation into executing code inside a protected process by establishing the protection model, available handles, memory objects, and loader constraints. The installment is intentionally primitive-focused, giving readers enough internals to understand why ordinary injection fails before the later stages assemble a workable chain."],
    ["The Ghost in the PPL, Part 2", "https://itm4n.github.io/ghost-in-the-ppl-part-2/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "PPL bypass KnownDll section object namespace injection Windows", "Extends the Ghost in the PPL research through object-manager and image-loading behavior, refining the initial capabilities into a route that can influence protected execution. It records the dead ends and security checks encountered along the way, which is especially useful for reasoning about the difference between writable state and executable influence."],
    ["The Ghost in the PPL, Part 3", "https://itm4n.github.io/ghost-in-the-ppl-part-3/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "PPL bypass exploit chain LSASS protected process code execution", "Completes the series by joining the discovered namespace, image, and execution primitives into a practical protected-process compromise and then examining limitations and remediation. Read with the first two parts, it is one of the clearest end-to-end studies of modern user-mode PPL attack surface and exploit-chain engineering."],
    ["Direct System Calls for Red Teams", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2020/12/bypassing-user-mode-hooks-and-direct-invocation-of-system-calls-for-red-teams/", "MDSec", "2020", 5, "direct syscalls Windows ntdll user mode hooks process injection", "A careful treatment of resolving and invoking Windows system calls without relying on potentially hooked ntdll stubs. It discusses the motivation, implementation choices, version-dependent service numbers, and injection use case, giving readers enough context to evaluate both the bypass and the telemetry that remains below user mode."],
    ["FireWalker: Generic User-Space Hook Bypass", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2020/08/firewalker-a-new-approach-to-generically-bypass-user-space-edr-hooking/", "MDSec", "2020", 5, "FireWalker EDR hook bypass hardware breakpoints exception handler", "Introduces a generic approach to stepping through and bypassing user-space EDR hooks using exception-driven control rather than restoring library bytes or hard-coding syscall identifiers. The writeup develops the mechanism and limitations in detail, making it a valuable study of what hooks observe and how alternative control flow interacts with them."],
    ["Silencing Cylance", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2019/03/silencing-cylance-a-case-study-in-modern-edrs/", "MDSec", "2019", 5, "Cylance EDR self protection service driver bypass case study", "A product-specific investigation of Cylance's user and kernel components, self-protection, and enforcement behavior that proceeds from reverse engineering to a tested bypass. It is valuable as methodology: the researchers map the product architecture and validate assumptions instead of presenting a generic AV-disable command."],
    ["Cisco AMP Self-Protection Bypass", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2018/10/cisco-amp-bypassing-self-protection/", "MDSec", "2018", 4, "Cisco AMP EDR self protection bypass Windows service", "A concise real-world case study in analyzing and bypassing an endpoint product's self-protection during an engagement. The article records the service and process behavior, the control weakness, and operational result, providing historical evidence of why protection claims must be checked against the complete component architecture."],
    ["Chaos Rootkit", "https://github.com/ZeroMemoryEx/Chaos-Rootkit", "ZeroMemoryEx", "2023", 5, "Windows rootkit DKOM process driver file hiding callbacks networking", "A substantial open-source Windows rootkit research project implementing multiple hiding and tampering capabilities rather than a single proof of concept. The code offers a concrete basis for studying DKOM, callbacks, object discovery, and cross-view detection assumptions, and it is frequently referenced from vulnerable-driver research graphs."],
    ["AvastHV", "https://github.com/tanduRE/AvastHV", "tanduRE", "2020", 5, "Avast hypervisor SSDT hook nested virtualization Windows kernel", "A research project that repurposes Avast's virtualization components to intercept Windows system calls from the hypervisor rather than patching the ordinary kernel. It provides rare code-level material for understanding how security-product virtualization can become an execution and monitoring primitive below PatchGuard's usual view."],
    ["Qilin EDR Killer Infection Chain", "https://blog.talosintelligence.com/qilin-edr-killer/", "Cisco Talos", "2026", 5, "Qilin EDR killer ETW syscalls kernel object manipulation hooks", "A code-level analysis of an EDR-killing DLL deployed with Qilin ransomware, covering its PE loader, SEH and VEH control-flow obfuscation, syscall and API resolution, user-mode hook removal, ETW suppression, and kernel-object manipulation. The report is especially useful because it follows the whole execution chain and relates each evasion layer to observable behavior."],
    ["DKOM, Now with Symbolic Links", "https://windows-internals.com/dkom-now-with-symbolic-links/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "DKOM object manager symbolic links kernel hiding manipulation", "Demonstrates Direct Kernel Object Manipulation against object-manager symbolic links and uses the exercise to expose the structures and lookup behavior behind familiar DOS-device paths. Beyond the hiding effect, the post is a strong example of deriving a manipulation from object lifetime and namespace internals rather than copying offsets."],
    ["Kernel Data Discovery Through Lookaside Lists", "https://windows-internals.com/lookaside-list-forensics/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "kernel data discovery lookaside lists forensics rootkit signature scanning", "Proposes lookaside-list metadata as a more structural way to discover kernel allocations than fragile byte signatures. The approach is relevant to both stealth tooling and memory forensics because it reasons from allocator ownership and cached object types, while also documenting the version and lifecycle assumptions a detector must validate."],
    ["RedEdr", "https://github.com/dobin/RedEdr", "dobin", "Living", 5, "EDR introspection ETW ETW-TI Defender telemetry hooks callbacks", "An open-source laboratory for observing the same Windows telemetry surfaces that endpoint products consume, including ETW, ETW Threat Intelligence, user-mode hooks, kernel callbacks, and Defender-specific providers. It earns a place here because it supports measurement and validation: researchers can see which behavior generated which signal instead of assuming that a bypass worked because a payload executed."],
    ["EDR-Introspection", "https://github.com/yo-yo-yo-jbo/EDR-Introspection", "John Barak", "Living", 5, "EDR internals minifilter callbacks ETW WFP telemetry enumeration", "A research tool for enumerating the operating-system integrations used by endpoint products, including process and object callbacks, minifilters, ETW providers, WFP filters, and related kernel registrations. It is especially useful for building a product-specific attack-surface map before testing evasion claims, and for comparing what remains visible after a technique changes one telemetry path."],
    ["libelevate: handle elevation against ObRegisterCallbacks", "https://github.com/notscimmy/libelevate", "notscimmy", "2017", 4, "ObRegisterCallbacks DKOM handle table access elevation anti-cheat EDR", "A compact kernel research project that bypasses access stripping by modifying a target handle-table entry after callbacks have run, rather than removing the callback registration itself. The accompanying explanation is valuable for studying ExEnumHandleTable, encoded handle entries, and the distinction between disabling an enforcement mechanism and repairing the rights it removed."],
    ["About Hiding on Windows", "https://kernullist.github.io/kernullist-blog/posts/hiding-on-windows/", "Kernullist", "2026", 5, "DKOM injection BYOVD hiding cross-view detection", "Surveys hiding processes, threads, DLLs, drivers, callbacks, and executable regions using DKOM, injection, and BYOVD techniques. Its cross-view detection discussion is particularly useful because it pairs offensive manipulation with the defender's competing sources of truth."],
    ["Attacking EDRs Part 1: EDR Drivers", "https://labs.infoguard.ch/posts/edr_part1_intro_-_security_analysis_of_edr_drivers/", "InfoGuard Labs", "2025", 5, "EDR driver callbacks attack surface reverse engineering", "Establishes a methodology for analyzing the kernel drivers that give EDR products visibility and enforcement power. It maps callbacks, exposed interfaces, and attack surface so later bypass work is grounded in how the product actually collects telemetry."],
    ["awesome-edr-bypass", "https://github.com/tkmru/awesome-edr-bypass", "tkmru", "Living", 4, "EDR bypass curated research tools", "A curated directory of EDR bypass research, techniques, presentations, and tooling. It is best used as a discovery index; verify individual techniques against modern product versions before treating them as operationally current."],
    ["KernelCallbackTable Injection PoC", "https://github.com/0xHossam/KernelCallbackTable-Injection-PoC#introduction", "0xHossam", "2024", 4, "process injection PEB KernelCallbackTable execution hijack", "Demonstrates process injection by replacing a callback pointer in the target's PEB-backed KernelCallbackTable. The compact PoC makes the execution flow easy to trace and provides a useful basis for studying telemetry and defensive detection."],
    ["kurasagi: runtime PatchGuard bypass", "https://github.com/NeoMaster831/kurasagi", "NeoMaster831", "2025", 4, "Windows 11 PatchGuard bypass 24H2 25H2", "A research implementation targeting runtime PatchGuard bypass on Windows 11 24H2 and 25H2. Because it depends strongly on undocumented and build-specific behavior, use it as an advanced study target rather than a portable technique."],
    ["BYOVD and legitimate certificates", "https://blog.ghostwolflab.com/apt/737/", "Ghost Wolf Lab", "2026", 3, "BYOVD APT certificates vulnerable drivers", "Discusses how BYOVD tradecraft is shifting from obviously vulnerable drivers toward trust inherited from legitimate certificates. It is a useful threat-research perspective for connecting driver abuse, signing policy, and the limits of blocklist-only defenses."],
    ["EDRPrison: borrow a legitimate driver to mute EDR", "https://www.3nailsinfosec.com/post/edrprison-borrow-a-legitimate-driver-to-mute-edr-agent", "Ziyi Shen", "2024", 5, "EDR evasion WinDivert WFP callout network telemetry", "Builds an EDR network-isolation technique around the legitimate WinDivert callout driver and Windows Filtering Platform metadata. The article explains why firewall, proxy, and persistent-filter approaches are weaker, then traces how process-associated packets can be selectively dropped without opening the protected EDR process."],
    ["Nirvana v2: detecting raw and gadgeted direct syscalls", "https://cameronbabcock.net/blog/direct-syscall-detection-instrumentation-callbacks/", "Cameron Babcock", "2026", 5, "direct syscall detection instrumentation callback ThreadLastSystemCall provenance", "Builds a kernel-grounded detector that catalogs live ntdll and win32u syscall stubs, captures the previous user PC through ProcessInstrumentationCallback, obtains the serviced ID from ThreadLastSystemCall, and verifies that syscall ownership matches return-address ownership. The source and WinDbg notes demonstrate clean, raw, and borrowed-gadget cases without relying on entry-point hooks."],
    ["ETW Internals: architecture, tampering, and detection", "https://kernullist.github.io/kernullist-blog/posts/etw-internals-deep-dive/", "Kernullist", "2026", 5, "ETW ETWTI provider session consumer DKOM AutoLogger detection", "Maps ETW as a routing fabric across provider registration, enable slots, logger contexts, buffers, filters, real-time consumers, AutoLoggers, silos, and security-qualified ETWTI access. It analyzes user-mode patching versus kernel DKOM, byte-level provider silencing and delivery-path corruption, then derives cross-view canaries and integrity checks so defenders can distinguish a quiet system from a blinded sensor."],
    ["Windows Instrumentation Callbacks, part 1", "https://cirosec.de/en/news/windows-instrumentation-callbacks/", "Lino Facco / cirosec", "2025", 5, "Windows instrumentation callback KiSetupForInstrumentationReturn syscall spoofing patchless hooks", "Reverse engineers the Windows 10 and 11 process instrumentation callback path from KPROCESS.InstrumentationCallback through KiSetupForInstrumentationReturn and the saved KTRAP_FRAME. The article documents NtSetInformationProcess setup, x64 register and stack restoration, recursion hazards, and practical syscall logging and spoofing, establishing the mechanics later used for patchless monitoring or evasion."],
    ["Using process creation properties to catch evasion", "https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2022/06/30/using-process-creation-properties-to-catch-evasion-techniques/", "Microsoft Defender Research", "2022", 5, "process tampering NtCreateProcessEx ECP image section TOCTOU antimalware", "Generalizes Doppelgänging, Ghosting, and related transient-file execution into one detection model. It contrasts NtCreateUserProcess with legacy section-based NtCreateProcessEx, follows process callbacks and GUID_ECP_CREATE_USER_PROCESS provenance, then combines the missing ECP with MmDoesFileHaveUserWritableReferences to identify pagefile-backed image sections whose malicious disk state vanished before scanning."],
  ]},
  { id: "byovd", kicker: "Cross the trust boundary", title: "BYOVD & Kernel Driver Abuse", items: [
    ["The (Almost) Forgotten Vulnerable Driver", "https://decoder.cloud/2025/01/09/the-almost-forgotten-vulnerable-driver/", "Decoder", "2025", 5, "StopZilla vulnerable driver increment primitive PPL PreviousMode BYOVD", "Revisits a signed StopZilla driver whose METHOD_NEITHER IOCTL exposes a constrained increment primitive, then applies it to token privileges, LSASS protection fields, and KTHREAD PreviousMode. The post is unusually useful because it records build-specific offsets and explains why the PreviousMode route behaves differently on Windows 11 24H2."],
    ["Exploiting Toshiba qiomem.sys", "https://valium007.github.io/posts/toshiba-vuln/", "Valium", "2026", 5, "Toshiba qiomem physical memory MmMapIoSpace PnP HVCI BYOVD", "Reverse engineers qiomem.sys IOCTLs that map attacker-chosen physical addresses, reconstructs the packed request format, and demonstrates round-trip physical reads and writes. It also solves the often-overlooked loading constraint by creating a matching software PnP device and tests the driver under HVCI and the Microsoft blocklist."],
    ["From Domain User to Kernel Memory", "https://expel.com/blog/well-that-escalated-quickly-how-a-red-team-went-from-domain-user-to-kernel-memory/", "Expel", "2025", 5, "red team BYOVD vulnerable driver kernel memory exploit chain", "Documents a real red-team path from domain-user access to control of Windows kernel memory, preserving the discovery, driver selection, exploit engineering, and defensive implications of each transition. It is valuable because BYOVD is presented as one link in a complete operation rather than as an isolated driver-loading demonstration."],
    ["Chasing the Silver Fox: Kernel Shadows", "https://research.checkpoint.com/2025/silver-fox-apt-vulnerable-drivers/", "Check Point Research", "2025", 5, "Silver Fox APT BYOVD vulnerable drivers EDR evasion kernel malware", "Tracks Silver Fox campaigns as they rotate vulnerable and malicious kernel drivers to disable security controls, with driver-level analysis, execution flow, infrastructure, and detection material. The research connects catalog hashes to an evolving adversary workflow and shows why defenders must reason about capabilities and signer lineage, not filenames alone."],
    ["Mimidrv In Depth", "https://posts.specterops.io/mimidrv-in-depth-4d273d19e148", "Matt Hand / SpecterOps", "2020", 5, "mimidrv Windows kernel driver IOCTL process protection token callbacks", "Reverse engineers Mimikatz's kernel driver and maps its user-mode commands to device IOCTLs, kernel structures, process protection manipulation, token operations, and callback removal. It is an important bridge between public offensive tooling and the exact privileged mechanisms that detections or driver policies must constrain."],
    ["Dellicious", "https://github.com/jbaines-r7/dellicious", "Jake Baines / Rapid7", "2021", 5, "BYOVD Dell DBUtilDrv2 LSA protection PPL process flags", "A focused implementation that installs vulnerable Dell DBUtilDrv2, locates a target EPROCESS, and modifies signature and protection fields to enable or disable LSA protection before removing the device. The README documents required driver hashes, build offsets, artifacts, influences, and exact CLI output, making the kernel-write path auditable rather than opaque."],
    ["GoodBaiii", "https://github.com/RainbowDynamix/GoodBaiii", "RainbowDynamix", "2024", 4, "BYOVD Baidu BdApiUtil low integrity process termination", "A small, source-available proof of concept showing that Baidu's BdApiUtil driver can terminate arbitrary processes even when invoked from low integrity, with an optional bring-your-own-driver path. It includes the vulnerable-driver hash and concrete driver-load telemetry, so the offensive primitive is paired with actionable detection guidance."],
    ["Blackout", "https://github.com/ZeroMemoryEx/Blackout", "ZeroMemoryEx", "2023", 4, "BYOVD anti malware protected process termination vulnerable driver", "A concise BYOVD implementation for terminating protected anti-malware processes through a signed vulnerable driver. Its value is the readable orchestration and kernel interaction, which can be compared with sibling projects to understand how different drivers expose similar process-kill outcomes and what artifacts each path produces."],
    ["Backstab", "https://github.com/Yaxser/Backstab", "Yaxser", "2023", 4, "BYOVD antimalware process killer vulnerable driver callbacks", "A source-level tool for killing protected security-product processes using a vulnerable signed driver, linked from LOLDrivers records and the author's broader BYOVD research. It is useful for tracing driver deployment, device communication, target selection, and teardown as one complete chain rather than treating the vulnerable IOCTL in isolation."],
    ["CYBERSEC 2023 BYOVD Demo", "https://github.com/zeze-zeze/CYBERSEC2023-BYOVD-Demo", "zeze-zeze", "2023", 4, "BYOVD conference demo Windows kernel vulnerable driver EDR", "The public demonstration artifact accompanying a CYBERSEC presentation on bringing vulnerable drivers into an attack chain. It preserves the code and operational setup needed to reproduce the technique and compare the driver's kernel capability with the user-mode actions it enables."],
    ["Exploring vulnerable Windows drivers", "https://blog.talosintelligence.com/exploring-vulnerable-windows-drivers/", "Cisco Talos", "2024", 5, "BYOVD arbitrary memory write MSR EDR ransomware driver blocklist", "One of the strongest modern surveys of how vulnerable drivers are converted into token theft, unsigned kernel-code loading, EDR termination, and destructive payloads. It joins vulnerability classes to real ransomware campaigns and explains where Microsoft's vulnerable-driver blocklist helps—and where it does not."],
    ["Signed kernel drivers: an unguarded gateway to Windows' core", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2022/01/11/signed-kernel-drivers-unguarded-gateway-windows-core/", "ESET Research", "2022", 5, "BYOVD signed drivers DSE malware rootkit kernel", "A foundational study of signed-driver abuse across APT and commodity malware, supported by a large-scale survey of vulnerable drivers. It gives the historical and architectural context needed to understand why code signing alone cannot solve BYOVD."],
    ["LOLDrivers", "https://www.loldrivers.io/", "Community project", "Living", 5, "BYOVD hashes certificates vulnerable malicious drivers detection", "The canonical community-maintained catalog of Windows drivers abused to bypass security controls or execute kernel code. Each record connects hashes, signatures, known abuse, detections, and references, making it the first stop for triage—not a substitute for reversing the actual driver."],
    ["Shedding light on the ABYSSWORKER driver", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/abyssworker", "Elastic Security Labs", "2025", 5, "malicious driver EDR killer callbacks minifilter IOCTL ransomware", "A code-level analysis of the MEDUSA-linked ABYSSWORKER driver, including IOCTL handlers that terminate processes, remove callbacks, detach minifilters, and replace dispatch routines. RVAs, samples, YARA, and a client implementation make the research unusually reproducible."],
    ["Lazarus & BYOVD: evil to the Windows core", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2022/09/30/amazon-themed-campaigns-lazarus-netherlands-belgium/", "ESET Research", "2022", 5, "Lazarus CVE-2021-21551 Dell driver rootkit EDR blinding", "Documents Lazarus weaponizing Dell's DBUtil vulnerability to obtain kernel read/write and disable monitoring components. It is a high-value bridge between exploit primitives and a real APT's operational rootkit and defense-evasion design."],
    ["Screwed Drivers", "https://github.com/eclypsium/Screwed-Drivers", "Eclypsium", "2019", 5, "signed drivers firmware access kernel primitives research corpus", "The research corpus behind Eclypsium's discovery of widespread signed drivers exposing privileged hardware and firmware access. It is useful both as a historic BYOVD turning point and as a concrete collection for comparing vulnerable interface patterns across vendors."],
    ["physmem_drivers", "https://github.com/namazso/physmem_drivers", "namazso", "Living", 5, "physical memory vulnerable signed drivers comparative library", "A compact comparative library for signed drivers that expose physical-memory primitives, with common abstractions and per-driver implementations. Reading the code side by side reveals how recurring IOCTL and mapping designs can be normalized into reusable kernel read/write capabilities."],
    ["KDU", "https://github.com/hfiref0x/KDU", "hfiref0x", "Living", 5, "kernel driver utility vulnerable driver providers DSE mapping", "A mature research utility with a provider model covering many vulnerable-driver families and multiple kernel-code loading strategies. Its breadth and careful build-specific handling make it executable documentation of the BYOVD ecosystem, though it belongs only in isolated research environments."],
    ["BYOVD Research", "https://github.com/KOSEC-LLC/BYOVD-Research", "KOSEC", "Living", 4, "BYOVD driver research exploit chains vendor analysis", "A focused repository collecting reproducible vulnerable-driver research and exploitation artifacts. It is valuable as a bridge from catalog records to code-level validation, with enough context to compare driver primitives rather than treating hashes as the research endpoint."],
    ["BlackSnufkin BYOVD", "https://github.com/BlackSnufkin/BYOVD", "BlackSnufkin", "Living", 4, "BYOVD EDR termination callbacks kernel driver PoC", "A practical implementation of vulnerable-driver-assisted security-product tampering with clear source and operational flow. Use it to study how user-mode orchestration, device IOCTLs, process discovery, and kernel capabilities are assembled into an EDR-kill chain."],
    ["RealBlindingEDR", "https://github.com/myzxcg/RealBlindingEDR", "myz", "2024", 5, "EDR callbacks minifilters ETW Ti vulnerable driver kernel tampering", "A source-level implementation of blinding EDR telemetry through kernel read/write, including callback, minifilter, and ETW-related targets. It is frequently referenced by threat research because it connects generic BYOVD primitives to the exact kernel structures defenders depend on."],
    ["Hunting Vulnerable Kernel Drivers", "https://blogs.vmware.com/security/2023/10/hunting-vulnerable-kernel-drivers.html", "Takahiro Haruyama / VMware TAU", "2023", 5, "WDM WDF vulnerable driver hunting IDAPython firmware kernel memory", "Builds an IDAPython-assisted pipeline for triaging both WDM and WDF drivers, then applies it to roughly 18,000 samples and validates 34 vulnerable driver families. The article explains device ACL filtering, firmware and MSR access, kernel read/write primitives, exploit development, reporting, and the limits of blocklist-based BYOVD defenses."],
    ["Driver-Based Attacks: Past and Present", "https://www.rapid7.com/blog/post/2021/12/13/driver-based-attacks-past-and-present/", "Jake Baines / Rapid7", "2021", 5, "BYOVD Dell DBUtil PPL LSA protection driver blocklist", "Connects historical in-the-wild driver abuse to a concrete exploitation of Dell DBUtilDrv2, using kernel writes to change process protection and expose LSASS. It also compares unsigned-driver loaders, explains why administrative-only access does not remove BYOVD value, and records practical detection and mitigation options."],
    ["Screwed Drivers: Signed, Sealed, Delivered", "https://eclypsium.com/blog/screwed-drivers-signed-sealed-delivered/", "Eclypsium", "2019", 5, "signed vulnerable drivers firmware physical memory port IO BYOVD", "The original long-form publication behind Eclypsium's cross-vendor driver corpus, showing how legitimate hardware utilities expose privileged physical-memory, model-specific register, port-I/O, and firmware capabilities. It frames the recurring design failure and explains why valid signatures can turn vendor maintenance components into reusable kernel-entry paths."],
    ["Mother of All Drivers", "https://eclypsium.com/research/mother-of-all-drivers-new-vulnerabilities-found-in-windows-drivers/", "Eclypsium", "2019", 4, "Windows drivers firmware update arbitrary kernel access vendor research", "Extends the Screwed Drivers investigation with additional affected vendors and driver families, tracing weak access control and hardware-facing interfaces into kernel compromise and firmware risk. The report is useful for comparing recurring vulnerable patterns across otherwise unrelated OEM update and diagnostic utilities."],
    ["Screwed Drivers Open ATMs to Attack", "https://eclypsium.com/research/screwed-drivers-open-atms-to-attack/", "Eclypsium", "2020", 4, "ATM POS vulnerable driver port IO PCI firmware persistence", "Applies vulnerable-driver analysis to Windows-based ATM and point-of-sale systems, identifying a signed driver that exposes arbitrary x86 port I/O and a path toward PCI and firmware manipulation. It adds operational context around legacy Windows fleets, vendor update constraints, physical access, and long-lived blocklist gaps."],
    ["facebook-media Driver Kernel LPE", "https://github.com/Haider303/facebook-media-driver-exploit", "Haider Mustafa", "2026", 4, "facebook-media driver virtual physical memory read write token steal", "A compact source exploit for a signed driver exposing kernel virtual reads and physical-memory reads and writes through three unvalidated IOCTLs. It walks active EPROCESS objects, translates the available primitives into a SYSTEM-token replacement, records build-dependent structure offsets, and keeps the driver contract visible for independent review."],
    ["WinNotify.sys Arbitrary Kernel Read/Write", "https://github.com/Haider303/winnotify-exp", "Haider Mustafa", "2026", 4, "WinNotify signed driver low privilege arbitrary kernel read write token LPE", "Demonstrates a Microsoft-signed driver's world-accessible interface yielding arbitrary kernel reads and writes from a standard-user process. The source resolves the kernel base, traverses EPROCESS state, and replaces the caller's token on Windows 10 22H2, while clearly identifying the build-specific offsets that must be revalidated elsewhere."],
    ["BYOVD to the next level, part 2: reflective driver loading", "https://blog.quarkslab.com/exploiting-lenovo-driver-cve-2025-8061_part2.html", "Luis Casvella / Quarkslab", "2025", 5, "Lenovo BYOVD reflective driver loading kernel mapper DSE bypass", "Carries the LnvMSRIO primitives into a complete unsigned-driver mapping chain: temporary NtAddAtom patching for PASSIVE_LEVEL kernel API calls, nonpaged-pool allocation, PE relocation and import resolution, physical-memory copying, and entry-point invocation. The article also explains IRQL and PatchGuard constraints that simplistic mapper descriptions omit."],
    ["gdrv3.sys: thirteen signed-driver hardware primitives", "https://zonifer.dev/posts/byovd-kernel-driver-hardware-primitives.html", "Zonifer", "2026", 5, "gdrv3 Gigabyte BYOVD physical memory MSR kernel memcpy port IO", "Reverse engineers a signed Gigabyte driver into a concrete map of thirteen IOCTLs rather than stopping after the first exploitable call. The recovered surface includes physical-memory mapping, arbitrary kernel copying, model-specific-register access, raw port I/O, PCI configuration, and related hardware operations, with request layouts and missing authorization checks tied directly to BYOVD outcomes."],
    ["ThrottleStop CVE-2025-7771: physical memory to process internals", "https://www.poh0.dev/windows/driver/vulnerability/2025/09/22/throttlestop-vulnerable-driver/", "poh0", "2025", 5, "CVE-2025-7771 ThrottleStop physical memory Superfetch PFN VAD BYOVD", "Reconstructs ThrottleStop.sys device naming and METHOD_BUFFERED IOCTLs 0x80006498 and 0x8000649C for attacker-selected MmMapIoSpace reads and writes. The source-backed PoC then uses Superfetch PFN information for virtual-to-physical translation, locates EPROCESS state, and walks a target's VAD tree, demonstrating how a raw hardware primitive becomes useful cross-process memory access."],
    ["Vulnerable Driver Manipulation", "https://git.back.engineering/IDontCode/VDM/raw/tag/v1.3/VDM.pdf", "IDontCode / back.engineering", "2020", 5, "VDM vulnerable drivers physical memory page tables kernel function calls", "Develops a reusable abstraction for signed drivers that expose physical-memory mapping, including device and IOCTL discovery, buffer contracts, page-table traversal, virtual-memory reads and writes, and invocation of exported kernel routines. By applying the same exploitation architecture across multiple providers, the paper shows which pieces belong to the driver and which can be normalized into a portable BYOVD layer."],
    ["Bring Your Own Backdoor: how vulnerable drivers let hackers in", "https://blogs.vmware.com/security/2023/04/bring-your-own-backdoor-how-vulnerable-drivers-let-hackers-in.html", "Dana Behling / VMware TAU", "2023", 4, "BYOVD MSR IOCTL PnP firmware UEFI driver vulnerability taxonomy", "Builds a Windows-driver abuse taxonomy around attacker-controlled MSRs, unprotected IOCTLs, plug-and-play trust, firmware update paths, and UEFI components. Each class is connected to concrete primitives such as LSTAR replacement or MmMapIoSpace writes, platform mitigations, and real campaign or CVE references, making the article a useful graph hub rather than a generic BYOVD definition."],
    ["Unveiling BYOVD Threats: a comprehensive analysis", "https://www.ndss-symposium.org/wp-content/uploads/2026-s1491-paper.pdf", "NDSS Symposium researchers", "2026", 5, "BYOVD empirical study vulnerable drivers IOCTL capabilities blocklists termdd", "Presents a large empirical study of vulnerable-driver abuse, validating which samples still load on modern Windows and classifying the privileged capabilities exposed through their interfaces. The paper connects driver provenance, IOCTL behavior, observed attacks, blocklist coverage, and detailed cases such as legacy termdd.sys abuse, providing evidence for ecosystem-level conclusions that individual reversals cannot support."],
  ]},
  { id: "ipc", kicker: "Map privileged conversations", title: "COM, RPC & ALPC", items: [
    ["Relaying Kerberos from DCOM OXID Resolving", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2024/04/relaying-kerberos-authentication-from.html", "James Forshaw", "2024", 5, "DCOM OXID resolver Kerberos relay SPN target information ADCS", "Extends DCOM authentication research by showing how a marshaled target-information suffix can decouple the hostname used for OXID communication from the SPN authenticated by Kerberos. The post develops the OBJREF, DNS, RPCSS, integrity, and ADCS constraints explicitly and validates the primitive against contemporary SilverPotato research."],
    ["Finding Running RPC Servers with NtObjectManager", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2022/06/finding-running-rpc-server-information.html", "James Forshaw", "2022", 5, "Windows RPC endpoint enumeration NtObjectManager ALPC RpcView attack surface", "Compares four ways to identify live Windows RPC interfaces: endpoint-mapper queries, service and module correlation, process inspection, and asking an endpoint for its registered interface IDs. The article documents the blind spots of every method and combines them into a practical NtObjectManager workflow for mapping real attack surface rather than merely parsing binaries."],
    ["How the Windows Firewall RPC Filter Works", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2021/08/how-windows-firewall-rpc-filter-works.html", "James Forshaw", "2021", 5, "Windows firewall RPC filter interface UUID endpoint protocol security", "Reverse engineers the Windows Firewall RPC filtering layer, explaining how rules match interfaces, procedures, endpoints, protocol sequences, authentication, and network profiles before traffic reaches an RPC server. The implementation-focused analysis is crucial for understanding why an apparently reachable TCP endpoint may still be blocked and how interface-specific exposure should be tested."],
    ["How to Secure a Windows RPC Server—and How Not To", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2021/08/how-to-secure-windows-rpc-server-and.html", "James Forshaw", "2021", 5, "Windows RPC server security descriptors authentication callbacks multiplexed endpoints", "Builds a precise security model for Windows RPC across endpoint ACLs, interface security descriptors, authentication levels, registration flags, callbacks, impersonation, and ad-hoc checks. It also explains endpoint multiplexing and unauthenticated transports, showing why a server can be exposed through a weaker binding even when one endpoint appears correctly secured."],
    ["Finding Windows RPC Clients Through Brute Force", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2018/11/finding-windows-rpc-client.html", "James Forshaw", "2018", 5, "Windows RPC client discovery NDR format strings MIDL reverse engineering", "Presents a reverse-engineering technique for locating statically linked or otherwise hidden Windows RPC client stubs by searching candidate NDR format strings and validating their surrounding structures. The method fills an important tooling gap because client implementations reveal privileged callback and coercion paths that server-only enumeration cannot discover."],
    ["Finding Interactive-User COM Objects", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2018/09/finding-interactive-user-com-objects_9.html", "James Forshaw", "2018", 5, "COM interactive user activation session token OleViewDotNet PowerShell", "Uses OleView.NET and PowerShell to identify COM classes whose activation escapes a service or noninteractive session and reaches the logged-on user's context. The article maps registration, launch behavior, session selection, marshaling, and security assumptions, turning an obscure COM activation mode into an auditable cross-session attack surface."],
    ["Offensive Windows IPC Internals 1: Named Pipes", "https://csandker.io/2021/01/10/Offensive-Windows-IPC-1-NamedPipes.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2021", 5, "Windows named pipes impersonation SQOS race condition IPC attack surface", "Explains named-pipe modes, overlapped I/O, security descriptors, client impersonation, SQOS, local-versus-remote semantics, and instance-creation races from an offensive perspective. The included client/server examples and kernel call-path discussion make it the foundational first part of Sandker's Windows IPC series."],
    ["Windows Bug Class: Trapped COM Objects with IDispatch", "https://projectzero.google/2025/01/windows-bug-class-accessing-trapped-com.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2025", 5, "COM IDispatch ITypeInfo trapped object PPL code execution bug class", "Defines a cross-boundary bug class in which a remotely accessible object leaves dangerous helper objects trapped inside a privileged server, then demonstrates how IDispatch and type-library interfaces can instantiate in-process COM classes. The worked WaaSRemediation example reaches a PPL-Windows process and provides concrete hunting guidance rather than describing only one fixed CVE."],
    ["Insecure RpcEptMapper Registry Permissions", "https://itm4n.github.io/windows-registry-rpceptmapper-eop/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "RpcEptMapper RPC endpoint mapper registry permissions service security", "Documents an unexpected permission weakness in the RpcEptMapper service configuration and methodically maps what a low-privilege user can alter. The post is an excellent IPC case study because it connects registry security descriptors, shared service hosting, RPC infrastructure, and restart behavior before a separate follow-up develops the exploit."],
    ["Fuzzing Windows RPC with RpcView", "https://itm4n.github.io/fuzzing-windows-rpc-rpcview/", "itm4n", "2021", 5, "Windows RPC fuzzing RpcView interface reconstruction NDR harness", "Presents a practical workflow for turning RpcView's recovered interface metadata into callable and fuzzable Windows RPC clients. It covers bindings, procedure formats, parameter reconstruction, harness design, and failure diagnosis, providing a concrete bridge between endpoint enumeration and systematic attack-surface testing."],
    ["From RpcView to PetitPotam", "https://itm4n.github.io/from-rpcview-to-petitpotam/", "itm4n", "2021", 5, "PetitPotam EFSRPC NTLM coercion RpcView Windows authentication", "Retraces the discovery path from RPC interface inspection to the PetitPotam authentication-coercion primitive, including EFSRPC procedures, bindings, authentication behavior, and reachable server variants. The narrative is especially valuable as a discovery methodology: it shows how tooling output becomes a security hypothesis and then a reproducible protocol-level result."],
    ["Process Injection via COM IRundown::DoCallback", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2022/04/process-injection-via-component-object-model-com-irundowndocallback/", "MDSec", "2022", 5, "COM IRundown DoCallback process injection RPC threadless", "Develops an injection technique around the undocumented IRundown::DoCallback interface, COM marshaling, and an existing target thread rather than a conventional remote-thread creation API. The article traces its inspiration to Project Zero work, explains the interface and call path, and publishes implementation details suitable for defensive reproduction."],
    ["Windows Lateral Movement with DCOM", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2020/09/i-like-to-move-it-windows-lateral-movement-part-2-dcom/", "MDSec", "2020", 4, "DCOM lateral movement activation remote execution Windows", "A practical examination of DCOM-based lateral movement that goes beyond listing well-known CLSIDs by explaining activation, remote object use, authentication assumptions, and observable behavior. It is useful context for COM security research because it shows how the same infrastructure is operated across hosts during a real red-team workflow."],
    ["External C2 Through Internet Explorer COM Objects", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2019/02/external-c2-ie-com-objects-and-how-to-use-them-for-command-and-control/", "MDSec", "2019", 4, "Internet Explorer COM External C2 IPC command control", "Builds a custom command-and-control transport through Internet Explorer COM automation and Cobalt Strike's External C2 interface. The writeup exposes the COM object interactions and data path, making it a useful case study in repurposing a trusted Windows component rather than merely naming a living-off-the-land binary."],
    ["Calling Local Windows RPC Servers from .NET", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2019/12/calling-local-windows-rpc-servers-from.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2019", 5, "Windows local RPC .NET NDR client generation UAC bypass", "Introduces Project Zero's .NET RPC tooling by parsing local server metadata, generating strongly typed clients, selecting endpoints and authentication, and exercising a real UAC bypass from PowerShell. It turns opaque NDR interfaces into callable research targets while preserving enough protocol detail to understand what the generated client is doing."],
    ["Injecting Code into Windows Protected Processes Using COM, Part 1", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/10/injecting-code-into-windows-protected.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "COM PPL protected process code integrity KnownDlls injection", "Builds the background and first half of a Protected Process Light injection chain from Windows code-integrity policy, KnownDll handling, COM activation, and trust-level behavior. Paired with the follow-up exploit, it is one of the clearest demonstrations of COM as a security-boundary mechanism rather than merely an application automation technology."],
    ["Investigating Filter Communication Ports", "https://windows-internals.com/investigating-filter-communication-ports/", "Yarden Shafir", "2023", 5, "minifilter communication ports Filter Manager IPC security descriptors", "Reverse engineers the communication mechanism between filesystem minifilters and user-mode services, including Filter Manager port objects, connection state, messages, and access control. It fills an important IPC gap left by COM/RPC/ALPC material and provides a practical basis for auditing privileged filter services and their trust assumptions."],
    ["Offensive Windows IPC Internals 3: ALPC", "https://csandker.io/2022/05/24/Offensive-Windows-IPC-3-ALPC.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2022", 5, "ALPC ports messages attributes impersonation mapped views heap spray", "A systematic explanation of ALPC port relationships, message flow, attributes, security descriptors, impersonation, and resource-lifetime attack surface. It includes a working client/server laboratory and concrete methods for finding accessible ports and vulnerable high-privilege servers."],
    ["Debugging and Reversing ALPC", "https://csandker.io/2022/05/29/Debugging-And-Reversing-ALPC.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2022", 5, "ALPC WinDbg kernel debugging port objects reversing", "A practical companion that traces ALPC from user-mode calls into kernel objects with WinDbg. Read it after the IPC overview to learn how to verify undocumented behavior rather than relying on diagrams or stale structure definitions."],
    ["Injecting code into Windows Protected Processes using COM", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/11/injecting-code-into-windows-protected.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "COM PPL protected process IDispatch ALPC injection", "Shows how COM marshaling and exposed automation interfaces can become an injection path into Protected Process Light targets. The research is exemplary because it develops the object and transport mechanics, exploit constraints, and mitigations rather than presenting COM as a registry trick."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Relaying DCOM Authentication", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2021/10/windows-exploitation-tricks-relaying.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "DCOM Kerberos relay OXID resolver RPC ALPC authentication", "Dissects DCOM activation, OXID resolution, RPC bindings, and authentication to construct a local Kerberos relay primitive. It is required reading for understanding the protocol machinery behind coercion and relay families instead of treating them as opaque Potato variants."],
    ["OleView.NET", "https://github.com/tyranid/oleviewdotnet", "James Forshaw", "Living", 5, "COM RPC inspection activation marshaling security tooling", "A comprehensive .NET suite for enumerating, inspecting, activating, and security-testing COM and RPC infrastructure. Its parsers, viewers, scripting model, and database make it both a daily research tool and executable documentation of COM internals."],
    ["Offensive Windows IPC Internals 2: RPC", "https://csandker.io/2021/02/21/Offensive-Windows-IPC-2-RPC.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2021", 5, "RPC interfaces endpoints authentication impersonation attack surface", "Builds an offensive mental model of Windows RPC from interface definitions and bindings through authentication and impersonation. It is particularly useful before COM research because it exposes the transport and server assumptions that COM normally hides."],
    ["Named Pipe Secure Prefixes", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2017/11/named-pipe-secure-prefixes.html", "James Forshaw", "2017", 5, "NPFS named pipe squatting secure prefixes SeTcbPrivilege SDDL", "Reverse engineers the undocumented NPFS prefix objects that prevent low-privilege processes from squatting a privileged service's pipe name. The article follows NtCreateNamedPipeFile into the driver, identifies the SeTcbPrivilege gate and prefix DACL checks, documents SMSS-created protected namespaces, and shows how lifetime is tied to open handles."],
    ["Windows Tooling Updates: OleView.NET", "https://projectzero.google/2024/12/windows-tooling-updates-oleviewnet.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2024", 5, "OleView.NET COM proxy RPC ALPC OXID NDR tooling", "Documents major OleView.NET research improvements for reconstructing COM proxies, parsing type information, and invoking interfaces over RPC. The post explains ORPCTHIS/ORPCTHAT, ALPC-specific transport fields, OXID resolution, IRpcChannelBuffer reuse, activation, and the practical compromises required to make undocumented COM calls reliable."],
    ["Exploiting a Leaked Thread Handle", "https://projectzero.google/2016/03/exploiting-leaked-thread-handle.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2016", 5, "MS16-032 Secondary Logon RPC thread handle leak token SYSTEM", "Analyzes MS16-032 in the Secondary Logon service, where an RPC process-creation path leaks a highly privileged thread handle across the security boundary. The article then develops non-memory-corruption exploitation around thread context, impersonation, token state, and process creation, showing how a single object capability can be equivalent to code execution."],
    ["Calling Local Windows RPC Servers from .NET", "https://projectzero.google/2019/12/calling-local-windows-rpc-servers-from.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2019", 5, "Local RPC ALPC NDR managed client UAC NtApiDotNet", "Builds a pure managed path from extracting RPC metadata out of Windows binaries through NDR marshaling and direct ALPC transport, then applies it to a previously undocumented UAC bypass. The worked PowerShell flow shows interface selection, endpoint-mapper lookup, client generation, binding, and invocation without hiding the protocol behind a native proxy DLL."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Spoofing Named Pipe Client PID", "https://projectzero.google/2019/09/windows-exploitation-tricks-spoofing.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2019", 5, "named pipe NPFS client PID spoofing SMB2 impersonation", "Reverse engineers how NPFS derives client PID and session metadata from extended attributes and demonstrates why a named-pipe server must not treat that identity as authoritative. It covers direct EA injection on older systems, local SMB's fixed ProcessId field, PID cycling, version boundaries, and the exact security-check patterns that become exploitable."],
    ["Internet Explorer EPM Sandbox Escape CVE-2014-6350", "https://projectzero.google/2014/12/internet-explorer-epm-sandbox-escape.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2014", 5, "DCOM COM marshaling EPM sandbox escape OBJREF memory disclosure", "Develops an unusual Enhanced Protected Mode escape through COM and DCOM rather than a conventional broker call. The write-up explains marshaled interface pointers, remote object references, activation across integrity boundaries, and how a companion memory disclosure supplies the address knowledge needed to convert the COM behavior into code execution."],
    ["Sharing a Logon Session a Little Too Much", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2020/04/sharing-logon-session-little-too-much.html", "James Forshaw", "2020", 5, "NETWORK SERVICE logon session SMB named pipe impersonation RPCSS token", "Shows that loopback SMB authentication by a NETWORK SERVICE process can yield an impersonation token carrying the service SID state of RPCSS, because LSASS associates the logon session with its first token. A named-pipe server and NtObjectManager experiments turn that subtle token-sharing behavior into full access to the otherwise protected RPCSS process, clearly exposing the boundary and its prerequisites."],
    ["Device Guard on Windows 10 S: Executing Arbitrary Code", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2017/07/dg-on-windows-10-s-executing-arbitrary.html", "James Forshaw", "2017", 5, "Windows 10 S Device Guard named pipe .NET Remoting BinaryFormatter code execution", "Breaks the Windows 10 S application policy by targeting AddInProcess.exe, whose named-pipe .NET Remoting channel accepts Full TypeFilterLevel BinaryFormatter messages. The article reconstructs the IPC URI and wire format, generates a serialized request offline, then finds an allowed scriptlet and FileSystemObject path to write raw exploit bytes into the pipe despite command and scripting restrictions."],
    ["Stupid Is as Stupid Does with .NET Remoting", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2014/11/stupid-is-as-stupid-does-when-it-comes.html", "James Forshaw", "2014", 5, ".NET Remoting IpcChannel named pipe BinaryFormatter TypeFilterLevel exploit", "Analyzes a privileged local .NET Remoting service whose IpcChannel is marked secure but exposes a Full TypeFilterLevel formatter over a predictable named pipe. The post separates transport authentication from object-deserialization safety, reconstructs the service URI and formatter sink chain, and develops the reusable exploitation approach that later Windows policy bypasses build upon."],
  ]},
  { id: "execution", kicker: "Follow execution into memory", title: "APC, Loaders & Injection", items: [
    ["Delegated NT DLL Callback Table", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2024/02/13/delegated-nt-dll/", "modexp", "2024", 5, "DelegatedNtdll LdrpDelegatedNtdllExports callback table WoW64 hooks", "Documents the delegated NTDLL export table introduced in modern Windows and shows how its function pointers provide callback interception in 32-bit compatibility paths without inline code modification. The post identifies architecture-specific DLL locations, symbol names, table layout, protection assumptions, and a discovery proof of concept useful for both implant and hook-integrity research."],
    ["Windows ARM64 Shellcode", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2024/09/16/windows_arm64/", "modexp", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 ARM64 shellcode AArch64 PEB API hashing COM IStream", "Builds Windows ARM64 shellcode from the calling convention and toolchain upward, covering TEB/PEB traversal, export parsing, API hashing, COM interface invocation, HTTP streaming, allocation, and payload execution. Complete AArch64 assembly and structure definitions make this a rare primary reference for payload engineering beyond the dominant x64 architecture."],
    ["Process Injection via Command Line and Environment", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2020/07/31/wpi-cmdline-envar/", "modexp", "2020", 5, "Windows process injection command line environment PEB window title shellcode", "Explores process creation fields as covert shellcode carriers by placing payloads in command-line, environment, and window-title storage, locating them through the remote PEB, changing protection, and redirecting an existing callback to execute. The comparative implementations expose both the native data layout and the operational artifacts each variant leaves."],
    ["Process Injection by Breaking BaDDEr", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2019/08/09/windows-process-injection-breaking-badder/", "modexp", "2019", 5, "Windows DDE DDEML explorer process injection callbacks shellcode", "Reverse engineers Dynamic Data Exchange servers hosted by Explorer and repurposes DDEML transaction and callback behavior as a process-injection route. The post covers server enumeration, internal structures, memory placement, callable function-pointer selection, and the technique's narrow target constraints rather than marketing DDE as a universal injection primitive."],
    ["In-Memory Script Execution Shellcode", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2019/07/21/inmem-exec-script/", "modexp", "2019", 5, "Windows shellcode JavaScript VBScript JScript XSL ActiveScript in memory", "Implements position-independent Windows shellcode that hosts Active Scripting engines and executes JavaScript, VBScript, JScript, or XSL content directly from memory. The article develops COM initialization, interface discovery, script-site callbacks, language selection, error handling, and compact assembly, providing unusually transparent coverage of script hosting without launching a script interpreter."],
    ["In-Memory DLL Execution Shellcode", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2019/06/24/inmem-exec-dll/", "modexp", "2019", 5, "Windows reflective DLL loader shellcode PE relocations imports TLS memory", "Constructs a compact in-memory PE DLL loader in shellcode, handling headers, section mapping, relocations, import resolution, memory protections, TLS callbacks, and entry-point invocation. Because each loader responsibility is shown in source and tied to PE structures, the post is a strong implementation reference rather than another wrapper around LoadLibrary."],
    ["Loading .NET Assemblies from Shellcode", "https://modexp.wordpress.com/2019/05/10/dotnet-loader-shellcode/", "modexp", "2019", 5, "Windows .NET CLR hosting shellcode ICLRRuntimeHost assembly memory", "Builds native shellcode that discovers and hosts the CLR, loads a managed assembly from memory, resolves its entry point, marshals arguments, and invokes it without powershell.exe. The article exposes the COM interfaces and runtime-version decisions behind managed execution, making it useful for auditing later loaders that inherit the same CLR-hosting pattern."],
    ["How .NET Executables Are Loaded", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/dotnet-executable-load/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2019", 5, ".NET executable loader _CorExeMain PE CLR bootstrap Windows internals", "Traces Windows loading of a managed executable from the PE entry stub and mscoree import through _CorExeMain, CLR initialization, metadata inspection, and transfer to managed Main. Debugger experiments and patching demonstrations clarify the native-to-managed boundary that in-memory loaders and process-injection techniques deliberately reproduce or bypass."],
    ["A Beginner's Guide to Windows Shellcode Execution Techniques", "https://csandker.io/2019/07/24/ABeginnersGuideToWindowsShellcodeExecutionTechniques.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2019", 4, "Windows shellcode execution VirtualAlloc CreateThread callbacks APC fibers", "Compares multiple Windows shellcode execution paths through their allocation, memory-protection, and control-transfer APIs, giving newcomers concrete implementations to inspect side by side. Its value is the structured progression from a byte buffer to execution and the visibility of each native call, though readers should pair it with current telemetry research."],
    ["VBA RunPE, Part 1", "https://itm4n.github.io/vba-runpe-part1/", "itm4n", "2018", 5, "VBA RunPE process hollowing PE loader Windows API Office", "Builds a RunPE-style loader in VBA from first principles, covering PE parsing, target-process creation, remote memory layout, relocation-sensitive image placement, and thread-context manipulation. It is a useful execution reference because the restricted language forces every native boundary and structure to be made explicit."],
    ["VBA RunPE, Part 2", "https://itm4n.github.io/vba-runpe-part2/", "itm4n", "2018", 5, "VBA RunPE process hollowing relocations imports 64-bit Windows", "Completes the VBA loader by addressing the architectural and PE details left by the initial proof of concept, including robust structure handling and execution transfer. Together the two parts provide an unusually transparent process-hollowing implementation whose constraints are easier to audit than those of an opaque dropper."],
    ["Reinventing PowerShell in C/C++", "https://itm4n.github.io/reinventing-powershell/", "itm4n", "2025", 5, "PowerShell CLR hosting C++ automation assembly in memory execution", "Reconstructs PowerShell-like execution through native CLR hosting rather than launching powershell.exe, mapping runtime initialization, assembly loading, runspace or automation integration, and output handling. The article is strong execution research because it explains the managed-native boundary and operational tradeoffs instead of presenting only a detection-evasion wrapper."],
    ["Nighthawk 0.1: Memory and Thread Tradecraft", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2021/12/nighthawk-0-1-new-beginnings/", "MDSec", "2021", 5, "Windows process injection section mapping APC ETW-TI callbacks", "Documents the memory allocation, section mapping, thread selection, APC delivery, and cleanup design behind a modern Windows command-and-control implant. The value is in the explicit sequence of native APIs and telemetry considerations, which lets readers reason about both the implementation and the signals created at each stage."],
    ["Nighthawk 0.2: Catch Us If You Can", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2022/05/nighthawk-0-2-catch-us-if-you-can/", "MDSec", "2022", 5, "Windows in memory execution sleep obfuscation injection syscall", "Expands the earlier Nighthawk execution model with new in-memory and evasion research, discussing how payload state, sleep behavior, system calls, and execution transitions are managed. It is best read as an engineering update that records which operational assumptions changed when the implant met newer endpoint telemetry."],
    ["Detecting and Advancing In-Memory .NET Tradecraft", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2020/06/detecting-and-advancing-in-memory-net-tradecraft/", "MDSec", "2020", 5, ".NET CLR in memory execution assemblies detection Windows", "Analyzes how in-memory .NET execution appears inside a Windows process and develops techniques alongside the defensive observations that reveal them. By treating CLR loading, assemblies, memory artifacts, and telemetry together, it gives both operators and analysts a more durable model than a single reflective-loading proof of concept."],
    ["IIS Raid: Backdooring IIS with Native Modules", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2020/02/iis-raid-backdooring-iis-using-native-modules/", "MDSec", "2020", 5, "IIS native module backdoor request pipeline Windows execution", "Implements an IIS backdoor as a native module and explains registration, request-pipeline integration, command handling, and response behavior. The article is strong Windows execution research because it derives persistence and code execution from the server's supported extension architecture while exposing concrete configuration and forensic artifacts."],
    ["Payload Generation with CACTUSTORCH", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2017/07/payload-generation-with-cactustorch/", "MDSec", "2017", 4, "DotNetToJScript Windows script COM CLR payload execution", "Explains a payload-generation framework built on DotNetToJScript, connecting script hosts, COM activation, CLR bootstrap, and in-memory assembly execution. Although older, it remains useful for understanding the mechanics behind a major family of Windows script-based loaders and the trust transitions defenders monitor."],
    ["Thread and Process State Change", "https://windows-internals.com/thread-and-process-state-change/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "NtChangeProcessState NtChangeThreadState process thread state objects", "Investigates the newer process and thread state-change objects and the native APIs that operate on them, tracing their kernel implementation and supported actions. The article provides rare documentation for mechanisms that influence suspension, resumption, and process lifecycle outside the familiar Win32 wrappers, which is useful for both tooling and telemetry research."],
    ["Deferred Procedure Waits in Windows", "https://windows-internals.com/dpws-are-the-new-dpcs-deferred-procedure-waits-in-windows-10-21h1/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "deferred procedure waits DPW DPC Windows kernel scheduling", "Introduces Deferred Procedure Waits from their undocumented structures and scheduler paths, contrasting them with conventional DPC execution. The research is useful for understanding new kernel execution contexts, synchronization semantics, and the forensic or security implications of work that does not fit older DPC-centric mental models."],
    ["APC Series: User APC API", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/apc/user-apc/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2020", 5, "APC QueueUserAPC NtQueueApcThread alertable waits", "The correct entry point to a three-part APC series, establishing delivery rules, alertable waits, queueing APIs, and observable behavior. It replaces the usual copy-paste injection explanation with a precise execution model that remains useful for both offensive code and detection."],
    ["APC Series: User APC Internals", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/apc/kernel-user-apc-api/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2020", 5, "KAPC KiDeliverApc kernel user APC internals", "Reverse engineers the kernel path behind user APC objects, queueing, state transitions, and delivery to user mode. This is the piece to read when an APC PoC behaves differently across thread states and you need to reason from kernel implementation rather than API documentation."],
    ["APC Series: KiUserApcDispatcher and WoW64", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/apc/wow64-user-apc/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2020", 5, "KiUserApcDispatcher WoW64 APC injection Heaven's Gate", "Explains the dispatcher calling convention, NtContinue loop, and the 32/64-bit compatibility machinery used to deliver APCs into WoW64 processes. The cross-architecture injection analysis is unusually detailed and exposes monitoring pitfalls around encoded APC routines."],
    ["WoW64 Internals", "https://wbenny.github.io/2018/11/04/wow64-internals.html", "wbenny", "2018", 5, "WoW64 syscall transition turbo thunk Heaven's Gate internals", "A rigorous map of WoW64 process architecture, system-call transitions, generated thunks, and CPU-mode changes. It is foundational for debugging cross-architecture loaders and understanding why injection code that works in native x64 can fail inside WoW64."],
    ["Reflective DLL Injection", "https://github.com/stephenfewer/ReflectiveDLLInjection", "Stephen Fewer", "Living", 5, "reflective DLL loader PE relocations imports injection", "The original implementation that popularized loading a DLL from memory without the normal LoadLibrary path. Study it as a historical baseline for relocation, import resolution, and self-location, then compare its memory artifacts with modern loader and EDR research."],
    ["PE-sieve", "https://github.com/hasherezade/pe-sieve", "Hasherezade", "Living", 5, "malware scanner hollowing implants PE reconstruction memory", "A mature scanner for injected, replaced, and manually mapped PE images, shellcode, hooks, and in-memory patches. Its code and companion tools are excellent references for learning what imperfect loaders leave behind and how defenders reconstruct those artifacts."],
    ["Overview of Windows Execution Aliases", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/09/overview-of-windows-execution-aliases.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "App Execution Alias IO_REPARSE_TAG_APPEXECLINK CreateProcess AppX token", "Reverse engineers the zero-byte executables in WindowsApps as IO_REPARSE_TAG_APPEXECLINK objects handled specially by CreateProcess. It reconstructs the serialized alias format, AppInfo RPC activation-token creation, packaged-app launch flow, trust labels, and a file-switching TOCTOU that bypasses one Desktop Bridge eligibility check."],
    ["DLL Import Redirection in Windows 10", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2020/02/dll-import-redirection-in-windows-10_8.html", "James Forshaw", "2020", 5, "import redirection NTDLL loader AppX NtCreateUserProcess signing level image section", "Uncovers Windows' undocumented import-redirection table for packaged applications and reconstructs its process-parameter, manifest, loader, and forwarding structures. The post then escapes the intended packaging boundary by combining NtCreateUserProcess with a cached image-section/signing-level mismatch, demonstrating why loader features must validate file identity across every open."],
    ["Bypassing CIG Through KnownDlls", "https://www.tiraniddo.dev/2019/08/windows-code-injection-bypassing-cig.html", "James Forshaw", "2019", 5, "Code Integrity Guard KnownDlls section object symbolic link process injection", "Develops a code-injection path against Code Integrity Guard by studying how KnownDll section objects are selected and mapped during process startup. The research connects object-manager namespaces, section creation, image-signing policy, process creation, and loader timing into a concrete bypass while clearly bounding the privileges and target configuration it requires."],
    ["Exploiting Arbitrary Object Directory Creation", "https://projectzero.google/2018/08/windows-exploitation-tricks-exploiting.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "Object Manager KnownDlls DefineDosDevice CSRSS section DLL loading LPE", "Turns an arbitrary Object Manager directory primitive into SYSTEM by chaining CSRSS's BaseSrvDefineDosDevice RPC behavior, permanent symbolic links, KnownDll section lookup, and a privileged service's DLL load. The article is a model of finding an execution sink for a namespace bug and carefully preserving raced objects with handles."],
    ["Process Hollowing on Windows 11 24H2", "https://hshrzd.wordpress.com/2025/01/27/process-hollowing-on-windows-11-24h2/", "Hasherezade", "2025", 5, "Windows 11 24H2 process hollowing hotpatch MEM_PRIVATE MEM_IMAGE HVCI", "Root-causes why classic RunPE fails during process initialization on Windows 11 24H2: the hotpatch loader queries MemoryImageExtensionInformation on a MEM_PRIVATE implant, and HVCI adds an NtManageHotPatch failure. The article supplies narrowly scoped NTDLL patches, explains instruction-cache timing, and compares section-backed alternatives that preserve MEM_IMAGE semantics."],
    ["Process Doppelgänging", "https://hshrzd.wordpress.com/2017/12/18/process-doppelganging-a-new-way-to-impersonate-a-process/", "Hasherezade", "2017", 5, "process doppelganging NTFS transactions NtCreateSection NtCreateProcessEx PE loader", "Explains and implements process impersonation by writing an executable inside an NTFS transaction, creating an image section from the modified view, rolling back the file, and constructing a process through native APIs. The comparison with hollowing makes clear which PE mapping work is delegated to the Windows loader, which PEB and thread steps remain, and which disk-memory mismatches support detection."],
    ["Process Ghosting: executable image tampering", "https://www.elastic.co/blog/process-ghosting-a-new-executable-image-tampering-attack", "Gabriel Landau / Elastic Security", "2021", 5, "process ghosting delete pending image section tampering Defender detection", "Introduces Process Ghosting by placing a payload into a delete-pending file, creating an executable image section, closing the file so its name disappears, and only then creating the process. The original disclosure compares exact API ordering with Hollowing, Doppelgänging, and Herpaderping, demonstrates interference with pre-execution scanning, and derives FILE_OBJECT-based detection signals."],
    ["EDR Parallel-asis through Analysis", "https://www.mdsec.co.uk/2022/01/edr-parallel-asis-through-analysis/", "MDSec", "2022", 5, "Windows parallel loader ntdll syscall copies unhooking process initialization", "Reverse engineers the Windows 10 parallel DLL loader after unexpected startup threads reveal temporary copies of native syscall stubs created before ordinary application execution. The research uses those clean stubs to recover syscall numbers and map an unhooked NTDLL, connecting loader concurrency and initialization timing to a concrete execution and instrumentation primitive."],
  ]},
  { id: "malware", kicker: "Reverse real tradecraft", title: "Windows Malware & Loader Analysis", items: [
    ["Signed Driver Malware Moves Up the Trust Chain", "https://www.sophos.com/en-us/blog/signed-driver-malware-moves-up-the-software-trust-chain", "Sophos X-Ops", "2022", 5, "BURNTCIGAR signed malicious driver WHCP EDR killer Cuba ransomware", "Reverse engineers BURNTCIGAR's loader and kernel driver after an attempted security-product shutdown, mapping the KApcHelper device, process-kill IOCTLs, VMProtect packing, signer evolution, and target list. The report is essential for understanding the shift from merely vulnerable signed drivers to attacker-built malware carrying legitimate WHCP signatures."],
    ["AuKill Abuses the Process Explorer Driver", "https://www.sophos.com/en-us/blog/aukill-edr-killer-malware-abuses-process-explorer-driver", "Sophos X-Ops", "2023", 5, "AuKill Process Explorer driver BYOVD EDR killer ransomware", "Analyzes AuKill's use of a legitimate Process Explorer driver to acquire privileged process handles and terminate endpoint products before ransomware deployment. The report follows the loader, service setup, driver-client protocol, protected target handling, observed incidents, and detection opportunities, making the operational chain directly useful to both reversers and defenders."],
    ["BURNTCIGAR 2: Driver-Based Attack Tool Update", "https://www.sophos.com/en-us/blog/burnt-cigar-2", "Sophos X-Ops", "2024", 5, "BURNTCIGAR 2 Poortry malicious driver EDR killer Windows crash", "Revisits the BURNTCIGAR/Poortry driver family as its developers expand process and file manipulation while changing signatures and deployment behavior. Static and incident analysis explain how newer variants impair protected endpoints and sometimes destabilize Windows, providing a version-aware continuation of the original signed-driver investigation."],
    ["DeadLock Ransomware's New BYOVD Loader", "https://blog.talosintelligence.com/byovd-loader-deadlock-ransomware/", "Cisco Talos", "2025", 5, "DeadLock ransomware BYOVD loader vulnerable driver EDR disable", "Dissects a newly observed loader used before DeadLock ransomware, including its vulnerable-driver deployment, privileged device interactions, security-product disruption, and handoff to the Windows encryptor. The report preserves samples, execution stages, behavioral indicators, and campaign context instead of treating the driver as an isolated IOC."],
    ["RedDriver: Undocumented Driver-Based Browser Hijacker", "https://blog.talosintelligence.com/undocumented-reddriver/", "Cisco Talos", "2023", 5, "RedDriver malicious Windows driver browser hijacker packet filtering China", "Reverse engineers an undocumented, signed Windows driver used to hijack browser traffic against Chinese-speaking users and internet cafés. The analysis follows installation, device communication, filtering and redirection behavior, certificates, supporting components, and network indicators, making it a rare study of kernel-assisted traffic manipulation outside ransomware."],
    ["ThrottleStop Driver AV Killer", "https://securelist.com/av-killer-exploiting-throttlestop-sys/117026/", "Kaspersky GReAT", "2025", 5, "ThrottleStop.sys AV killer physical memory shellcode kernel BYOVD", "Analyzes an AV-killer that abuses the legitimate ThrottleStop driver for physical-memory access, translates kernel targets, and installs shellcode to terminate security processes. The report includes the user-mode loader, vulnerable IOCTL path, kernel function modifications, PatchGuard considerations, YARA detection, and exact artifacts needed for defensive reproduction."],
    ["Hunting Attestation-Signed Malware", "https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/threat-intelligence/hunting-attestation-signed-malware/", "Mandiant", "2022", 5, "Windows attestation signed malicious drivers hunting certificates rootkits", "Develops a hunting methodology for malicious Windows drivers that passed Microsoft's attestation-signing process, joining certificate metadata, code similarity, submission patterns, and driver behavior. Multiple clusters and real investigations show how trust infrastructure can become a discovery pivot while avoiding the assumption that every signed kernel module is benign."],
    ["Targeted Attacks Leverage Microsoft-Signed Malicious Drivers", "https://www.sentinelone.com/labs/driving-through-defenses-targeted-attacks-leverage-signed-malicious-microsoft-drivers/", "SentinelLabs", "2022", 5, "Microsoft signed malicious driver EDR evasion SIM swapping Hive ransomware", "Documents multiple intrusions where Microsoft-signed malicious drivers and companion user-mode clients attempted to control or kill endpoint processes, including SIM-swapping operations and Hive ransomware deployment. Driver analysis, victimology, signer details, disclosure to MSRC, and ADV220005 context connect the samples to a wider failure mode in the signing pipeline."],
    ["BlackByte Removes EDR Kernel Callbacks", "https://www.sophos.com/en-us/blog/blackbyte-ransomware-returns", "Sophos X-Ops", "2022", 5, "BlackByte ransomware RTCore64 BYOVD kernel callbacks ETW TI", "Reverse engineers BlackByte's abuse of RTCore64.sys arbitrary kernel read/write to locate and erase process, thread, and image-load callbacks belonging to more than a thousand security drivers. It also covers ETW Threat Intelligence tampering, build-specific offsets, service installation, and code copied from EDRSandblast, creating a detailed bridge from public tooling to ransomware tradecraft."],
    ["AcidBox Repurposes a Turla Driver Exploit", "https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/acidbox-rare-malware/", "Unit 42", "2020", 5, "AcidBox Turla VirtualBox driver exploit Russian targets malware", "Reconstructs a rare malware family that repurposed a Turla-linked vulnerable-driver exploit against Russian organizations, tracing the delivery components, driver abuse, privilege transition, persistence, and encrypted communications. The analysis is valuable for comparing a public or previously attributed kernel technique with its implementation by a separate operational cluster."],
    ["WINTAPIX: Kernel Driver Backdoor", "https://www.fortinet.com/blog/threat-research/wintapix-kernal-driver-middle-east-countries", "FortiGuard Labs", "2023", 5, "WINTAPIX malicious kernel driver Donut shellcode Middle East backdoor", "Analyzes a signed Windows kernel driver targeting Middle Eastern organizations that embeds Donut-generated shellcode and acts as a loader, backdoor, and proxy. The report maps driver initialization, payload extraction, injection and communication behavior, certificate pivots, victim telemetry, and related variants while preserving concrete hunting indicators."],
    ["Shamoon the Wiper: Driver and Disk Destruction", "https://securelist.com/shamoon-the-wiper-further-details-part-ii/57784/", "Kaspersky GReAT", "2012", 5, "Shamoon wiper RawDisk driver MBR disk destruction Windows malware", "Provides a technical decomposition of Shamoon's destructive Windows components, including use of a signed RawDisk driver to bypass filesystem controls and overwrite disks. The report separates dropper, wiper, reporting, and driver interactions, records timestamps and artifacts, and remains foundational for studying how legitimate low-level storage software is repurposed for destructive malware."],
    ["CopperStealer: Password and Cookie Theft at Scale", "https://www.proofpoint.com/us/blog/threat-insight/now-you-see-it-now-you-dont-copperstealer-performs-widespread-theft", "Proofpoint", "2021", 4, "CopperStealer Windows malware browser credentials cookies Facebook Google accounts", "Profiles a rapidly evolving Windows credential stealer across more than eighty versions, covering browser database access, cookie and password theft, account targeting, persistence, distribution, C2 protocols, DGA changes, and sinkholing results. The longitudinal sample comparison makes it useful loader-and-malware analysis beyond a single campaign snapshot."],
    ["PARALLAX Loader and REF2731", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/exploring-the-ref2731-intrusion-set", "Elastic Security Labs", "2022", 5, "PARALLAX NETWIRE DLL sideloading Heaven's Gate direct syscalls injection", "Reconstructs a multi-stage Windows campaign from malicious document through MsiDb DLL side-loading, encrypted WAV shellcode, direct syscall recovery, Heaven's Gate, suspended-process injection, and NETWIRE delivery. The report connects each loader transition to concrete files, APIs, memory behavior, and public detections rather than treating the campaign as a list of indicators."],
    ["SHADOWPAD Loader in REF2924", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/update-to-the-REF2924-intrusion-set-and-related-campaigns", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 5, "SHADOWPAD Bitdefender DLL sideloading registry shellcode injection", "Analyzes a SHADOWPAD loader side-loaded by an old Bitdefender crash handler, including its encrypted companion data, registry storage, service persistence, process creation, and injection into Windows Media Player and dllhost. The article also follows shared code and campaign relationships, linking loader internals with operational deployment."],
    ["Elastic Analysis of the r77 Rootkit", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/elastic-security-labs-steps-through-the-r77-rootkit", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 5, "r77 rootkit API hooks process hollowing registry PowerShell named pipe", "Walks through r77's installer, .NET stager, service, and injected core modules, covering registry-hosted payloads, scheduled tasks, AMSI patching, process hollowing, DLL unhooking, named-pipe coordination, and Native API filtering. Detection rules and YARA are published alongside the code analysis, supporting both reproduction and hunting."],
    ["LOBSHOT hVNC Malware", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/elastic-security-labs-discovers-lobshot-malware", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 5, "LOBSHOT hVNC malvertising dynamic imports explorer parent evasion", "A full analysis of a previously undocumented hVNC family distributed through convincing Google Ads and installers. It covers dynamic API resolution, Defender emulation checks, process ancestry breaking, persistence, desktop interaction, configuration extraction, infrastructure pivots, and detections, providing a complete view from delivery to interactive fraud capability."],
    ["XWORM and AGENTTESLA Loader Chain", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/attack-chain-leads-to-xworm-and-agenttesla", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 4, "XWORM AGENTTESLA RTF PowerShell .NET process hollowing AMSI", "Traces a weaponized document through a remotely fetched RTF, Excel macro, obfuscated PowerShell, and custom .NET loader into XWORM or AGENTTESLA. The loader analysis documents AMSI patching, suspended trusted processes, ZwUnmapViewOfSection, image replacement, and payload-specific configuration with published YARA rules."],
    ["SUDDENICON in the 3CX Supply-Chain Attack", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/elastic-users-protected-from-suddenicon-supply-chain-attack", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 5, "3CX SUDDENICON supply chain ffmpeg DLL shellcode GitHub C2", "A rapid but technically grounded triage of the compromised 3CX Windows client, showing how backdoored libraries locate and decrypt SUDDENICON, map it through shellcode, delay execution, recover C2 data from icon files, and fetch another payload. It includes behavioral queries and YARA while carefully distinguishing confirmed behavior from early assessment."],
    ["BLISTER Loader Evolution", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/blister-loader", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 5, "BLISTER loader manual mapping Heaven's Gate process hollowing unhooking", "Revisits BLISTER after the original campaign report and dissects its evolving x86 and x64 loader: custom API hashing, manual mapping, clean ntdll replacement, Heaven's Gate wrappers, Rabbit decryption, LZNT1 decompression, persistence, reflective execution, and process hollowing. A configuration extractor and detection artifacts make the analysis directly reproducible."],
    ["RONINGLOADER: DragonBreath's Path to PPL Abuse", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/roningloader", "Elastic Security Labs", "2025", 5, "RONINGLOADER PPL abuse signed driver WDAC thread pool injection", "Dissects a multi-stage Windows loader that combines a signed kernel driver, custom WDAC policy, PPL abuse, phantom DLLs, and thread-pool injection to suppress multiple security products before launching a gh0st RAT variant. The report connects installer stages, certificate pivots, kernel abuse, user-mode injection, and final payload behavior with public detections."],
    ["BRUSHWORM and BRUSHLOGGER", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/brushworm-targets-financial-services", "Elastic Security Labs", "2026", 4, "BRUSHWORM BRUSHLOGGER DLL sideloading keylogger USB propagation", "Analyzes a modular Windows backdoor and companion keylogger recovered from a financial-sector intrusion, including AES-encrypted configuration, scheduled-task persistence, removable-media propagation, extension-based theft, DLL side-loading, keyboard hooks, and iterative development samples. The straightforward code makes the article a useful study in reconstructing capability even when malware is not heavily obfuscated."],
    ["Defeating BazarLoader Anti-Analysis Techniques", "https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/bazarloader-anti-analysis-techniques/", "Unit 42", "2022", 5, "BazarLoader anti analysis API hashing control flow obfuscation debugger", "Turns BazarLoader's anti-analysis layers into a repeatable reversing workflow, with scripts and methods for recovering APIs, untangling execution, and neutralizing checks that impede static and dynamic analysis. The focus on reusable analyst techniques rather than campaign indicators makes it valuable beyond the specific malware family."],
    ["CL-UNK-1068 Windows Loader Operations", "https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/cl-unk-1068-targets-critical-sectors/", "Unit 42", "2026", 4, "Windows DLL side loading Python loader critical infrastructure malware", "Documents a long-running intrusion set's Windows tooling with detailed attention to Python-based DLL side-loading, malicious loaders, persistence, credential access, and operator utilities. The article provides enough sample and execution context to connect individual loader mechanics to a broader operational chain without reducing the analysis to indicators."],
    ["OXLOADER technical analysis", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/oxloader-malware-loader-infostealer", "Elastic Security Labs", "2026", 5, "loader reloc section self modifying MBA anti VM Donut", "A full analysis of a modern loader using CRT-initializer hijacking, self-modifying decryption stubs, control-flow obfuscation, sandbox checks, and .reloc section abuse. It follows execution into Donut-based in-memory delivery and includes detection artifacts, so the article supports both reversing and defensive validation."],
    ["Deep dive on the BLISTER loader", "https://www.elastic.co/blog/deep-dive-on-the-blister-loader", "Elastic Security Labs", "2021", 5, "BLISTER loader signed certificate embedded payload injection", "Analyzes a signed Windows loader that blends malicious logic into legitimate libraries, delays execution, decrypts embedded payloads, and injects them into trusted processes. The combination of loader mechanics, campaign context, and a public configuration extractor makes it a durable case study."],
    ["DarkGate Internals", "https://blog.sekoia.io/darkgate-internals/", "Sekoia.io", "2023", 5, "DarkGate loader APC injection NtTestAlert crypter malware", "Dissects DarkGate's multi-stage execution, configuration, crypter behavior, process injection, and use of NtTestAlert for APC delivery. It is a useful real-world counterpart to the APC internals series because the same mechanism is visible inside an operational malware family."],
    ["BITS and Bytes: analyzing BITSLOTH", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/bits-and-bytes-analyzing-bitsloth", "Elastic Security Labs", "2024", 5, "BITSLOTH Windows backdoor BITS C2 handlers reversing", "A careful reverse engineering of a Windows backdoor that uses BITS as its command-and-control channel and exposes dozens of task handlers. It demonstrates how native Windows services shape malware architecture and includes implementation-level details and detections."],
    ["P8LOADER and SPECTRALVIPER", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/elastic-charms-spectralviper", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 4, "P8LOADER manual PE mapping RuntimeBroker unbacked memory", "Documents an x64 loader that manually maps PE files from disk or memory and a modular backdoor deployed through it. The analysis is concise but valuable for connecting classic section mapping, relocations, and import resolution to the memory telemetry produced by a real intrusion."],
    ["Qilin ransomware and the hidden dangers of BYOVD", "https://blackpointcyber.com/blog/qilin-ransomware-and-the-hidden-dangers-of-byovd/", "Blackpoint Cyber", "2025", 5, "Qilin ransomware EDRSandblast Toshiba physical memory BYOVD", "Reconstructs a Qilin intrusion in which a sideloaded DLL deploys a customized EDRSandblast and an abused Toshiba driver. It follows byte-wise physical-memory IOCTLs through virtual-to-physical translation, a Beep.sys control-path overwrite, callback removal, and ETW tampering, tying kernel primitives to the surrounding ransomware operation."],
    ["Scattered Spider attempts BYOVD to avoid detection", "https://www.crowdstrike.com/en-us/blog/scattered-spider-attempts-to-avoid-detection-with-bring-your-own-vulnerable-driver-tactic/", "CrowdStrike Intelligence", "2023", 5, "Scattered Spider CVE-2015-2291 Intel driver EDR tampering", "Documents Scattered Spider using Intel's vulnerable iqvw64.sys driver to load attacker-controlled kernel code and patch security-product routines with trampoline hooks. The report connects product-specific offsets, stolen or test signing certificates, and concrete csagent.sys modifications to an observed intrusion campaign."],
    ["W-2: from malvertising to kernel-mode EDR kill", "https://www.huntress.com/blog/w2-malvertising-to-kernel-mode-edr-kill", "Anna Pham, Huntress", "2026", 5, "malvertising Havoc HwAudKiller Huawei driver IOCTL EDR", "Traces a Google Ads and rogue ScreenConnect intrusion into an in-memory EDR killer backed by a previously undocumented signed Huawei driver. The analysis identifies the Havoc service, device path, PID-taking IOCTL, unchecked ZwOpenProcess and ZwTerminateProcess flow, kill loop, target list, and host-level detection artifacts."],
    ["Killing me gently: inside Gentlemen's EDR killer framework", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/en/eset-research/killing-me-gently-inside-gentlemens-edr-killer-framework/", "Jakub Souček, ESET Research", "2026", 5, "Gentlemen ransomware EDR killer vulnerable drivers rootkits BYOVD", "Maps eight variants of the GentleKiller framework across abused NSecKrnl, Safetica, Zemana, Qihoo, IObit, and other drivers. By comparing shared masquerading and evasion layers with rapidly incorporated public PoCs, it shows how a ransomware affiliate maintains and evolves a modular kernel-tampering capability."],
    ["Embargo ransomware: Rock'n'Rust", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/en/eset-research/embargo-ransomware-rocknrust/", "Jan Holman and Tomáš Zvara, ESET Research", "2024", 5, "Embargo ransomware MS4Killer probmon minifilter Rust EDR", "Reverse engineers Embargo's Rust-based MDeployer, MS4Killer, and ransomware chain. It explains how a victim-tailored s4killer derivative decrypts and registers probmon.sys as a minifilter, communicates through FilterConnectCommunicationPort and FilterSendMessage, and repeatedly terminates selected security processes."],
    ["FINALDRAFT and PATHLOADER Technical Analysis", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/finaldraft", "Elastic Security Labs", "2025", 5, "FINALDRAFT PATHLOADER Microsoft Graph Outlook drafts C2 reflective loading", "Reverse engineers a Windows downloader and a previously undocumented espionage implant that turns Outlook draft messages into a command channel through Microsoft Graph. The report recovers PATHLOADER's embedded configuration and encrypted shellcode, then maps FINALDRAFT's reflective loading, API hashing, command handlers, token impersonation, network pivoting, and protocol structure with public configuration extractors and detections."],
    ["GHOSTPULSE's Pixel-Level Payload Storage", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/tricks-and-treats", "Elastic Security Labs", "2024", 5, "GHOSTPULSE HIJACKLOADER PNG pixels GDIPlus encrypted configuration payload", "Explains how a Windows loader evolved from hiding encrypted data in PNG IDAT chunks to reconstructing its configuration and payload from individual RGB pixel values through GDI+. The analysis documents the CRC32-scanned metadata structure, XOR decryption path, single-file resource packaging, and an updated extractor, making the steganographic implementation reproducible rather than merely describing the delivery campaign."],
    ["BUGHATCH Malware Analysis", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/bughatch-malware-analysis", "Elastic Security Labs", "2022", 5, "BUGHATCH reflective loader SeDebugPrivilege custom C2 protocol shellcode", "Walks from an obfuscated PowerShell and shellcode loader into the native BUGHATCH implant used in CUBA ransomware operations. It reconstructs reflective PE loading, privilege adjustment, host fingerprinting, thread synchronization, per-session XOR key generation, HTTP message framing, command dispatch, and several payload execution modes, with pseudocode and YARA that support hands-on reversing."],
    ["Thawing the Permafrost of ICEDID", "https://www.elastic.co/pdf/elastic-security-labs-thawing-the-permafrost-of-icedid.pdf", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 5, "ICEDID GZip loader bot payload configuration hooks browser proxy C2", "Provides an end-to-end reverse engineering report for a GZip-era ICEDID loader and bot instead of stopping at campaign telemetry. It follows staged decryption and persistence into the core implant, recovers configuration and command handling, and explains browser-proxy behavior, Windows API use, communications, and the tooling needed to extract actionable structure from samples."],
    ["BlackLotus UEFI Bootkit: Myth Confirmed", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2023/03/01/blacklotus-uefi-bootkit-myth-confirmed/", "Martin Smolár, ESET Research", "2023", 5, "BlackLotus UEFI bootkit Secure Boot CVE-2022-21894 HVCI winlogon", "Presents the first public end-to-end analysis of BlackLotus, from its installer and Baton Drop exploitation of CVE-2022-21894 through Machine Owner Key enrollment and persistent UEFI execution. It traces hooks across Windows Boot Manager, winload, the kernel, and security drivers, then explains the protected kernel component and winlogon-hosted HTTP downloader that survive on fully updated Windows 11 systems."],
    ["ESPecter: UEFI Threats Moving to the ESP", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2021/10/05/uefi-threats-moving-esp-introducing-especter-bootkit/", "Martin Smolár and Anton Cherepanov, ESET Research", "2021", 5, "ESPecter UEFI bootkit bootmgfw winload DSE kernel driver espionage", "Reverse engineers a real Windows bootkit that evolved from legacy MBR infection into a patched bootmgfw.efi implant on the EFI System Partition. The report follows integrity-check bypasses and detours through Boot Manager, winload, and ntoskrnl, shows how SepInitializeCodeIntegrity is patched to disable DSE, and continues into the unsigned driver, process injection, encrypted configuration, and user-mode espionage payloads."],
    ["NSPX30: An AitM-Enabled Implant Evolving Since 2005", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/en/eset-research/nspx30-sophisticated-aitm-enabled-implant-evolving-since-2005/", "Facundo Muñoz, ESET Research", "2024", 5, "NSPX30 Blackwood AitM loader orchestrator backdoor plugin evolution", "Reconstructs almost two decades of a Windows espionage platform from Project Wood and DCM to NSPX30 by comparing code, build artifacts, loaders, orchestrators, backdoors, and plugins across generations. The analysis explains its unusual on-path traffic interception delivery, multistage persistence, allowlisting against security products, encrypted configurations, C2 protocol, and modular collection capabilities with unusually rich historical sample evidence."],
    ["SprySOCKS for Windows and Its RawWNPF Rootkit", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/en/eset-research/fishmongers-arsenal-upgraded-sprysocks-windows/", "ESET Research", "2026", 5, "SprySOCKS Windows DriverLoader RawWNPF rootkit IOCTL network process hiding", "Dissects the Windows port of SprySOCKS together with a signed DriverLoader that decrypts and manually maps a second kernel component. The RawWNPF analysis enumerates its private IOCTL interface and follows InfinityHook-style NtQuerySystemInformation filtering, nsiproxy completion-routine hooks, process and connection hiding, file protection, encrypted configuration, and the differences between user-mode and driver-backed variants."],
  ]},
  { id: "cves", kicker: "Study complete cases", title: "CVE & Case Studies", items: [
    ["Exploiting Enterprise Backup Software: Part One", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/exploiting-enterprise-backup-software-for-privilege-escalation-part-one", "Alex Oudenaarden / Northwave", "2024", 5, "Macrium Reflect psmounterex kernel heap overflow OOB read driver", "Reverse engineers Macrium Reflect's psmounterex.sys after an automated crash and develops two complementary kernel-heap vulnerabilities: a state-corruption out-of-bounds read and a mount-manager-assisted out-of-bounds write. Part one carefully establishes the device exposure, request paths, allocation behavior, and constraints later used for exploitation."],
    ["Exploiting Enterprise Backup Software: Part Two", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/exploiting-enterprise-backup-software-for-privilege-escalation-part-two?hsLang=en", "Alex Oudenaarden / Northwave", "2024", 5, "Macrium Reflect segment heap token spray OOB read write LPE", "Turns the paired Macrium Reflect heap primitives into a reliable local privilege-escalation exploit on the modern segment heap. The authors use duplicated-token grooming, process-token placement, read-assisted heap reconnaissance, constrained allocation retries, and a precise SEP_TOKEN_PRIVILEGES overwrite while documenting why simpler sprays fail."],
    ["Ivanti/Pulse VPN Privilege Escalation Exploit", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/ivanti-pulse-vpn-privilege-escalation", "Alex Oudenaarden and Tijme Gommers", "2023", 5, "CVE-2023-38043 CVE-2023-35080 CVE-2023-38543 Ivanti kernel function call", "Develops three Ivanti Secure Access Client driver flaws into a constrained kernel-function-call chain through an exposed IOCTL and attacker-controlled IoCsqRemoveIrp state. The analysis handles CFG restrictions, post-call cleanup crashes, spin-lock behavior, and function selection instead of treating the primitive as an automatic path to SYSTEM."],
    ["VIVE VR Driver Out-of-Bounds Read", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/vive-vr-headset-kernel-driver-vulnerable-for-out-of-bounds-memory-read", "Tijme Gommers / Northwave", "2024", 4, "HTC VIVE ViveRRaudio IOCTL OOB kernel memory disclosure", "Audits HTC VIVE Business Streaming's world-accessible ViveRRaudio.sys device and identifies IOCTL 0x9C40240F copying a fixed test string with an attacker-controlled output length. The post reconstructs the dispatch path, MDL mapping, information-disclosure primitive, proof of concept, affected version, coordinated disclosure, and vendor patch."],
    ["CVE-2024-31757: TeraByte Kernel Handle Leak", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/vulnerability-notice-terabyte-image-for-windows", "Northwave Research", "2024", 4, "CVE-2024-31757 TBOFLHelper64 kernel handle leak privilege escalation", "Documents two low-privilege kernel-handle leaks in TeraByte Image for Windows' TBOFLHelper64.sys, caused by a device interface accessible to every local user. The original notice identifies affected hashes and versions, explains how leaked System-process handles can support elevation, and records the coordinated fix in version 4.0.0.0."],
    ["ADLINK PXI Physical-Memory Disclosure", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/vulnerability-notice-adlink-pxi-platform-services", "Northwave Research", "2024", 4, "ADLINK ADRMDRVSYS IOCTL physical memory LSASS disclosure", "Describes a world-accessible ADRMDRVSYS.sys interface in ADLINK PXI Platform Services whose IOCTL 0x2234D4 maps caller-selected physical memory into user space. The original advisory connects the primitive to sensitive-memory and LSASS disclosure, supplies affected versions and hashes, and preserves the vendor-coordination timeline."],
    ["CVE-2024-28519: eScan Kernel Handle Leak", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/vulnerability-notice-escan-antivirus", "Northwave Research", "2024", 4, "CVE-2024-28519 eScan ProcObsrvesx kernel handle leak LPE", "The original disclosure of a low-privilege kernel-handle leak in eScan Antivirus' ProcObsrvesx.sys, whose device is accessible to every local user. It identifies the affected driver version, relates the flaw to the component's process-handle operations and local elevation, and records coordinated remediation by Microworld Technologies."],
    ["CVE-2024-31756: MarvinTest Hw64 Handle Leak", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/vulnerability-notice-hardware-access-driver-marvintest-solutions", "Northwave Research", "2024", 4, "CVE-2024-31756 MarvinTest Hw64 kernel handle leak Candiru driver", "Documents a low-privilege kernel-handle leak in MarvinTest's Hw64.sys hardware-access driver and explains how handles held by communicating processes can be repurposed for elevation. The notice preserves hashes, affected and fixed versions, disclosure dates, and the important lineage to a different Hw64.sys flaw previously exploited by Candiru."],
    ["CVE-2023-52271: Topaz Antifraud PPL Termination", "https://northwave-cybersecurity.com/vulnerability-notice-topaz-antifraud", "Northwave Research", "2024", 4, "CVE-2023-52271 Topaz wsftprm arbitrary kernel calls PPL Defender", "Analyzes Topaz Antifraud's world-accessible wsftprm.sys interface, whose IOCTL path lets an unprivileged caller invoke kernel functions useful for arbitrary process termination. Northwave built a working exploit that kills PPL-protected Microsoft Defender processes and records the affected version, patch, and coordinated disclosure timeline."],
    ["CVE-2025-8061: Lenovo LnvMSRIO Exploit", "https://github.com/spawn451/CVE-2025-8061-Exploit", "spawn451", "2025", 5, "CVE-2025-8061 Lenovo LnvMSRIO physical memory Superfetch VA PA LPE", "Implements the LnvMSRIO.sys physical-memory read and write IOCTLs and builds a Superfetch PFN-based virtual-to-physical translation layer around them. The Delphi proof of concept exposes request structures, driver lifecycle, kernel-memory verification, and the assumptions required to turn a hardware-facing primitive into useful Windows kernel access."],
    ["CVE-2024-30085: exploiting the Cloud Files minifilter", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2024/12-all-i-want-for-christmas-is-a-cve-2024-30085-exploit/", "Cherie-Anne Lee / STAR Labs", "2024", 5, "CVE-2024-30085 cldflt reparse point paged pool WNF ALPC PipeAttribute", "Builds a complete Windows kernel LPE from a cldflt.sys reparse-data heap overflow. Two controlled triggers corrupt WNF state data for disclosure and writes, while ALPC handle tables and PipeAttribute objects convert the pool damage into arbitrary read/write before token privileges are modified and a SYSTEM process is opened."],
    ["CVE-2023-41444: irec.sys Driver Exploitation", "https://blog.dru1d.ninja/windows-driver-exploit-development-irec-sys-a5eb45093945", "Tyler Booth (dru1d)", "2023", 5, "CVE-2023-41444 irec.sys driver LSASS process handle IOCTL exploit", "Starts from a sparse LOLDrivers record, identifies the Binalyze forensic driver, recovers its device and twenty-two IOCTL paths in Ghidra, and exploits a ZwOpenProcess wrapper to obtain an LSASS-readable handle. The article exemplifies the discovery graph used by this catalog and includes a public proof of concept."],
    ["CVE-2023-38817: Echo Anti-Cheat Driver", "https://ioctl.fail/echo-ac-writeup/", "Whanos and kite03", "2023", 5, "CVE-2023-38817 echo anti cheat arbitrary kernel read write token theft", "Audits a commercial anti-cheat scanner whose unrestricted driver interface exposes kernel memory read and write operations, then turns those IOCTLs into EPROCESS token theft and SYSTEM execution. The writeup includes request formats, reverse-engineering evidence, exploit source, disclosure history, and the later certificate and blocklist response."],
    ["CVE-2022-3699: Lenovo Diagnostics Arbitrary R/W", "https://nephosec.com/cve-2022-3699-lenovo-diagnostics-driver-eop-arbitrary-r-w/", "NephoSec", "2022", 5, "CVE-2022-3699 Lenovo diagnostics driver arbitrary kernel read write", "Provides the long-form analysis behind the Lenovo Diagnostics driver flaw, recovering its accessible device, IOCTL contract, and arbitrary kernel read/write capability before demonstrating elevation. It complements the compact exploit repository with the reasoning needed to understand why the primitive exists and how its constraints are handled."],
    ["CVE-2020-17382: Weaponizing MSI Ambient Link", "https://www.matteomalvica.com/blog/2020/09/24/weaponizing-cve-2020-17382/", "Matteo Malvica (uf0)", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-17382 MSI Ambient Link driver kernel exploitation token stealing", "Develops MSI Ambient Link's vulnerable driver from interface and IOCTL reversing through a working local privilege-escalation exploit. The article exposes the buffer contracts, kernel memory primitive, address and structure requirements, and final token manipulation, making it substantially more useful than the short advisory or a precompiled proof of concept."],
    ["Tower of Flaws: Anti-Cheat Driver Audit", "https://vespalec.com/blog/tower-of-flaws/", "Vespalec", "2025", 5, "Tower of Fantasy anti cheat driver vulnerabilities IOCTL CVE exploit", "Performs a broad audit of Tower of Fantasy's anti-cheat driver, mapping its exposed interface and multiple unsafe operations before building concrete demonstrations of impact. The long-form analysis, coordinated disclosure context, and accompanying source make it a strong example of systematically reviewing a large privileged attack surface rather than stopping at one dangerous import."],
    ["CVE-2021-21551: Dell dbutil Driver Flaws", "https://www.sentinelone.com/labs/cve-2021-21551-hundreds-of-millions-of-dell-computers-at-risk-due-to-multiple-bios-driver-privilege-escalation-flaws/", "Kasif Dekel / SentinelLabs", "2021", 5, "CVE-2021-21551 Dell dbutil driver arbitrary read write port IOCTL LPE", "The discoverer's analysis of five flaws in Dell's long-shipped firmware-update driver, including unrestricted device access, attacker-controlled memmove arguments, kernel arbitrary read/write, and privileged port I/O. It connects root cause to token-privilege modification, direct storage access, remediation, and the residual BYOVD risk of signed copies."],
    ["CVE-2018-7502: TwinCAT3 Kernel Drivers", "https://srcincite.io/advisories/src-2018-0007/", "Steven Seeley / Source Incite", "2018", 5, "CVE-2018-7502 Beckhoff TwinCAT3 untrusted pointer IOCTL kernel LPE", "The original advisory for an untrusted-pointer dereference shared by nineteen Beckhoff TwinCAT3 kernel drivers through IOCTL 0x222206. It identifies every affected module, states the low-privilege boundary, links the coordinated vendor fix, and preserves a public proof of concept that can be audited against the concise root-cause description."],
    ["CVE-2019-18845: Viper RGB Driver LPE", "https://www.activecyber.us/activelabs/viper-rgb-driver-local-privilege-escalation-cve-2019-18845", "Active Cyber", "2019", 4, "CVE-2019-18845 Viper RGB Patriot driver local privilege escalation", "Presents the original vulnerability research into the privileged Viper RGB software driver, following its exposed device interface and unsafe request handling to local elevation. The post is retained as a focused vendor-driver case study with disclosure context and technical reproduction rather than merely a CVE database record."],
    ["Gigabyte Driver Elevation-of-Privilege Vulnerabilities", "https://www.secureauth.com/labs/advisories/gigabyte-drivers-elevation-privilege-vulnerabilities", "SecureAuth Labs", "2018", 5, "Gigabyte gdrv driver IOCTL physical memory privilege escalation advisory", "The original coordinated research into Gigabyte utility drivers that exposed privileged kernel and hardware operations to local callers. It documents the affected components, vulnerable interface, security impact, and vendor response, providing the provenance needed to understand why gdrv-family binaries later became recurring BYOVD providers."],
    ["From Admin to Kernel: One Driver, Zero Attention", "https://dor00tkit.github.io/Dor00tkit/posts/from-admin-to-kernel-one-year-one-driver-zero-attention/", "Dor00tkit", "2026", 5, "vulnerable Windows driver reverse engineering kernel primitive BYOVD exploit", "Takes a neglected signed driver from identification through static and dynamic reverse engineering, IOCTL reconstruction, capability validation, and kernel-impact demonstration. The article earns inclusion by documenting the entire research process and practical constraints, not just publishing a hash or claiming that a dangerous function is reachable."],
    ["CVE-2020-0981: One Line Broke the Chrome Sandbox", "https://projectzero.google/2020/04/you-wont-believe-what-this-one-line.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-0981 Windows restricted token Chrome sandbox escape job object", "Traces a one-line Windows kernel change that copied the wrong token parent identifier and broke Chromium's restricted-token assumptions, then constructs the remaining chain around accessible tokens, job limits, child-process policy, and console behavior. It is an exceptional case study in how individually modest platform behaviors compose into a complete browser sandbox escape."],
    ["CVE-2020-0668: Windows Service Tracing EoP", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2020-0668-windows-service-tracing-eop/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-0668 service tracing arbitrary file move oplock LPE", "Dissects a Windows Service Tracing bug that lets an unprivileged user influence privileged file operations, then develops the constraints needed to weaponize it for elevation. The article covers trace configuration, path behavior, reparse points and timing, target selection, and the gap between a vulnerability trigger and a practical SYSTEM chain."],
    ["CVE-2020-0787: BITS Undocumented RPC EoP", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2020-0787-windows-bits-eop/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-0787 BITS RPC arbitrary file move privilege escalation", "Recovers an undocumented BITS RPC function and shows how its privileged file operation can be controlled for local elevation. The analysis combines RPC interface reconstruction, parameter semantics, filesystem experimentation, and exploit design, providing a rare end-to-end example of finding and weaponizing a service RPC bug."],
    ["CVE-2020-0863: DiagTrack Arbitrary File Read", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2020-0863-windows-diagtrack-info-disclo/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-0863 DiagTrack service arbitrary file read RPC disclosure", "Analyzes an arbitrary file-read vulnerability in the Diagnostic Tracking service, mapping the privileged service interface and the data path that returns protected content to a low-privilege caller. It is a valuable confidentiality case study because it explains access context, RPC invocation, and how to demonstrate impact without overstating it as code execution."],
    ["CVE-2020-1170: Windows Defender EoP", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2020-1170-windows-defender-eop/", "itm4n", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-1170 Windows Defender quarantine file operation LPE", "Reverse engineers a Windows Defender elevation flaw involving privileged handling of attacker-influenced files and develops a reproducible exploit chain. The post connects Defender's service workflow, filesystem permissions, timing, and payload placement, making the remediation and residual attack surface easier to evaluate."],
    ["CVE-2022-41099: BitLocker Bypass Analysis", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2022-41099-analysis-bitlocker-drive-encryption-bypass/", "itm4n", "2023", 5, "CVE-2022-41099 BitLocker bypass WinRE patch analysis", "Provides a patch-driven analysis of a BitLocker security-feature bypass affecting the Windows Recovery Environment. It reconstructs the vulnerable boot and recovery behavior, explains the trust assumption that failed, and evaluates Microsoft's fix, offering a strong example of analyzing a platform-security CVE outside the kernel memory-corruption model."],
    ["CVE-2025-59201: NCSI Elevation of Privilege", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2025-59201-ncsi-eop/", "itm4n", "2026", 5, "CVE-2025-59201 NCSI service network connectivity SYSTEM EoP", "A current Windows elevation case study centered on Network Connectivity Status Indicator behavior, developed from patch and component analysis into an explanation of the privileged action an attacker can influence. It documents the service boundary, trigger, exploitation constraints, and fix rather than repeating the MSRC summary."],
    ["CVE-2026-20817: Windows Error Reporting EoP", "https://itm4n.github.io/cve-2026-20817-wersvc-eop/", "itm4n", "2026", 5, "CVE-2026-20817 WerSvc ALPC command execution SYSTEM patch analysis", "Reverse engineers a removed Windows Error Reporting feature that accepted attacker-controlled state through ALPC and could lead to privileged command execution. The article tests the tempting initial explanation against implementation details, reconstructs the real permission failure, and uses the patch to bound affected behavior."],
    ["PrintNightmare Exploitation in 2024", "https://itm4n.github.io/printnightmare-exploitation/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "PrintNightmare CVE-2021-1675 CVE-2021-34527 spooler exploitation patches", "A practical, build-aware guide to the PrintNightmare family that separates the related CVEs, explains Point and Print policy, driver installation paths, authentication and protocol choices, and demonstrates what remains exploitable after successive fixes. It is a much stronger reference than one-shot scripts written against the original vulnerable builds."],
    ["The PrintNightmare Is Not Over Yet", "https://itm4n.github.io/printnightmare-not-over/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "PrintNightmare spooler driver installation bypass Windows patch", "Revisits Print Spooler exploitation after the major PrintNightmare mitigations and identifies remaining behavior that preserves security impact under specific configurations. The research is valuable for its precise version and policy reasoning, showing why a named vulnerability family cannot be considered closed solely from the first patch."],
    ["CVE-2020-17087: cng.sys Pool Overflow", "https://googleprojectzero.github.io/0days-in-the-wild/0day-RCAs/2020/CVE-2020-17087.html", "Mateusz Jurczyk / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "CVE-2020-17087 cng.sys integer truncation pool overflow named pipe", "A concise root-cause analysis of a 16-bit allocation-size truncation in a user-reachable cng.sys IOCTL that produced a large kernel pool overflow. It records the trigger boundary, Chrome sandbox-escape context, named-pipe arbitrary read/write strategy, patch information, variant ideas, structural hardening, and the unusual direct-driver interaction defenders can monitor."],
    ["CVE-2020-1027: CSRSS Heap Buffer Overflow", "https://googleprojectzero.github.io/0days-in-the-wild/0day-RCAs/2020/CVE-2020-1027.html", "Sergei Glazunov / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "CVE-2020-1027 CSRSS ALPC activation context heap overflow CFG ROP", "Documents a CSRSS side-by-side activation-context bug reachable through ALPC, including a complete trigger, the unchecked UNICODE_STRING capacity, controlled heap overflow, object corruption, write-what-where construction, fake loader-list code reuse, CFG transition, and ROP. The analysis also identifies the IPC audit and sandbox attack-surface reductions that could prevent variants."],
    ["CVE-2020-0986: splwow64 Pointer Dereference", "https://googleprojectzero.github.io/0days-in-the-wild/0day-RCAs/2020/CVE-2020-0986.html", "Maddie Stone / Project Zero", "2020", 5, "CVE-2020-0986 splwow64 LPC untrusted pointer arbitrary memcpy sandbox", "Analyzes an in-the-wild splwow64 flaw where attacker-controlled LPC message fields provide the arguments for a privileged memcpy. The RCA includes a minimized trigger, shared-buffer layout, relation to CVE-2019-0880, exploit-chain context, the incomplete pointer-to-offset patch, follow-on CVEs, and concrete variant and detection directions."],
    ["CVE-2020-0938: Windows Type 1 Font Corruption", "https://googleprojectzero.github.io/0days-in-the-wild/0day-RCAs/2020/CVE-2020-0938.html", "Mateusz Jurczyk / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "CVE-2020-0938 ATMFD Type1 font stack corruption BlendDesignPositions", "A detailed analysis of non-contiguous stack writes in the legacy Type 1 Multiple Masters BlendDesignPositions parser, complete with a minimal malicious font and cross-version context. It explains how the bug was chained on older Windows, why fontdrvhost and win32k lockdown reduced value on Windows 10, and where parser-differential and variant research should focus."],
    ["CVE-2020-1020: VToHOrigin Font Write", "https://googleprojectzero.github.io/0days-in-the-wild/0day-RCAs/2020/CVE-2020-1020.html", "Mateusz Jurczyk / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "CVE-2020-1020 Windows font driver Type1 VToHOrigin write primitive", "Covers the companion Windows Type 1 font vulnerability used with CVE-2020-0938 in an in-the-wild chain, separating its controlled write role from the stack-control bug. The RCA preserves trigger and exploit context while evaluating how legacy parser design, duplicated font engines, sandbox policy, and moving font parsing out of the kernel affect the attack surface."],
    ["CVE-2026-29923: pstrip64.sys LPE", "https://github.com/athenasec16/CVE-2026-29923", "AthenaSec", "2026", 5, "CVE-2026-29923 pstrip64 physical memory EPROCESS token LPE", "A full driver-to-SYSTEM case study for PowerStrip's pstrip64.sys: it reverses the IOCTL dispatcher, recovers physical-memory mapping, handles a 64-to-32-bit pointer truncation constraint, scans pool allocations with validation heuristics, accounts for different EPROCESS header layouts, replaces the token, and publishes the tested source and defensive guidance."],
    ["CVE-2025-61155: GameDriverX64 Process Termination", "https://github.com/pollotherunner/CVE-2025-61155", "pollotherunner", "2025", 5, "CVE-2025-61155 GameDriverX64 anticheat IOCTL process termination", "The discoverer's official advisory and C++ proof of concept for an anti-cheat driver that lets any local user terminate arbitrary processes through an exposed IOCTL. The repository includes disclosure material, target details, a demonstration, related threat research, and a direct bridge into the deeper Tower of Flaws analysis."],
    ["CVE-2023-20564: AMD Ryzen Master Physical Memory", "https://github.com/NtGabrielGomes/CVE-2023-20564", "NtGabrielGomes", "2023", 4, "CVE-2023-20564 AMD Ryzen Master physical memory read write", "A source proof of concept for AMD Ryzen Master's insufficiently validated physical-memory read and write IOCTLs. It records request structures, control codes, driver service lifecycle, read-write verification, expected output, affected component, and vendor references, providing a concrete starting point for studying how physical access becomes kernel compromise."],
    ["CVE-2022-42046: wfshbr64 DKOM LPE", "https://github.com/kkent030315/CVE-2022-42046", "kkent030315 and DoranekoSystems", "2022", 5, "CVE-2022-42046 wfshbr64 DKOM EPROCESS protection flags bypass", "A well-documented proof of concept for a signed driver that performs caller-controlled bitwise operations at arbitrary EPROCESS offsets. The repository shows manipulation of Protection and SignatureLevel, analyzes unsafe IRP handling, records the vendor's attempted validation, and demonstrates how byte-shifted operations bypassed that mitigation."],
    ["CVE-2022-3699: Lenovo Diagnostics Driver", "https://github.com/alfarom256/CVE-2022-3699", "Alvaro Munoz", "2022", 4, "CVE-2022-3699 Lenovo diagnostics driver arbitrary read write LPE", "A focused exploit repository for the Lenovo Diagnostics driver elevation-of-privilege vulnerability, exposing the arbitrary kernel read/write path and the code used to turn it into elevation. It is useful as a compact companion to vendor and CVE records because the actual request structures and exploit implementation are preserved."],
    ["CVE-2018-19320: Gigabyte gdrv.sys LPE", "https://github.com/hmnthabit/CVE-2018-19320-LPE", "hmnthabit", "2021", 4, "CVE-2018-19320 Gigabyte gdrv kernel memory write SYSTEM", "A working local privilege-escalation exploit for Gigabyte's gdrv.sys, which exposes low-level memory allocation and write capabilities to insufficiently privileged callers. The repository records affected vendor utilities, the tested Windows build, source, demonstration, and original SecureAuth advisory for cross-checking the vulnerability."],
    ["CVE-2026-36425: OPSWAT ardrv.sys", "https://github.com/redteamfortress/CVE-2026-36425", "Jehad Abudagga / Red Team Fortress", "2026", 5, "CVE-2026-36425 OPSWAT ardrv process termination registry file IO", "The coordinated advisory for an AppRemover driver whose world-accessible device exposes unauthenticated process termination through memory corruption, job objects, and ZwTerminateProcess. It also documents adjacent registry-write, port-I/O, and forced-file-deletion handlers, affected versions, disclosure timeline, and concrete blocklisting and monitoring recommendations."],
    ["PrintDemon: CVE-2020-1048 and More", "https://windows-internals.com/printdemon-cve-2020-1048/", "Alex Ionescu and Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "PrintDemon CVE-2020-1048 spooler LPE persistence arbitrary file write", "A comprehensive investigation of Print Spooler file-writing behavior that produced privilege escalation, persistence, and stealth techniques as well as follow-on fixes. It combines service internals, printer configuration, impersonation, filesystem effects, disclosure timeline, and patch analysis, making it a model multi-impact Windows case study."],
    ["Faxing Your Way to SYSTEM", "https://windows-internals.com/faxing-your-way-to-system/", "Alex Ionescu and Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "Windows Fax service SYSTEM privilege escalation DLL loading", "Analyzes a Windows Fax service attack path from service configuration and RPC-accessible behavior through controlled file placement and privileged code loading. The post's strength is its complete treatment of prerequisites, service lifecycle, and remediation, showing how a legacy Windows component can expose a modern local escalation chain without kernel memory corruption."],
    ["CVE-2019-1458: Win32k uninitialized variable", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/p/rca-cve-2019-1458.html", "Maddie Stone / Project Zero", "2020", 5, "CVE-2019-1458 win32k uninitialized variable bitmap KASLR arbitrary write", "A structured root-cause analysis of an in-the-wild Win32k flaw that records the vulnerable state transition, limited write primitive, public proof of concept, exploit strategy, applicable mitigations, and promising variant-analysis directions. Its explicit separation of root cause, exploitation, structural improvements, and detection makes it an excellent template for studying any Windows zero-day."],
    ["The Windows Registry Adventure: an attack surface review", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2024/04/the-windows-registry-adventure-1-registry.html", "Mateusz Jurczyk / Project Zero", "2024", 5, "Windows kernel registry hive fuzzing memory corruption attack surface CVE", "The opening installment of a deep audit of the Windows registry implementation, built from public symbols, reverse engineering, coverage-guided kernel fuzzing, and more than twenty reported issues. It maps the duplicated parser and hive code across boot, kernel, offline, and user-mode components before later exploitation work, giving researchers a rigorous way to bound a complex attack surface."],
    ["CVE-2025-8061: exploiting a Lenovo driver", "https://blog.quarkslab.com/exploiting-lenovo-driver-cve-2025-8061.html", "Quarkslab", "2025", 5, "Lenovo driver LPE reverse engineering CVE-2025-8061", "Follows a vulnerable Lenovo driver from interface reverse engineering through primitive discovery to a working local privilege-escalation chain. The end-to-end methodology makes it useful well beyond this single CVE."],
    ["eneio64.sys physical-memory R/W", "https://xacone.github.io/eneio-driver.html", "xacone", "2023", 5, "CVE-2020-12446 BYOVD HVCI physical memory", "Starts from exposed physical-memory access in eneio64.sys and builds the translation machinery required for useful virtual kernel reads and writes. It also covers HVCI and driver-blocklist constraints that simplified BYOVD writeups often omit."],
    ["AOMEI amwrtdrv raw-disk LPE", "https://afflicted.sh/blog/posts/amwrtdrv-aomei-lpe.html", "afflicted.sh", "2026", 5, "raw disk GPT FAT12 UEFI pre-kernel LPE", "Turns ordinary-user raw-disk access into a pre-kernel execution chain by planting a FAT12 image and redirecting a GPT entry. The post is exceptional for showing how a seemingly narrow driver permission error crosses storage, firmware, and boot trust boundaries."],
    ["SignalRGB: standard user to SYSTEM", "https://afflicted.sh/blog/posts/signalrgb-service-lpe.html", "afflicted.sh", "2026", 4, "service ACL writable binary LocalSystem LPE", "Analyzes a LocalSystem auto-start service whose executable resides in a user-writable directory. It also explains practical replacement and restart constraints, turning a familiar service-permission bug into a complete operational case study."],
    ["SAS CTF Windows 7 challenge explained", "https://securelist.com/sas-ctf-windows-7-challenge-explained/114180/", "Kaspersky Securelist", "2024", 4, "kernel shellcode persistence APT Windows 7 CTF", "Connects a Windows 7 CTF challenge to a kernel-shellcode persistence technique observed in APT activity. The article is valuable for seeing how a real threat technique can be distilled into a reverse-engineering and exploitation exercise."],
    ["CVE-2026-21222: information disclosure", "https://windowsforum.com/threads/cve-2026-21222-windows-kernel-information-disclosure-risk-and-mitigation.400816/", "WindowsForum", "2026", 2, "Windows kernel information disclosure mitigation", "A secondary overview of the reported Windows kernel information-disclosure issue and basic mitigation guidance. Use it as a lead rather than an authoritative technical reference, then confirm details in Microsoft advisories and original research when available."],
    ["CVE-2024-26170: CimFS from crash discovery to SYSTEM", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2025/03-cimfs-crashing-in-memory-finding-system-kernel-edition/", "Chen Le Qi / STAR Labs", "2025", 5, "CVE-2024-26170 cimfs filesystem fuzzing OOB read Windows kernel LPE", "Documents the complete research lifecycle for a previously unexplored Windows 11 filesystem driver: bypassing the control-device path check, reconstructing the CIM mount format, building a mutation fuzzer, grouping seven crash classes, and exploiting an out-of-bounds read reached through a hard-link alternate data stream. It is unusually strong because discovery engineering and final SYSTEM exploitation receive equal depth."],
    ["CVE-2023-36802 under modern exploitation constraints", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2026/06-old-bug-harder-rules-exploiting-cve-2023-36802-without-the-usual-shortcuts/", "Nguyễn Đức Hiếu / STAR Labs", "2026", 5, "CVE-2023-36802 mskssrv type confusion kernel pool arbitrary decrement read write", "Rebuilds exploitation of the mskssrv.sys rendezvous-object type confusion without NtQuery-based kernel pointer disclosures or KTHREAD PreviousMode abuse. Patch diffing and trigger reconstruction lead into leak, DWORD write, and arbitrary-decrement primitives, followed by pool-list corruption, arbitrary read/write, EPROCESS discovery, and SYSTEM on the constrained target."],
    ["CVE-2022-24547: CastSrv cross-session elevation", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2024/12-behind-the-scenes-understanding-cve-2022-24547/", "Đào Tuấn Linh / STAR Labs", "2024", 4, "CVE-2022-24547 CastSrv COM session moniker symbolic link DACL LPE", "Explains how the interactive-user CastServer COM class can be activated in another logged-on user's session and induced to create a permissive PlayToReceiver directory without defending against symbolic-link redirection. The reproduction maps CLSID, interface methods, session-moniker activation, folder creation, DACL behavior, exploit conditions, and detection guidance."],
    ["CVE-2024-26230: Windows Telephony Service UAF", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2025/01-cve-2024-26230-windows-telephony-service-its-got-some-call-ing-issues-elevation-of-privilege/", "Đào Tuấn Linh / STAR Labs", "2025", 5, "CVE-2024-26230 TapiSrv RPC use after free GOLD object heap LPE", "Reverse engineers a TapiSrv RPC lifetime bug in which FreeDialogInstance releases a GOLD object while a context handle retains the dangling pointer, and TUISPIDLLCallBack later invokes its virtual function. The article develops same-process heap replacement primitives, service triggering, exploit reproduction, and the final Network Service-to-SYSTEM path while separating a related priority-list bug."],
    ["CVE-2025-54098: Hyper-V vhdmp.sys arbitrary file write", "https://starlabs.sg/advisories/25/25-54098/", "Chen Le Qi / STAR Labs", "2025", 5, "CVE-2025-54098 Hyper-V vhdmp arbitrary file write OBJ_FORCE_ACCESS_CHECK LPE", "Analyzes a Hyper-V virtual-disk kernel path that opens an attacker-selected file through a Zw routine without OBJ_FORCE_ACCESS_CHECK, so the operation bypasses the caller token's normal filesystem authorization. The advisory preserves the affected component, privileged write behavior, root access-check mistake, elevation impact, patch timeline, and enough kernel semantics to recognize the same bug pattern elsewhere."],
  ]},
  { id: "tools", kicker: "Keep beside the debugger", title: "Tools & Technical References", items: [
    ["qiomem Physical-Memory PoC", "https://github.com/valium007/qiomem", "Valium", "2026", 5, "qiomem.sys physical memory read write PnP driver exploit source", "The source artifact accompanying the Toshiba qiomem.sys analysis, including driver-interface discovery, software-device creation for PnP loading, packed IOCTL requests, and physical-memory access code. It allows the article's unusual loading and HVCI claims to be reviewed directly rather than inferred from screenshots."],
    ["Echo Anti-Cheat Driver PoC", "https://github.com/kite03/echoac-poc", "kite03", "2023", 5, "CVE-2023-38817 echo_driver arbitrary kernel read write exploit", "The public implementation for CVE-2023-38817, preserving the Echo driver's request structures, initialization call, kernel read/write wrappers, EPROCESS traversal, and token-copy escalation. It is the executable companion to the long-form disclosure and a compact lab target for auditing driver exploit assumptions."],
    ["TowerOfFlaws", "https://github.com/svespalec/TowerOfFlaws", "Vespalec", "2025", 5, "Tower of Fantasy anti cheat vulnerable driver exploit PoC source", "The code and research artifacts behind the Tower of Flaws anti-cheat driver audit, organized so individual vulnerable operations and proof-of-concept paths can be inspected alongside the article. The repository preserves implementation detail that would otherwise be lost in screenshots and supports repeatable lab validation."],
    ["KslDump", "https://github.com/andreisss/KslDump", "andreisss", "Living", 4, "BYOVD Kaspersky driver LSASS dump process memory kernel tool", "A focused vulnerable-driver-assisted utility for obtaining protected process memory through a Kaspersky driver path, with source that exposes the user-mode orchestration and device interaction. It is useful for comparing an operational credential-access tool with the underlying driver primitive and its required system state."],
    ["KslKatz", "https://github.com/vergamota/KslKatz", "vergamota", "Living", 4, "Kaspersky driver BYOVD LSASS PPL credential dumping source", "A source-level implementation that combines a Kaspersky driver capability with LSASS access and credential-extraction workflow. The repository belongs in the technical-reference table because it shows how device loading, IOCTL use, protection bypass, and post-access tooling are assembled, while requiring isolated lab handling."],
    ["Debugging Protected Processes", "https://itm4n.github.io/debugging-protected-processes/", "itm4n", "2022", 5, "WinDbg protected process PPL debugging kernel debugger methodology", "Shows how to investigate protected and protected-light processes when ordinary user-mode debugging is blocked, using kernel debugging and carefully selected process state. The workflow is broadly reusable for validating PPL research because it explains debugger context, breakpoints, symbols, and the limitations that can otherwise produce misleading observations."],
    ["A Deep Dive into TPM-Based BitLocker", "https://itm4n.github.io/tpm-based-bitlocker/", "itm4n", "2023", 5, "BitLocker TPM PCR protectors measured boot Windows internals", "Explains TPM-backed BitLocker from the key hierarchy and protectors through PCR-bound sealing, measured boot, recovery behavior, and the Windows components that orchestrate unlock. It supplies the architectural context needed to assess BitLocker bypass claims and separates cryptographic guarantees from configuration and recovery-path weaknesses."],
    ["Extracting PEAP Credentials from Wired Connections", "https://itm4n.github.io/peap-credentials-wired-connections/", "itm4n", "2024", 5, "PEAP 802.1X Windows wired credentials DPAPI registry extraction", "Investigates how Windows stores and retrieves credentials for wired PEAP and 802.1X profiles, tracing configuration artifacts, protected data, relevant services, and decryption context. The post is a useful forensic and credential-storage reference because it identifies the exact scope and prerequisites instead of implying that every enterprise network secret is directly recoverable."],
    ["Auditing Symantec ACC with PrivescCheck", "https://itm4n.github.io/checking-symantec-application-control-config-with-privesccheck/", "itm4n", "2025", 4, "Symantec Application Control PrivescCheck policy audit Windows", "Adds Symantec Application Control configuration checks to PrivescCheck and explains how the relevant policy state affects local privilege-escalation opportunities. The article connects collection code to the control's security meaning, making it useful both for extending a native assessment tool and for interpreting the resulting findings responsibly."],
    ["Offline Extraction of Symantec ACC Configuration", "https://itm4n.github.io/offline-extraction-symantec-application-control-config/", "itm4n", "2025", 4, "Symantec Application Control offline registry policy extraction forensics", "Develops an offline method for extracting Symantec Application Control configuration from Windows artifacts when the protected endpoint cannot be queried normally. It documents storage locations, parsing and decoding steps, and validation, providing a reproducible forensic companion to the live PrivescCheck assessment workflow."],
    ["BitLocker's Little Secrets: the Undocumented FVE API", "https://itm4n.github.io/bitlocker-little-secrets-the-undocumented-fve-api/", "itm4n", "2026", 5, "BitLocker FVE API undocumented RPC reverse engineering volume encryption", "Reverse engineers the undocumented Full Volume Encryption API used by Windows to manage BitLocker, recovering interfaces, data structures, and operational semantics from native components. It is a high-value reference for researchers building precise BitLocker experiments because it replaces fragile command-line automation with an understanding of the underlying management boundary."],
    ["POPKORN Artifact", "https://github.com/ucsb-seclab/popkorn-artifact", "UCSB SecLab", "2022", 5, "Windows driver symbolic execution angr vulnerability discovery dataset", "The reproducibility package for POPKORN: Popping Windows Kernel Drivers at Scale, containing the evaluated driver corpus, angr-based analysis, Docker environment, expected results, and scripts for single-target or bulk runs. It is a strong research reference because findings can be reproduced and the analysis can be applied to a new driver dataset."],
    ["Elastic Protections Artifacts", "https://github.com/elastic/protections-artifacts", "Elastic Security", "Living", 5, "Windows endpoint detection EQL YARA ransomware behavior rules", "Elastic's published endpoint protection logic, including behavior rules, YARA signatures, and ransomware artifacts generated from the same research behind its public threat reports. It is a useful primary defensive reference for testing whether a driver, loader, or evasion technique creates observable behavior covered by production-oriented rules."],
    ["VoidSec Exploit Development Archive", "https://github.com/VoidSec/Exploit-Development", "VoidSec", "Living", 5, "Windows exploits proof of concept drivers CVE exploit development", "A maintained archive of weaponized exploits and proof-of-concept code tied to VoidSec's vulnerability research. The repository complements the author's long-form driver methodology and case studies by preserving buildable artifacts that can be reviewed against the narrative and vendor fixes."],
    ["WindowsKernelVuln", "https://github.com/zeze-zeze/WindowsKernelVuln", "zeze-zeze", "Living", 4, "Windows kernel vulnerability exploitation examples drivers training", "A Windows kernel vulnerability research collection with code and notes spanning driver bugs and exploitation techniques. It is most useful as a lab corpus for comparing implementation patterns and locating original references; individual samples should still be matched to their target build and advisory before use."],
    ["Secure Kernel Research with LiveCloudKd", "https://windows-internals.com/secure-kernel-research-with-livecloudkd/", "Yarden Shafir", "2024", 5, "LiveCloudKd secure kernel VTL1 debugging memory acquisition", "A practical workflow for using LiveCloudKd to inspect the Secure Kernel and VTL1 state that ordinary kernel debugging cannot directly expose. It explains the acquisition model, symbol use, and analysis boundaries, making the article and tool valuable for validating VBS, KDP, and HyperGuard research against a live system."],
    ["An Exercise in Dynamic Analysis", "https://windows-internals.com/an-exercise-in-dynamic-analysis/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "WinDbg dynamic analysis Windows kernel reverse engineering methodology", "A methodology-focused exercise in answering Windows internals questions through live debugging and controlled experiments. Rather than presenting a static conclusion, it demonstrates breakpoint selection, state inspection, hypothesis refinement, and verification, which makes it a reusable guide for researching undocumented kernel behavior safely."],
    ["Troubleshooting a System Crash", "https://windows-internals.com/troubleshooting-a-system-crash/", "Yarden Shafir", "2024", 4, "Windows crash dump WinDbg bugcheck root cause driver debugging", "Walks through a real Windows crash investigation using dump analysis, stack and object inspection, and progressive hypothesis testing. It belongs in the reference table because it teaches how to establish causality from debugger evidence instead of stopping at the blamed module name reported by automated crash tools."],
    ["I/O Rings: When One I/O Operation Is Not Enough", "https://windows-internals.com/i-o-rings-when-one-i-o-operation-is-not-enough/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "Windows I/O rings internals asynchronous I/O API structures", "The original deep introduction to Windows I/O rings, reconstructing the user-mode API, submission and completion queues, registered resources, and kernel implementation. It is the conceptual reference needed before reading later exploitation primitives, because it explains the legitimate object lifecycle and invariants that corruption violates."],
    ["One Year to I/O Ring: What Changed?", "https://windows-internals.com/one-year-to-i-o-ring-what-changed/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "Windows I/O rings version changes API kernel structures", "Compares the I/O ring implementation across a year of Windows releases, documenting API growth, structure changes, registration behavior, and security-relevant differences. The version-aware analysis prevents researchers from applying an early proof of concept blindly to newer builds and demonstrates how to maintain undocumented internals research over time."],
    ["IoRing vs io_uring", "https://windows-internals.com/ioring-vs-io_uring-a-comparison-of-windows-and-linux-implementations/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 4, "Windows IoRing Linux io_uring architecture comparison asynchronous I/O", "A careful architectural comparison of Windows I/O rings and Linux io_uring, covering queue ownership, registration, operation submission, completion, and kernel trust boundaries. The cross-platform framing clarifies which security assumptions are inherent to ring-based asynchronous I/O and which are specific implementation choices in Windows."],
    ["WinAFL", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/winafl", "Google Project Zero", "Living", 5, "Windows coverage guided fuzzing DynamoRIO TinyInst persistent mode", "The established AFL-derived coverage-guided fuzzer for Windows binaries, with DynamoRIO and TinyInst instrumentation, persistent and in-app modes, crash minimization, and extensive real-world vulnerability credits. Its documentation and harness examples make it a primary starting point for reproducible user-mode fuzzing rather than a generic link collection."],
    ["Sandbox Attack Surface Analysis Tools", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/sandbox-attacksurface-analysis-tools", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "Living", 5, "Windows sandbox attack surface COM RPC named pipes object manager tokens", "A maintained suite for enumerating and analyzing Windows sandbox attack surface across object-manager namespaces, processes, tokens, services, RPC, COM, network endpoints, and accessible resources. The tools embody the methodology behind several Project Zero sandbox-escape investigations and are especially useful for comparing effective policy with the boundary a product claims to enforce."],
    ["TinyInst", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/TinyInst", "Google Project Zero", "Living", 5, "dynamic instrumentation coverage Windows fuzzing debugger harness", "A lightweight dynamic instrumentation library used for coverage collection and fuzzing on Windows and other platforms, with debugger-based control and a deliberately smaller architecture than full binary-instrumentation frameworks. It is the relevant primary reference when WinAFL or Jackalope uses TinyInst-backed coverage and when a researcher needs to understand instrumentation behavior rather than treat it as a black box."],
    ["Jackalope", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/Jackalope", "Ivan Fratric / Project Zero", "Living", 5, "binary coverage guided fuzzer Windows TinyInst mutators persistent", "A modern binary coverage-guided fuzzer designed around TinyInst, supporting Windows targets, custom mutators, persistent execution, corpus management, and distributed workflows. The repository includes the actual engine and operational documentation, making it a high-signal alternative for targets that do not fit source-based fuzzing or WinAFL's harness model."],
    ["PerfView and TraceEvent", "https://github.com/microsoft/perfview", "Microsoft", "Living", 5, "ETW TraceEvent ETL stacks kernel providers performance diagnostics", "Microsoft's open-source ETW collection and analysis stack, including the TraceEvent library used to create sessions, enable kernel and user providers, decode events, capture stacks, and process ETL data programmatically. It is a primary implementation reference for researchers who need to verify telemetry behavior rather than infer it from an EDR interface."],
    ["Awesome Windows CTF", "https://zaratec.io/awesome-windows-ctf/", "zaratec", "Living", 5, "Windows CTF pwn challenges writeups kernel heap usermode Hyper-V", "A Windows-specific CTF index that separates challenges by competition, target layer, and exploitation topic, with direct links to artifacts and writeups. It is now used as a discovery graph for this catalog; individual challenges are promoted only after their technical content is independently checked."],
    ["Windows Malware Analysis Training, Volume 1", "https://github.com/hasherezade/malware_training_vol1", "Hasherezade", "Living", 5, "malware analysis PE processes WoW64 shellcode loaders hooking exercises", "A freely licensed Windows malware-analysis curriculum with slides and hands-on exercises covering PE files, processes, WoW64, shellcode, loaders, injection, hooking, persistence, and evasion. It is unusually valuable because concepts are paired with code and analysis tasks rather than presented as a tool checklist."],
    ["Driver Buddy Reloaded", "https://github.com/VoidSec/DriverBuddyReloaded", "VoidSec", "Living", 5, "IDA plugin Windows driver IOCTL WDM WDF reverse engineering", "An IDA Pro plugin that labels WDM/WDF structures, finds dispatch routines and device names, decodes IOCTLs, identifies pool tags, and flags dangerous functions or opcodes. It accelerates triage without hiding the analysis steps, which makes it suitable for both learning and repeated driver audits."],
    ["vulnerable-drivers", "https://github.com/KeServiceDescriptorTable/vulnerable-drivers", "KeServiceDescriptorTable", "Living", 4, "vulnerable Windows drivers samples research corpus", "A broad driver corpus linked from many recent LOLDrivers records and intended for vulnerability research. Its value is coverage and sample availability; provenance and exploitability still need to be established from each driver's advisory, issue, or independent reversing work."],
    ["prefetch-tool", "https://github.com/exploits-forsale/prefetch-tool", "exploits.forsale", "2024", 5, "KASLR prefetch side channel assembly timing", "A focused proof of concept for resolving the Windows kernel base through prefetch timing. Read the assembly-level timing loop alongside the 24H2 exploit research to connect the side-channel theory with hardware-specific reliability limits."],
    ["Vergilius Project", "https://www.vergiliusproject.com/", "Vergilius", "Living", 5, "Windows kernel structures symbols offsets", "A searchable catalog of tens of thousands of undocumented Windows kernel structures across builds and architectures. It is invaluable for quickly comparing layouts, but build-specific offsets should still be validated against symbols and the target binary."],
    ["System Informer: ntexapi.h", "https://github.com/winsiderss/systeminformer/blob/master/phnt/include/ntexapi.h", "System Informer / phnt", "Living", 5, "NtQuerySystemInformation SYSTEM_INFORMATION_CLASS Native API", "The phnt declarations for Native system-information APIs and the SYSTEM_INFORMATION_CLASS family. Use it for accurate enum values and structure layouts missing from the public SDK, while remembering these interfaces can change between Windows builds."],
    ["System Informer: ntpsapi.h", "https://github.com/winsiderss/systeminformer/blob/master/phnt/include/ntpsapi.h", "System Informer / phnt", "Living", 5, "Native process thread APIs information classes", "The phnt process-and-thread header covering Native process, thread, job, and related information classes. It is the quickest source for checking structures expected by NtQueryInformationProcess and NtQueryInformationThread before confirming behavior in symbols or disassembly."],
    ["NtDoc: PROCESSINFOCLASS", "https://ntdoc.m417z.com/processinfoclass", "NtDoc", "Living", 5, "PROCESSINFOCLASS NtQueryInformationProcess documentation", "A browsable, cross-linked reference for process information classes used by NtQueryInformationProcess and NtSetInformationProcess. It summarizes buffer types, access requirements, and version notes, making it a convenient companion to phnt headers."],
    ["IoRingReadWritePrimitive", "https://github.com/yardenshafir/IoRingReadWritePrimitive", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "Windows 11 I/O rings kernel read write primitive", "Shows how a limited kernel write or increment can be transformed into a full read/write primitive through Windows I/O rings. The small implementation is an excellent post-exploitation reference for understanding the user/kernel objects and corruption required by the technique."],
    ["DrvEye", "https://github.com/0xDbgMan/DrvEye", "0xDbgMan", "2026", 4, "driver triage IOCTL symlink certificates BYOVD", "Automates static triage of Windows drivers by surfacing IOCTLs, symbolic links, certificates, imports, and other exploitation-relevant features. Its BYOVD-oriented workflow is useful for prioritization, but findings still require manual reverse engineering and validation."],
    ["Windows Kernel Exploits archive", "https://github.com/SecWiki/windows-kernel-exploits", "SecWiki", "Living", 4, "Windows kernel CVE privilege escalation exploit archive", "A large historical archive of public Windows kernel privilege-escalation exploits organized by vulnerability and platform. It is useful for comparative study and lab reproduction, though many samples target obsolete builds and should never be assumed safe or production-ready."],
    ["awesome-fuzzing", "https://github.com/secfigo/awesome-fuzzing", "secfigo", "Living", 4, "fuzzing root cause analysis exploit development resources", "A broad curated index covering fuzzers, papers, courses, root-cause analysis, and exploit development. Use it to choose a domain-specific starting point rather than reading linearly, and check linked projects for current maintenance status."],
    ["vss-fr2system", "https://github.com/sailay1996/vss-fr2system", "sailay1996", "2026", 3, "VSS file read SYSTEM Windows technique", "A compact research repository exploring a Windows VSS/file-read-to-SYSTEM path. The upstream description is intentionally sparse, so treat the code as a lab artifact to reverse engineer and validate rather than as documented guidance."],
  ]},
] as const;
const total = groups.reduce((sum, group) => sum + group.items.length, 0);
const stars = (rating: number) => `${"★".repeat(rating)}${"☆".repeat(5 - rating)}`;
---

<div class="research-index" data-research-index>
  <div class="research-index__search">
    <label for="research-search">Search the index</label>
    <input id="research-search" type="search" placeholder="Try: KASLR, EDR, pool, CVE, I/O rings..." autocomplete="off" data-research-search />
    <p data-research-status aria-live="polite">{researchers.length} researchers and {total} resources</p>
  </div>
  <aside class="research-index__rubric" aria-label="Reading priority rubric">
    <strong>Reading priority</strong>
    <span><b>★★★★★</b> foundational / must-read</span><span><b>★★★★☆</b> strong practical depth</span><span><b>★★★☆☆</b> useful or specialized</span><span><b>★★☆☆☆</b> supplemental / secondary</span>
  </aside>
  <nav class="research-index__jump" aria-label="Jump to a research area">
    <a href="#researchers-heading">Researchers</a>
    {groups.map((group) => <a href={`#${group.id}-heading`}>{group.title}</a>)}
  </nav>
  <section data-index-group aria-labelledby="researchers-heading">
    <div class="research-index__heading"><div><p class="research-index__kicker">People to follow</p><h2 id="researchers-heading">Researchers &amp; Blogs</h2></div><span>{researchers.length} entries</span></div>
    <div class="research-index__table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Researcher</th><th>Blog</th><th>Primary focus</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      {researchers.map(([name, site, url, profile, focus]) => <tr data-index-row data-kind="researcher" data-searchable={`${name} ${site} ${focus}`}><td><a href={profile} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">{name}</a></td><td><a href={url} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">{site}</a></td><td>{focus}</td></tr>)}
    </tbody></table></div><p class="research-index__none" data-group-empty hidden>No matching researchers.</p>
  </section>
  {groups.map((group) => <section id={`${group.id}-section`} data-index-group aria-labelledby={`${group.id}-heading`}>
    <div class="research-index__heading"><div><p class="research-index__kicker">{group.kicker}</p><h2 id={`${group.id}-heading`}>{group.title}</h2></div><span>{group.items.length} entries</span></div>
    <div class="research-index__table-wrap"><table class="resource-table"><thead><tr><th>Resource</th><th>Year</th><th>Priority</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      {group.items.map(([title, url, source, year, rating, tags, note]) => <tr data-index-row data-kind="resource" data-searchable={`${title} ${source} ${year} ${tags} ${note}`}><td><a href={url} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">{title}</a><small>{source}</small></td><td><span class="research-index__year">{year}</span></td><td><span class="research-index__stars" title={`${rating} out of 5 reading priority`} aria-label={`${rating} out of 5 reading priority`}>{stars(rating)}</span></td><td>{note}</td></tr>)}
    </tbody></table></div><p class="research-index__none" data-group-empty hidden>No matching resources in this section.</p>
  </section>)}
</div>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-research-index]").forEach((root) => {
    const input = root.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>("[data-research-search]");
    const status = root.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-research-status]");
    const sections = [...root.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-index-group]")];
    input?.addEventListener("input", () => {
      const query = input.value.trim().toLowerCase(); let researchers = 0; let resources = 0;
      sections.forEach((section) => { let visible = 0; section.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-index-row]").forEach((row) => { const match = (row.dataset.searchable ?? "").toLowerCase().includes(query); row.hidden = !match; if (match) { visible++; row.dataset.kind === "researcher" ? researchers++ : resources++; } }); const empty = section.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-group-empty]"); if (empty) empty.hidden = visible !== 0; });
      if (status) status.textContent = `${researchers} researchers and ${resources} resources`;
    });
  });
</script>

<style>
  .research-index{display:grid;gap:var(--space-2xl);margin-top:var(--space-xl)}.research-index__search{position:sticky;top:4.75rem;z-index:5;display:grid;grid-template-columns:auto minmax(16rem,1fr) auto;align-items:center;gap:var(--space-md);padding:var(--space-md);border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-xl);background:color-mix(in srgb,var(--color-bg-primary) 94%,transparent);box-shadow:var(--shadow-md);backdrop-filter:blur(12px)}.research-index__search label{font-weight:700}.research-index__search input{width:100%;min-height:2.75rem;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-lg);background:var(--color-bg-primary);color:var(--color-text-primary);padding:.65rem .85rem;font:inherit}.research-index__search p{margin:0;color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-size:.8125rem;white-space:nowrap}.research-index__rubric{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:.65rem 1.25rem;padding:var(--space-md);border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-xl);background:var(--color-bg-secondary);font-size:.82rem}.research-index__rubric strong{width:100%}.research-index__rubric b,.research-index__stars{color:#d69e2e;letter-spacing:.04em}.research-index__jump{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:.5rem;margin-top:calc(var(--space-xl)*-1)}.research-index__jump a{border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-full);background:var(--color-bg-secondary);padding:.4rem .7rem;font-size:.78rem;text-decoration:none}.research-index__jump a:hover{border-color:var(--color-text-secondary)}.research-index section{display:grid;gap:var(--space-md);scroll-margin-top:6rem}.research-index__heading{display:flex;align-items:end;justify-content:space-between;gap:var(--space-md)}.research-index__heading h2,.research-index__kicker{margin:0}.research-index__kicker{color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:.72rem;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase}.research-index__heading>span{color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-size:.8125rem}.research-index__table-wrap{overflow-x:auto;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-xl)}.research-index table{width:100%;min-width:54rem;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:.9rem}.research-index .resource-table{min-width:68rem}.research-index th,.research-index td{padding:.9rem 1rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);text-align:left;vertical-align:top}.research-index th{background:var(--color-bg-secondary);color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-size:.75rem;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase}.research-index tbody tr:last-child td{border-bottom:0}.research-index tbody tr:hover{background:var(--color-bg-secondary)}.research-index td:first-child{width:25%;font-weight:650}.resource-table td:nth-child(2){width:7%}.resource-table td:nth-child(3){width:12%;white-space:nowrap}.research-index a{color:var(--color-text-primary);text-underline-offset:.2rem}.research-index small{display:block;margin-top:.25rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-weight:400}.research-index__year{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:.78rem}.research-index__none{margin:0;padding:var(--space-lg);border:1px dashed var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-lg);color:var(--color-text-secondary);text-align:center}[data-index-row][hidden]{display:none}@media(max-width:48rem){.research-index__search{position:static;grid-template-columns:1fr}.research-index__search p{white-space:normal}}
</style>
